<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0796 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-MERCEDES-HNS &LR;      01-09 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MERCEDES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
It's no longer lonely at top of Mercedes
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KAPALUA, Hawaii _ Everybody who is spellbound by Tiger Woods'
amazing run of success is convinced that he absolutely must win the
Mercedes Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Or Els.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, the laid-back South African who said earlier in this
tournament that he's not in Woods' league, certainly isn't playing
like he's content to stay in Triple-A. He charged into the big
leagues on Saturday and is in position to knock Woods out of the
cleanup spot, at least in terms of cleaning up on the biggest
paycheck of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Els shot 6-under-par 67 to tie Woods for the lead at the PGA
Tour's season-opening event. For the second day in a row, Els did
not have a bogey. And unlike Friday, he didn't have a double-bogey
either. He started the day four strokes behind Woods, but they both
ended at 11-under-par 208 going into the final round after Woods
managed only a 2-under 71 that was capped by an eagle. David Duval
matched Els' 67 and trails the leaders by four shots.
</P>
<P>
   That threesome represents three of the top five players in golf,
according to the official world rankings, which should set up a
gripping finale today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it more competitive,'' said Woods. ``That's what you
have to enjoy _ getting out there and battling against the best
players. Win or lose, it's going to be a lot of fun to try to come
out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, trying to be the first player since 1953 to win five
consecutive starts on the PGA Tour, won't do so without a fight
from Els. And maybe Duval, too.
</P>
<P>
   As the Plantation Course at Kapalua played three shots easier
than it had Friday, and more than four strokes more forgiving than
in the first round, Woods was one of the few players in the 30-man
field who couldn't take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Els, who made four birdies in a row on the front nine, had said
Friday that he wasn't sure anybody could stay with Woods unless the
world's top-ranked player started making some mistakes. On
Saturday, Woods made three bogeys in a nine-hole stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did make a couple of mistakes,'' Els said. ``As it turned
out, I played more consistently than he did on this day. It's nice
to know that I actually got him for one round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I beat him was at the Nissan (Los Angeles Open)
last year. I've played 25 tournaments since then and I've never
beaten him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anybody else has, either.
</P>
<P>
   But even though he had problems, Woods salvaged what could have
been a much worse round when he eagled the 18th, hitting a 3-iron
from 290 yards down the hill and 30 feet past the pin, then making
the putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really got anything going,'' Woods said. ``I wasn't
really playing all that well and Ernie hit a lot of good shots.
That's the way it is sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I was 2-under par, it wasn't a solid 2-under par.
I was kind of scraping it around.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then to end on three good, solid shots leaves a better
taste in your mouth going into the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason for Woods not to be confident when today's
final round commences. The last 11 times he has been in the lead or
tied for the lead after 54 holes, he has won the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will that have any effect on it? No,'' he said. ``It never
does, because you have to go out there and execute the golf shots
and play the correct way.''
</P>
<P>
   Els clearly did that Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Woods, who looked downright pedestrian after making
birdie on two of the first five holes. He had a five-stroke
advantage at one point, but then watched the still-strong breezes
of Maui wreak havoc with his game.
</P>
<P>
   He lost the lead for the first time since early Friday when he
stubbed a chip shot on the par-5 15th and then could not get up and
down.
</P>
<P>
   Els, meanwhile, rode hot ball-striking to four consecutive
birdies starting at the fourth. None of his birdie putts was longer
than 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   He also rolled in an 8-footer at the par-3 11th to get to
10-under par for the tournament. A string of pars was all it took
to get in front of Woods when he bogeyed the 15th.
</P>
<P>
   Els missed several mid-range birdie attempts on the back nine,
but still was in position to take a lead into today until the 18th.
The 663-yard hole plays directly downhill and the 25-mph wind was
whistling from the players' backs.
</P>
<P>
   Els hit a driver and 3-wood pin high and two-putted from 50 feet
on the right fringe for a birdie. But Woods one-upped him when he
drained his eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, he had an off day and still shot 2 under,'' Els
said. ``I mean, the talent and ability is there by abundance.''
</P>
<P>
   Els said he wasn't overly worried about Woods running away from
the field after he had birdied the first hole to go five strokes
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do?'' he said. ``When he starts off like that, if
he's going to blitz the golf course, what can you do? You can only
control your own game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing pretty well this week. I'm just going to try to
give myself chances and try to stay up with the guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think you'll see a different Tiger Woods (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Or Els.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
