<SLUG> BC-HIDDEN-HILLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIET VIBE HAS WELL-OFF HEADING FOR THE HILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Harrison Sheppard  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Tiny Hidden Hills is the most exclusive, priciest
community in L.A.'s San Fernando Valley, home to celebrities and
CEOs, a place where a house that sells for $1 million is considered
a fixer-upper.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to armed patrols, gated fences and security cameras,
Hidden Hills, about 27 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles, is
highly protected, and isolated, from the outside world -- qualities
that make it attractive to such celebrities as Sinbad, Alex Van
Halen, Lisa Marie Presley, Bob Eubanks and Beau Bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the gates, those who live there compare it to an idyllic
suburb of yesteryear, a true community where kids feel safe playing
in the streets and everybody knows each other, except for some of
the celebrities who crave privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this sounds crazy, but it's probably one of the most
amazing communities you'll see in your life,'' said Lisa Gutman,
who moved to Hidden Hills eight years ago and sells real estate
there for Re/Max in Calabasas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of these communities you move in and you instantly
know you'll never leave it. People don't leave, they move around,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden Hills was built in the 1950s and incorporated as a city
in 1961. There are 628 homes and now only 20 vacant lots, all on
about two square miles of land. Just under 2,000 people live there.
Minimum lot sizes start at an acre.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the median price of a home sold in Hidden Hills was
$1.2 million, up from $909,000 in 1998, according to
Acxiom/DataQuick, a real estate research firm. But most homes that
go for $1 million are bought for the land, so builders can tear
down the houses and put up much larger estates.
</P>
<P>
   The security has given Hidden Hills one of the lowest crime
rates anywhere -- typically less than a dozen incidents a year,
almost none major or violent. But it also creates a forbidding, and
almost too-perfect facade to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kid around -- we call it the Stepford Wives or Peyton
Place,'' Gutman said. ``You live here, you're part of Hidden Hills.
Our things are not open to outsiders.''
</P>
<P>
   The community has a strong back-to-nature vibe to it, with horse
trails throughout the neighborhoods, not to mention the occasional
coyote and snake in the back yard. Houses are large, but most
aren't overwhelming. On weekends, children set up lemonade stands
on the corners.
</P>
<P>
   Patte Gilbert, a Realtor with Fred Sands Realtors in nearby
Calabasas, said those looking for the tightest security don't move
into Hidden Hills -- instead they just fence and seal up their own
homes. Those who do move there do so because they are looking for
the sense of community and safety not usually found in urban areas,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   They are also looking to send their children to good public
schools in the Las Virgenes Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that some clients have found Hidden Hills too
pretentious and exclusionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's meant to be that way,'' Gilbert said. ``I
don't think people are saying, I want to block the world out.'
They're saying, I want to experience a sense of community for me
and my family.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
