<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO EMBRACE `MALCOLM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get it right this time, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   Tonight Fox gives view ers a second chance to embrace an
offbeat, irreverent, even subversive comedy. The late, lamented
``Action'' sank like a Nielsen stone when viewers fled from its
bleeped-out cursing and ``adult situations,'' also known as kinky
sex scenes.
</P>
<P>
   If there's any justice _ and I'm aware there's not _ ``Malcolm
in the Middle'' won't suffer a similar fate.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm is the third of four children in a harried household. A
good kid, if a bit high-strung. Then it's discovered he has an IQ
of 165. Good news, you might think, but not to a gritty kid who
suddenly finds himself in a gifted class, surrounded by brainiacs
whose intelligence outweighs their social skills by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
   That sets the premise: Genius kid tries to balance
sometimes-geeky gift with status as target of brothers and parents.
The first three episodes are often rude, occasionally crude and
sometimes a little cruel.
</P>
<P>
   They're also funny.
</P>
<P>
   The first scene of the series serves as a litmus test. If a wife
shaving her naked husband's back at the kitchen table while the
kids eat breakfast sounds funny, you've found your show.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds disgusting _ well, I'm sure there's a ``Touched By
an Angel'' rerun on somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Linwood Boomer created the show, based partly on his own
experience of being labeled ``gifted'' as a child. (He played Adam
Kendall on ``Little House on the Prairi''e).
</P>
<P>
   The key word being ``partly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the same way like when you get together with the family at
Thanksgiving dinner or something,'' Boomer says, ``and you trot out
those old war stories, and every time you tell them they get more
and more exaggerated and more self-serving, and the memory gets a
little more selective.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Muniz is the engine that drives ``Malcolm.'' The
13-year-old nails the title role, capturing perfectly the anxiety
of a gifted kid struggling mightily to fit in with his ``normal''
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ``so'' cool,'' Muniz says of the role. ``It's sort of
like me and sort of not. . . . I'm not really (a genius), but
Malcolm doesn't really act like a genius. Only when he has to be
smart, he is. But when he's home, he's normal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm'' is a welcome jab in the ribs of the traditional
family comedy, and Fox's best chance at a successful live-action
comedy. It's not afraid to take shots at uncomfortable targets _
socially awkward kids, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, it's out-and-out funny. It's a throwaway line from a later
episode, but when an off-screen kid shrieks, ``Leave the squirrel
alone and get the fire extinguisher!'' I was hooked for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we'll find an audience or not,'' Boomer says.
``I certainly hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   Me, too. ``Malcolm'' deserves one. &QL; Reach Goodykoontz at
bill.goodykoontz(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8974. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
