<HEADLINE>
LIVING OUR LIVES ON THE HIT-AND-RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
Friday, Jan. 7, was the second anniversary, so I drove out to 35th
Avenue and Deer Valley, where it happened.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day is some kind of anniver sary. According to The Arizona
Republic, this Jan. 7 marked one year since the start of Bill
Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The paper said Jan. 7, 1953, was the day President Harry Truman
an nounced we had the H-bomb.
</P>
<P>
   A book from the public library says the Civil War battle of
Manassas Junction began on Jan. 7, 1862; and that the Flash Gordon
comic strip debuted Jan. 7, 1934; and that, on Jan. 7, 1955, singer
Marian Anderson became the first African-American to star in a New
York Metropolitan Opera production.
</P>
<P>
   Millard Fillmore, the 13th president of the United States, was
born on Jan. 7. So was Today Show host Katie Couric and pop star
Kenny Loggins.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese Emperor Hirohito died on Jan. 7, as did Trevor
Howard, the actor, John Berryman, the poet, and Mark Pase Miller, a
12-year-old from northwest Phoenix, about whom I had forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Mark's father, Paul, sent me an e-mail last week thanking me for
having written about his son two years ago, shortly after the
accident. As the anniversary of Mark's death approached, Miller was
thinking even more about a boy he already spends much of his day
thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't thought of him for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   So, on Friday I drove to 35th Avenue and Deer Valley. Just south
of the intersection, near a side street called Abraham Lane,
there's a white wooden cross with the name ``Mark'' on it planted
near the sidewalk on the east side of the street.
</P>
<P>
   Early on the morning of Jan. 7, 1997, Mark Miller left home for
middle school. He was an honor student, a happy, independent kid,
as are his brother and sister, Ben and Ashley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think about him going out that morning,'' Paul said.
``You always worry when your kids have to cross a busy street. But
Mark wasn't reckless.''
</P>
<P>
   In the neighborhoods north of the new Loop 101 freeway, 35th
Avenue becomes the two-lane road it had been before developers
seeded fallow cotton fields with money and up sprouted houses with
red tile roofs.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a while to reach the heart of the city from this part
of town. No one drives slowly. On that dark and overcast morning,
commuters didn't see the 12-year-old crossing the street.
</P>
<P>
   Mark was clipped by a passing car, knocked down but not killed.
The driver stopped. A gray car behind behind her didn't bother.
Mark was pulled under the automobile and dragged to the spot where
the cross now stands.
</P>
<P>
   The artificial roses wrapped around his homemade memorial have
faded over time, as has any hope of finding the hit-and-run driver,
as have our recollections of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our family is getting along as well as can be expected,'' Paul
said. ``The kids help a lot. They're our strength. As for the
driver of that car, I guess he or she will just have to live with
it. Although how you can drive off and not stop, I can't imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither can I. Neither can you, I'd guess. Though we do it just
about every time we read the paper. The news of the day appears
suddenly in our headlights, like a child on a darkened street. We
don't often stop, or even look back.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, on Friday morning, a newspaper writer put aside his
``im portant'' work and drove to a windy, traffic-heavy spot where
there was no one to meet, nothing to do and little to see besides a
small white cross wrapped in artificial roses. And a boy's name.
Mark. Reach Montini at Ed.Montini &LR; Ari zonaRepublic.com or at (602)
444-8978.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
