<HEADLINE>
NOW STREAK SHOULD MATTER TO LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ten in a row, 11, 12, 13, 14 ...? The Los Angeles
Lakers pretend not to be able to count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about the streak,'' Shaquille O'Neal said to
reporters late Friday night at the Staples Center, where the Lakers
had just made it 13 straight, on their way to 14 with Saturday
night's victory over the Supersonics in Seattle. ``You guys are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking, `Oh, no, we have to win the game to keep
the streak going,' '' Derek Fisher said of the Lakers' desperate
rally after they trailed the Charlotte Hornets by double figures
with seven minutes to play. ``I was thinking, `We have to win the
game.' '' Period.
</P>
<P>
   If the new, improved Lakers seem more willing than before to do
the little things that win games, they also want to seem not to
care that they're winning games in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   But they should care about the streak.
</P>
<P>
   They should care about the streak that reached one with that
ugly, though thrilling, 87-83 victory over Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   That game began a string of 16 Lakers games that include 14
against teams with winning records, among them road games against
Central Division leader Indiana on Jan. 14, Midwest Division leader
Utah on Jan. 24 and defending champion San Antonio on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The teams the Lakers have played so far, running up a
league-best 29-5 record, are a combined 100 games under .500. The
teams they'll face in this month-long stretch are 73 above.
</P>
<P>
   Think anybody's told them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches get paid to tell us that stuff,'' Fisher said a bit
wearily.
</P>
<P>
   If the Staples Center fans seemed uncharacteristically revved up
when Glen Rice's 3-pointer gave the Lakers their first lead late in
the Charlotte game, it's because they realize this was a pivotal
game.
</P>
<P>
   A Lakers loss, and the streak of victories against the NBA's
weaklings would have proven exactly nothing.
</P>
<P>
   A Lakers win, and maybe they've got something here.
</P>
<P>
   That figures to be the theme of the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends say, `Y'all are rolling,' '' Robert Horry said. ``I
say, `Heck, we aren't playing anybody that good.' We have a tough
stretch of road games coming up. That's going to be the real test
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of Horry's friends who think Phil Jackson's first L.A.
team is rolling straight to the NBA Finals, remember that only two
months ago the cynics were competing to see who could list the most
Lakers weaknesses. And those weaknesses are lurking, preparing to
bite the Lakers right in their prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Power forward. The next few weeks may determine whether you can
be the best team in the NBA with 36-year-old A.C. Green and the
injury-prone Horry at power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard: Or with creaky-kneed Ron Harper, 35, running the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Depth. Or without a serious backup center or fire-lighting
shooter coming off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq dependence. So much of the Lakers' success so far has
depended on O'Neal's inspired all-around play his improved
rebounding and defense have made the hole at power forward all but
irrelevant that it's scary to think what happens if he wears down.
Which isn't unthinkable, considering that in many games, he's on
the floor for every minute until it's won.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's contract. His performance against Charlotte, which
included six rebounds and two steals in the fourth-quarter rally,
suggested he's a happy, committed Laker. But what if his
pay-me-or-trade-me demand becomes a distraction again?
</P>
<P>
   Portland: The Lakers might be on pace for a 70-wins season, but
the Trail Blazers were only 3 games behind them going into Saturday
night. And the Blazers, with Scottie Pippen and Steve Smith new to
the lineup, were expected to be slow to hit their stride.
</P>
<P>
   As were the Lakers, of course, having to adjust to Jackson's
triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that the Lakers have room for improvement?
</P>
<P>
   Or has their fast start left them with a long way to fall?
</P>
<P>
   Jackson may have covered up some of the weaknesses with clever
substitutions, confidence-building psychology and a more efficient
offense, but how long can he do that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're sitting on top and everybody will be gunning for
us,'' Fisher said. ``That's when life starts to get a lot harder.
We will lose a game. And then we'll see what we're made of.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
