<HEADLINE>
INS IS RIGHT, LET ELIAN GO HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICARDO PIMENTEL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
Communists can't be good fathers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No, that's not it.
</P>
<P>
   As a country, we shouldn't send children back to countries where
they might face hardships.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, that can't be it either.
</P>
<P>
   Darn it, I'm having a tough time summoning any outrage over the
Immigration and Naturalization Service's decision this week that
6-year-old refugee Elian Gonzalez should be returned to his father
in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   So, I'll applaud.
</P>
<P>
   It was the right thing to do even if getting him there might be
tougher than simply saying he should go. Cuban expatriates in
Florida have vowed to do anything to block his return.
</P>
<P>
   Elian is the boy found clinging to an inner tube at sea after
his mother, stepfather and eight others died while trying to reach
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   His situation immediately became embroiled in international and
domestic politics. Cuban- &QL; 
Americans have been clamoring that he should not be returned. They
have legitimate problems with Castro, communism and totalitarian
regimes.
</P>
<P>
   Various presidential aspirants _ our own John McCain among them
_ weighed in. The fact that Cuban-Americans vote in high numbers
might have something to do with this.
</P>
<P>
   But, it all left many of us wondering what happened to the
Republican issue of family values.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple enough.
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy has befallen this child. There can hardly be a bigger
one in a child's life than the loss of a mother.
</P>
<P>
   At such times, trips to Disney World, toys and the showering
attention of well-wishers will not help as much as a simple hug
from a father, especially one, as is apparently the case here, who
loves his son and has been involved in his life. A lifetime of
relative privilege will not take the place of a lifetime of
guidance from a caring father, even one who's poor.
</P>
<P>
   Are we to believe that Mickey Mouse and the well-intentioned
attentions of more distant relatives _ all strangers to this boy _
will take its place?
</P>
<P>
   We can't have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   With plenty of good cause, we wring our hands here at home about
how uncaring, deadbeat, absentee fathers _ those who think
fathering is simply a matter of helping with the conception _ are
to blame for many of our societal ills.
</P>
<P>
   But, enter a father who wants to do the right thing and all of a
sudden we lose sight of the mantra we've all been chanting for a
number of years now: Fathers matter.
</P>
<P>
   The argument that the wishes of the mother should be considered
do tug at the heart. She clearly wanted her son in the United
States, as evidenced by the fact that she was bringing him here.
But does this mean she wanted him here parentless? It doesn't seem
likely, having met a lot of moms.
</P>
<P>
   So, enter the privation argument: By sending Elian back, we
sentence him to a lifetime of hardship.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that argument is that much of the hardship
visited upon Cuba is the result of a wrongheaded U.S. embargo of
that island nation. We're virtually alone in the world on this
score. Everyone else is doing business with Cuba, but not the
trading partner liable to make the biggest dent in the Cuban misery
index.
</P>
<P>
   This, too, is a policy held hostage to Cuban-American votes,
though there are some indications that Congress might be amenable
to a partial lifting of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   But, if poverty is the reason Elian should not be returned to
Cuba, we need to take another look at the kids we've sent back to
Mexico, Guatemala and El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so maybe we're worried about the loss of rights Elian will
suffer in a return to Cuba. We shouldn't. It's fairly certain that,
though Castro has outlasted nine U.S. presidents and some
assassination attempts, the dictator, now in his mid-70s, will not
outlast 6-year-old Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom for Cuba is inevitable and Elian will live to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Family reunification, the INS' stated rationale for the boy's
return, is sometimes better as an ideal than it is in practice.
Let's face it, there should be a law against some parents.
</P>
<P>
   But Elian and his father don't fit this profile.
</P>
<P>
   The INS was right and the expatriates continue to be wrong in
prolonging the boy's stay here. Let Elian go home to his father. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 0129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
