<SLUG> BC-ROBB-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNDITS WANT CANDIDATES TO TELL ALL, EXCEPT ABOUT FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB ROBB 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
As a generally religious people, it is surprising that Americans
have not evolved broadly accepted protocols for discussing the role
of faith in public life.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But we haven't, and the propriety of religious views in the
public square took center stage in both the Democratic and
Republican presidential debates last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic debate, Al Gore protested that he had never
volunteered his religious beliefs. But when asked directly about
them, he thought he had an obligation to respond truthfully and
fully. Nevertheless, he respected his opponent, Bill Bradley, for
declining to do precisely what Gore had just described as an
obligation.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, for his part, said that religious beliefs are deeply
personal and private, and should not be discussed in a political
campaign. He had never done so, and wasn't going to in this
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's position is the one approved by what one wag has
termed the ``chattering class,'' of which I am now a dissident
member: the largely liberal reporters and commentators who purport
to analyze and explain politics and public policy to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are inconsistencies in the chattering class' point of
view. For the most part, they also say we need to know what kind of
people candidates are, not just their policy positions.
</P>
<P>
   In all major religions, faith is not just something you bring to
occasional ceremonial exercises. It's a force that animates your
daily life. If you want to know what makes a religious person tick,
you begin with his faith.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the chattering class' immersion in the
self-confessional ethic of this era. We want candidates to tell us
all about themselves, except, apparently, for their religious
beliefs and experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Hence we get the strange paradox of the chattering class
applauding when John McCain reveals that he once dated a stripper
who cleaned her fingernails with a switchblade, yet cringing when
George W. Bush tells us that faith in Jesus Christ changed his
heart, enabling him to quit drinking and find focus in a political
career.
</P>
<P>
   For my part, I would prefer that we lived in a less
self-revelatory age and judged candidates more on how they would
govern the country than on what kind of people they are.
</P>
<P>
   While religious beliefs do provide a revealing glimpse into
character, they aren't a particularly useful guide to performance
in public office. And while both the religious left and the
religious right have a tendency sometimes to regard the Bible as
containing a political platform, in reality people of genuine faith
can begin with identical religious precepts and reason themselves
into widely different public-policy conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   But we don't live in an age in which we judge candidates on
their policies and political capabilities and are circumspect about
judging the character of people we don't really know very well. And
if we are in the business of judging the kind of people candidates
are, it's hard to understand why their faith life is not relevant,
while their past sex life, drug use, business activities and, in
this campaign, even college grades are relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, the chattering class goes beyond somewhat
amusing inconsistencies and devolves into something darker and more
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   In a generally execrable performance as moderator of Thursday's
Republican debate, Tim Russert of NBC asked George W. Bush the
following question: ``Fifteen million atheists in this country, 5
million Jews, 5 million Muslims, millions more Buddhists and
Hindus: Should they feel excluded from George W. Bush because of
his allegiance to Jesus?''
</P>
<P>
   You can bet your last ounce of political correctness that
Russert would never have asked a Jew, a Muslim, a Buddhist or a
Hindu whether other Americans should be concerned about them
holding public office because of their faith. Post-JFK, he
certainly wouldn't ask it of a Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he felt free to ask it of George W. Bush, a born-again
Christian.
</P>
<P>
   There are no other words to describe it: Russert's question was
an act of brutal and ugly religious bigotry. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 0134EST &QL; 
