<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. MCCAIN OPENS FILES IN DONOR FLAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER AND KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
WASHINGTON _ John McCain, hoping to defuse a potential political
bomb, opened his files Saturday and released letters he wrote to
U.S. regulatory agencies in behalf of large campaign donors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the letters was written for a satellite firm McCain aided
extensively before and after it raised $18,000 for him in campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Other major campaign donors helped by McCain included telephone
companies and broadcasters, many of whom have an interest in
legislation that falls under the auspices of the Senate Commerce
Committee, which the Arizona senator heads. Among them are rural
and Hispanic broadcasters in Arizona who say the legislation has
hurt their interests.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual gambit by the GOP presidential contender, more
than 500 letters in all were carried to a suburban hotel conference
room and arranged in stacks on a wooden table. Commerce Committee
aides were made available for hours to answer reporters' questions
about the McCain letters.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen letters were placed apart from the rest because they
benefited businesses or individuals who have contributed at least
$2,000 to McCain's campaign. It was those letters that pointed most
directly to the issue now dogging McCain: whether he has gone too
far in intervening with agencies in behalf of some of his largest
campaign benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   The questions have grown persistent enough that his handlers
believed a dramatic and thorough response was needed to prevent the
risk of serious harm to his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, while McCain campaigned in South Carolina, his
aides sought to use the letters themselves to demonstrate he has
not been influenced by campaign cash. The 500 letters, most of them
expressing concerns in behalf of Arizona constituents who did not
contribute at all, were intended to show that he fights just as
hard for non-contributors as for those with deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't differentiate between people who give or not,''
said Mark Buse, staff director of the Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Among the contributors were executives of EchoStar, a
Colorado-based satellite TV company that McCain has assisted both
through legislation and in an August 1998 letter he wrote to the
Federal Communications Commission that was released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   EchoStar is, in many ways, a case study for the questions facing
McCain. He aided the firm on a key legislative matter, and it's
clear he benefited from its employees' campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
   The letter contained no evidence that it was written in
anticipation of fund-raisers. McCain aides said his main concern
was simply to provide competition to the cable industry.
</P>
<P>
   EchoStar and its employees have given $18,000 for McCain's
candidacy, the campaign said. The company's chairman, Charles
Ergen, sponsored a March 1999 fund-raiser in which the firm's vice
president, its senior vice president, and its chief operating
officer all donated $1,000, according to Federal Election
Commission records. Ergen also gave $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCain was boosting EchoStar on several fronts. As
the Commerce Committee chairman, he helped EchoStar and firms like
it win permission in Congress last year to offer local programming,
including local affiliates of the four major broadcast networks.
For years, the satellite firms had complained they were handicapped
in competing with cable because they could not deliver local
stations. Now they can, thanks partly to McCain, who made their
cause one of his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in 1998, McCain had written to the FCC to elicit
statistical information to help the satellite firms respond to a
related issue: a Miami court decision threatening their
subscribers' network feeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We acted on this letter at this time because of a court case.
It has nothing to do with anything else,'' Buse said.
</P>
<P>
   But some broadcasters still are not happy. Under the new law,
satellite firms, at least for the next two years, may
``cherry-pick'' which local stations they want to carry, often
excluding rural populations served by small independent stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's not very fair for the smaller-market
stations,'' said Rich Howe, general manager of KUSK-TV in Prescott,
one of the rural Arizona stations that have so far been kept off
the satellites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping that's not going to be the definitive end of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although rural stations are hardest hit by the new legislation,
Howe noted that other broadcasters, including many small religious
stations, the local WB Channel, and the state's two local Hispanic
affiliates, Telemundo and Univision, are also left off satellite
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``That leaves out a lot of people,'' Howe said. He added
hopefully, ``We're still on the launching pad right now.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's staff on Saturday said he wants to see Hispanic
stations carried by satellite companies, which have become more
popular in recent years. And they point out that the companies,
under a provision called ``must carry,'' will be required to
include all local stations by 2002, just as cable operators do.
</P>
<P>
   ``(McCain) would like to see Telemundo on these services,'' Buse
said. ``And there is certainly a better chance of them getting up
now than if there was no law at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a number of industry officials remember the day McCain
was feted at Ergen's fund-raiser, attended by dozens of
satellite-industry executives.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of stations in New England and Arizona said
privately that McCain's attendance at the fund-raiser showed
favoritism toward the satellite companies at a time when the fates
of both cable broadcasters and satellite companies were in the
balance.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's aides defended the decision to hold the fund-raiser
despite its proximity to the crafting of sensitive, multiparty
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that if McCain were to stop writing legislation
whenever he needed to raise money, he would either have no money or
little legislation to show for his time on Capitol Hill. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 0144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
