r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-PACERS-L     01-09 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-PACERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS BEAT PACERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Clippers, behaving like the
fearless rookie pool player who sacrifices touch for velocity,
finally put an opponent behind the eight ball.
</P>
<P>
   Then they chalked up their first victory in five games.
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Olowokandi rumored to be a bigger disappointment
than the Y2K bug _ going relatively cuckoo, the Clips defeated the
Indiana Pacers 107-94 on Saturday in front of 17,004 at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi rallied for a career-high 24 points and a game-high
17 rebounds in a hustle that lifted his cronies to their first
victory over the Pacers in 2,571 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really? I was back in London kicking around a soccer ball,''
said Olowokandi when informed the Pacers (22-10) had an 11-game
winning streak over the Clippers (10-22) that dated back to Dec.
13, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi, who had been punted around Staples by Shaquille
O'Neal during last week's two-game Lakers series, found the defense
of 7-foot-4 Rik Smits a bit less hurtful.
</P>
<P>
   And the Clippers defense, which lately had been as tough as the
questions in a `Donny and Marie' interview, finally rose about the
level of embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up an average of 122 points over their last four
games, the Clippers didn't surrender a field goal to the Pacers
until the 5:56 mark of the opening quarter. The bucket was a fluke,
too, created when Clipper Lamar Odom deflected a Mark Jackson pass
through the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi had 10 points and eight rebounds in the opening half.
His jump hook at 7:23 of the first period gave the Clippers a 16-4
lead. They finished the quarter up 27-20.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone Nesby (23 points), whose price for missing the morning
shoot-around was his starting gig, provided a dozen points in the
second quarter. Taylor (23 points) had 16 points and no fouls at
intermission, which arrived with the Clippers leading 58-44.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi added eight points and six rebounds during the third
period, as the Clips entered the final quarter with a 79-67 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: When it was the Pacers' turn to make a selection in the
first round of the 1997 NBA Draft, they used the 12th pick to
choose 6-9 forward Austin Croshere, who played at Santa Monica's
Crossroads High before starring at Providence College. The Clippers
selected Maurice Taylor with the next pick. Last summer, the Clips
had a chance to acquire Croshere and point guard Travis Best in a
sign-and-trade offer for free agent Lorenzen Wright. They passed,
eventually dealing Wright to Atlanta for two first-round picks.
Best, who has a career average of seven points per game, is giving
the Pacers about the same off the bench. But Croshere, who averaged
3.4 points in just 27 appearances last season, is providing nine
points per game this season. Of course, until the Clippers'
additional first-round picks are made and developed (or packaged
and traded), it's impossible to judge their yield in dealing
Wright....
</P>
<P>
   While the hot air of trade winds involving Olowokandi swirled
around Chicago, Bulls GM Jerry Krause phoned Elgin Baylor Thursday
afternoon to assure him that he didn't start the rumor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 0156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
