<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SONICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' STREAK CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ From the unpredictable to the impossible, The Streak
that refused to die made it to its 14th anniversary Saturday night,
and the Seattle SuperSonics graciously played host for the party.
</P>
<P>
   Last one out, turn out the lights on the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers ran their winning streak to 14 games with
a 110-100 victory over the Sonics at KeyArena _ and as if that
weren't impressive enough, they reached the new plateau with their
greatest comeback of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Down 19 points early in the second half, up 20 by late in the
fourth. Only NASDAQ has had greater momentum swings this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say about that game,'' said coach Phil
Jackson. ``It's just two halves in a ballgame.... We came in the
locker room (at halftime) and said, thank god there are two halves
to a game and we can make some adjustments and come back out and
play some defense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some defense'' turned into a stifling attack that held the
Sonics who scored 66 in the first half _ to 12 points in the third
and just 34 in the second half. Just as impressive was the offense,
as Glen Rice, playing hero for the second straight night, scored 15
points in the third and finished with 24 points, two steals and
three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant added a shooting touch to his acrobatics, making his
first five 3-point tries of the night to lead the Lakers with 31
points, six rebounds and three steals. Shaquille O'Neal battled
through foul trouble but finished with 23 points, nine rebounds and
a team-high six assists.
</P>
<P>
   It all made for an amazing comeback-to-back weekend. The Lakers
overcame a 13-point deficit Friday to beat the Charlotte Hornets in
what was,at the time, their biggest come-from-behind win of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers, an NBA-best 29-5, aren't just piling up wins
anymore. They're picking up style points for winning every way
imaginable, adopting the second-half surge as their latest fashion
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says a lot,'' Rice said. ``It shows that this team has the
will, has the character, to be able to come out of a difficult
situation and come out on top and win a ballgame. It also shows we
have a panic button,but yet we still we go out there and we keep it
under control.''
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yeah, did we mention the Lakers are on pace for 70 wins?
</P>
<P>
   The way they played the second half, that figure is getting
harder to scoff at.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers down 70-51 early in the third, Bryant settled
down and got the offense into a rhythm, helping Rice start the
comeback with an eight-point burst. Minutes later, the Lakers had
completed a 21-2 run that tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then O'Neal, who had difficulty exploiting his size advantage
against the center-less Sonics, picked up his fifth foul with 3:09
left in the quarter. No matter. The Lakers' unsung bench picked it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry hit a jumper, Derek Fisher followed with another,
A.C. Green pitched in a bucket and then Fisher _ who recently
suffered a 2-for-30 stretch _ hit a 3-pointer to close out the
quarter and give the Lakers an 83-78 lead heading into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for the guys to play without me sometimes,''
O'Neal said. ``They responded well.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who also opened the fourth with a 3-pointer, led the
bench effort with eight points, all in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   A stunned Sonics squad, led by Vin Baker's 31 points, never
responded. And by the time Bryant hit an 18-footer over Ruben
Patterson (the self-proclaimed ``Kobe stopper'') for a 13-point
lead, then jogged off the floor tapping his heart, it was clear the
Lakers would not let up.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, who scored 19 in the first half, managed just two in
the second. Gary Payton, guarded mostly by Bryant, got just six
points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big for us,'' Bryant said. ``It's a confidence-booster.
You get in situations like this again, you have confidence that you
can come back and win. The game (Friday) night, even though it was
a tough game for us, that gave us a lot of confidence coming into
this evening, because we were playing bad, but we weren't playing
worse than we were last night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
