A0877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SALES10-COX     01-09 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retailers look to hook buyers with January bargains
 &HT;    By Brian Stevens
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Looking for bargains this winter? Traditional
seasonal sales abound as retailers look to lure back shoppers with
exhausted credit cards and exhausted spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do see household items _ whites, linens and towels _ on
sale,'' said Wright State University assistant professor of
marketing Chuck Gulas.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales typically occur in January after the holiday buying
blitz of November and December, Gulas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holiday credit card bills are coming due and people realize
they can't spend as much,'' Gulas said, leading retailers to use
winter sales as a draw for mall-weary post-holiday shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Brown, operations manager at Waccamaw's Homeplace in
Centerville, said the store's annual winter white sale always
brings in shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new year and people are looking for a fresh look. They
want something to take them through the winter doldrums,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gulas said after-Christmas advertising is often driven by the
winter blahs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are indoors, they're looking at things in the house _
getting organized and maybe looking to lose a few pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at the Sunday newspaper ad circulars proves Gulas' point:
The copy tells shoppers it's ``time to get organized'' with sales
on closet organizers, ``store it in style'' with heavy-duty plastic
containers, offers discounts on treadmills and a ``towel continuity
sale.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gulas said customers are drawn out by the discounts and
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Tabatabaie, a local shopper, said she hit the stores the
day after Christmas, ``knowing there's probably a sale this time of
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulas said savvy consumers can employ a ``shopping strategy,''
using the technology of the Internet to search for bargains at
traditional ``brick and mortar'' stores.
</P>
<P>
   Surf store Web sites and ``get a feel for price and selection''
before you head out to buy, Gulas said. While Internet commerce
accounts for only a fraction of retail sales, Gulas said the
technology is ``changing the whole face of retailing. Consumers
expect bargains on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for sales on big-ticket items like televisions and
electronics as the Super Bowl draws near, Gulas said.
</P>
<P>
   One full-color electronics store advertisement promised
``guaranteed delivery before Tuesday's big game'' on a 60-inch
projection television, and 10 others were for sale _ all tuned to
football games.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what your shopping fancy, Tabatabaie has this advice:
``Never pay full price.''
</P>
<P>
   HOT DEALS, COLD SHOPPERS
</P>
<P>
   Looking for bargains? Here are some ideas to get you started on
post-holiday sales shopping:
</P>
<P>
   _ Take advantage of big after-holiday markdowns and clearances
by shopping for wrapping paper, holiday cards and seasonal
decorations now.
</P>
<P>
   _ Plan ahead. Impulse buying never pays. Set a realistic budget
and stick to it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compare prices and shop carefully. Post-holiday sales
sometimes aren't the bargains they appear to be.
</P>
<P>
   _ Before buying anything _ especially sale items _ ask about the
store's refund and exchange policy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be aware of your shopping mood. Don't let a case of winter
blues blow your budget on a shopping binge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use store coupons. Even the larger department stores
occasionally offer coupons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wait for a sale. If you don't absolutely need it now, waiting
may pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
