   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   SOLDIER-DEATH (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Somewhere amid a long ordeal
of grief for her murdered son, it dawned on Patricia Kutteles that
she will never be done with the U.S. Army, where her son found a
home that proved his undoing and left her a cause she pursues now
as his only true memorial. ``I realized it won't ever end `til I
die,'' Mrs. Kutteles said of her struggle to absorb, first, the
brutal barracks bludgeoning of her son; and then, the shocking
discovery that he was taunted for months on base as a ``faggot''
and ``queer''; and, now, her deepening disgust with military
justice. By Francis X. Clines. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   SOLDIER-SENTENCE (Washington) _ The roommate of Private
Winchell, the gay soldier beaten to death at Fort Campbell, was
sentenced to 14 years in prison late Saturday for obstructing
justice. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-CITY (Halfway, Ore.) _ If the nation must have its first
official ``dot-com'' city, Halfway hardly seems the obvious choice.
Tucked away in the shadow of the snowy Wallowa Mountains in eastern
Oregon's sagebrush country, hard by the Idaho border and just south
of Hells Canyon, the community is decidedly not an Internet boom
town. By Sam Howe Verhovek. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   ROS-LEHTINEN-PROFILE (Miami) _ Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, the
fist-shaking anti-communist member of Congress from Little Havana.
By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-INVEST (Undated) _ Ted Forstmann, the billionaire leveraged
buyout specialist, John Walton, an heir to the Wal-Mart fortune,
John Doerr, the technology venture capitalist, and David Komansky,
the chairman of Merrill Lynch, have funneled millions of dollars to
programs that help poor, minority children to attend the schools of
their choice and to companies that are aiming to take advantage of
the growing acceptance of for-profit ventures in education. Now
they are going further. Their aim is nothing less than to overhaul
the nation's system of public education. To do so, they want to
eliminate what they call the government's ``monopoly'' role in
education, instead stimulating investment in private companies that
will build schools that any child can attend for free.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
