<SLUG> BC-NEWSMAGS-ENTERTAINMENT-MEDIA-ART-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME'S HUMOR COLUMNIST GIVES WEEKLY A TRULY DIFFERENT PERSPECTIVE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joel Stein, a 28-year-old magazine columnist, likes to pepper
his columns with bawdy humor, tasteless one-liners and something
that can best be described as a sort of polished vulgarity.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, he began one column about Susan Faludi's book
``Stiffed: The Betrayal of the American Man'' by writing, ``I don't
want Susan Faludi's pity. I want her tight little body.''
</P>
<P>
   He once asked the comedian Don Rickles if he liked to ``use
insult humor during sex.''
</P>
<P>
   He has written of his desire to wax his hairy body, printed a
discussion with the actor Ben Stiller about male sexual appendages,
and has suffered the wrath of a furious Sharon Stone, who slammed
down the phone and has sworn never to speak to him again.
</P>
<P>
   If you think Stein writes for Penthouse, Maxim magazine or the
local campus newspaper, think again: He writes for Time magazine.
As Time, the flagship publication of Time Warner Inc., and its
other newsweekly cousins _ Newsweek, published by the Washington
Post Co., and U.S. News and World Report, owned by the real-estate
developer Mortimer Zuckerman _ pay more attention to entertainment
and lifestyle reporting, the baby-faced 28-year-old Stein is
emerging as a symbol, if an extreme one, of the new newsweekly
mindset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, I don't think I am a real journalist,''
Stein said in an interview in his Time office recently, the walls
papered with letters from readers. ``If Watergate happens, it's not
like they're going to send me out in the field. I feel like I am,
well, whatever we all are now: I am a celebrity journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pace of news has quickened _ Americans get their news
from 24-hour cable television networks, directly from the Internet
or automatically downloaded to their Palm Pilot at the lunch table
_ the newsweekly magazine has undergone a transformation in the
last decade. Instead of staid cover portrait of generals or
presidents or political newsmakers, Time features cover stories
about Harry Potter books, the sudden popularity of the high-protein
diet, whether to have laser eye surgery and when to treat children
with Ritalin. When a major politician or public figure chooses a
media venue for an interview, the preferred outlet is usually
television, not a printed magazine.
</P>
<P>
   And while Time, Newsweek and U.S. News &AMP; World Report have all
broken news in recent years and still jump all over big stories,
they have definitively devoted more space to feature-friendly
categories like self-improvement, health, entertainment and
financial security.
</P>
<P>
   Their circulations have not budged in years. Time's circulation
has not moved from 4.1 million since 1994; Newsweek's has remained
at 3.1 million during that period and the circulation of U.S. News
and World Report has also remained flat, at about 2.2. million.
</P>
<P>
   One key to their future guaranteed readership is to gather
younger readers into the fold. Enter Stein, who said that he
receives his most ardent mail from teen-agers and college students.
One recent letter to Stein described the author's Joel Stein
college dormitory-room shrine.
</P>
<P>
   A 1993 graduate of Stanford University and former writer for the
Martha Stewart Living television show, Stein had limited
journalistic experience before joining Time, with the exception of
a two-year stretch writing sports articles and a humor column at
Time Out New York.
</P>
<P>
   After catching the eye of Walter Isaacson, Time's managing
editor, Stein joined the magazine in 1997 as an entertainment
reporter, noting the foibles and failures of celebrities on the
People page. He graduated to question-and-answer interviews, then
features, and now also writes a column that shares space with the
noted belletrist Calvin Trillin. In every three-week cycle, Stein
writes two weeks of columns, and Trillin writes one.
</P>
<P>
   Stein's ``Notebook'' columns _ in the self-mocking, openly
ironic tradition of Jerry Seinfeld and Howard Stern _ focus on
three topics: himself, his life and his deep, private, personal
thoughts. There was ``My Mother, The Bride,'' in which Stein
offered this advice about a parent's wedding: ``Unlike at a
friend's wedding, it's a bad idea to get drunk and hook up with
guests, because of the preponderance of cousins.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Shaving the Body, Fantastic,'' Stein fantasized for 4.1.
million readers about denuding his entire body of hair and offered
this piece of personal punditry: ``You see, the thing about me that
I find most lamentable, besides my hairy butt, is that I am
attracted to the wrong things in women.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Stein wrote of his dislike for dogs: ``How can
people love something so much that they're willing to walk behind
it and retrieve its feces with their own hands every day? I have
yet to meet a woman for whom I'd do that.'' The magazine received
almost 100 negative letters.
</P>
<P>
   Dog feces. Hairy body parts. Drunken sex with cousins. Is Time
magazine's august founder, Henry Luce, turning in his grave?
Isaacson said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Luce founded this magazine based on humor and a bit of
sassiness, and it's nice to see what we can do to keep up the
tradition,'' he said. Isaacson noted that Stein's columns guarantee
an influx of reader mail. ``There are people who love him and there
are people who are baffled by him, and I think it's good to have
someone in the magazine who provokes opinions,'' he said. Readers'
letters have described Stein variously as ``flat-out obnoxious''
and ``a journalistic mosquito'' as well as ``the best thing to
happen to Time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
