<DOCNO> NYT20000109.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEWSMAGS-ENTERTAINMEN     01-09 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSMAGS-ENTERTAINMENT-MEDIA-ART </SLUG>
 - 2NDTAKE-NYT  
 UNDATED: to Time.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stein said that his columns provoke a response because their
tone is so unexpected in a magazine from which older readers still
expect a tone of somewhat grave authority. After all, who expects a
Time columnist to ask a septuagenarian actress like Esther Williams
``was there a guy in Hollywood you didn't sleep with?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were writing this stuff for Entertainment Weekly or Vibe
or Pop Smear, I would get no reaction,'' Stein said. ``Take the
same stuff and put it in Time and everybody suddenly gets freaked
out. You can do very small things and the people who have been
subscribers for 50 years are either delighted or very, very upset
by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein said that his provocative personal voice is a key
difference in the Time of today, as opposed to the Time of, say,
1972. ``There is a difference in the magazine now,'' he said.
``Walter lets writers have a voice. He lets you express your
opinions and thoughts and feelings in a way that I didn't think a
news magazine ever would.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein's interviews, which the magazine runs as straight
question-and-answer pieces, are seemingly rambling sessions, a
hallmark of which is that they annoy celebrities. When he
interviewed Jennifer Lopez, the singer and actress, he asked her a
series of questions about her body. ``Well, if you really think
about it, what else do you want to know about Jennifer Lopez? Do
you really want to get to know the real Jennifer Lopez?'' Stein
said. ``It saves me from doing a lot of research. I just asked her
questions about her butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most journalists who freely offer their opinion in print,
Stein has ruffled feathers and bruised egos. The comedian Buddy
Hackett will only say this after his experience with Stein: ``I
don't think he's ever going to have a nice life. When you give out
pain, that's what you get back. Plus, he talked about himself the
whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stone won't talk to him anymore, Stein said, because a year
ago he asked her inappropriate questions when he was interviewing
her for a question-and-answer piece. Cindy Berger, Ms. Stone's
public relations agent at PMK, said that Stein had asked questions
of an intimate nature that had upset Ms. Stone. The piece never
ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was persona non grata around here for a while,'' said Ms.
Berger. Stein sent flowers to Ms. Berger and Ms. Stone. Asked if
she had forgiven him, Ms. Berger said: ``A publicist never
forgets.'' As for Ms. Stone, Stein said in a Church Lady voice:
``Well, I don't like her one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the contretemps with Jay McInerney, a novelist.
``Jay McInerney wanted to beat me up,'' Stein said brightly.
</P>
<P>
   Stein wrote a searing profile of McInerney, the author of
``Bright Lights, Big City'' when his last novel, ``Model
Behavior,'' was published in 1998. In an interview last week,
McInerney, apparently still smarting, called Stein ``a supercilious
nonjournalist with an ax to grind'' and said that the one other
piece he had read by Stein was an interview by Stein with Irvine
Welch, the author of the novel ``Trainspotting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it extremely annoying because it was all about Joel
Stein demonstrating his wit at the expense of Irvine Welch,''
McInerney said. ``I wanted to hear what Welch had to say and it was
all about Stein.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyndi Stivers, the editor in chief of Time Out New York and
Stein's former boss, said that Stein is as much a cultural observer
as he is a sort of self-focused monologuist _ if not the embodiment
of a trend as significant as the New Journalism was in the 1970s _
who uses Time as his bully pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful that they are putting first-person
voices in Time,'' she said. ``It makes Time fun to read. I just
can't believe that he gets away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stivers said that at Life magazine, another Time Inc.
publication, where she worked in the 1980s, ``you had to learn to
write in the Time Inc. generic prose, in the voice of the magazine,
and Joel is certainly not that. The first time I saw him write a
reported piece with a first-person reference in the lead I almost
fell out of my chair.''
</P>
<P>
   To Stein, the fact that he reveals intimate, seemingly eccentric
but actually quite normal aspects of his personality to the readers
of Time does not seem terribly original.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth Wurtzel was shocking when she wrote ``Prozac
Nation,'' Stein said. ``Howard Stern talks about himself, and
Seinfeld. People have been talking about themselves in ways they
really shouldn't be for so long that I no longer think I am
original.''
</P>
<P>
   And Isaacson said that Stein is not just an intentional lure for
young readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds like so much marketing talk to me,'' he said.
``He's here because not only is he funny but his humor has a real
intelligence and a real soul. It's not as if you say, `Let's skew
this way by adding a young writer.' You read his stuff and say,
`Hey. That's neat.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
