<HEADLINE>
EVEN AS AN ADULT, MIKEY STILL LIKES LIFE  
 WRITER FIGHTS SUBPOENA IN SHEPPARD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most familiar, most liked television commercials ever
_ the Mikey spot for Life cereal _ is being revived, with a
contemporary twist or two.
</P>
<P>
   The spot, which originally ran nationally from 1972 through
1984, featured two skeptical boys who pushed a bowl of Life at
their finicky brother Mikey, sure he would not enjoy it, because
``he hates everything.'' But to their surprise, Mikey liked Life,
then as now sold by Quaker Oats Co.
</P>
<P>
   The revival is in the form of a remake of the original spot,
which was created by Doyle Dane Bernbach in New York, now part of
the DDB Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   The remake, by the Chicago office of FCB Worldwide, part of True
North Communications, replaces the three boys with three adults to
show that, as an announcer proclaims, ``no one ever outgrows the
terrific taste of Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The remake, which is scheduled to begin running Jan. 17, adds
Life to a list of cereal brands aiming pitches at grown-ups. Others
include Cap'n Crunch, also sold by Quaker, and Frosted Flakes, sold
by Kellogg Co.
</P>
<P>
   In the remake, the adults _ two men and a woman _ follow the
original script word for word. The woman and one man play the
skeptics and the other man is the new Mikey. The only differences
are a new ending, showing the two skeptics also eating bowls of
Life, and the announcer's proclamation of Life's appropriateness
for adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neat part is that they're adults,'' Todd Magazine, vice
president for ready-to-eat cereals at Quaker in Chicago, said of
the new cast, ``but they're kids at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The response to the remake in testing has been overwhelming,''
he added. ``We expect it to be a big hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The new spot, scheduled to run through June, will be
supplemented with promotions like an online trivia contest at
www.lifecereal.com.
</P>
<P>
   If the original commercial generated questions from consumers
wondering who the boys were (three brothers named Gilchrist), the
new one might inspire a question, too: Why are the three adults
seated together at the breakfast table, with the woman and one man
in pajamas and the new Mikey dressed as if getting ready for work?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good question,'' Magazine said, laughing, ``but the
spot is about Life, not the people and their relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps someday there'll be a sequel to the remake, a soap opera
called ``As the Cereal Bowl Turns.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STUART ELLIOTT
</P>
<P>
   Writer Fights Subpoena in Sheppard Case
</P>
<P>
   More than 45 years after Marilyn Sheppard was murdered in her
Cleveland home, the case that inspired the television series ``The
Fugitive'' is still generating heat.
</P>
<P>
   The case is back in court again, and a battle is emerging
involving the media: Prosecutors want the files of an investigative
reporter who is writing a book about the case; the writer is
fighting the subpoena, and his lawyers are charging that
prosecutors have threatened to do him financial harm.
</P>
<P>
   The battle comes 33 years after Dr. Sam Sheppard, Ms. Sheppard's
husband, was retried in the murder and acquitted. He had served 10
years before the Supreme Court overturned the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The writer, James Neff, a 46-year-old former reporter for The
Cleveland Plain Dealer, plans in his book to recount the latest
trial, which is set to begin on Jan. 31 in Cuyahoga County Common
Pleas Court, to determine whether Sheppard was innocent or was
simply not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   If the jury determines that he was innocent, his estate will be
able to sue the state of Ohio for lost wages and $250,000 for the
10 years he spent in prison. Sheppard died in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuyahoga County prosecutor has issued a subpoena seeking all
the evidence that Neff collected. Neff said he feared the evidence
would enter the public record and thus be available ``to somebody
doing a quickie book.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a government taking of years of my work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Marburger, the First Amendment specialist at the Baker &AMP;
Hostetler law firm in Cleveland who is representing Neff, said a
prosecutor, Dean Boland, had threatened that ``if Neff did not
cooperate, they would put him on the witness list'' for the trial
and then get a court order barring him from the courtroom until he
testified, perhaps as the last witness.
</P>
<P>
   William Mason, the Cuyahoga County prosecutor, said he was
convinced that Boland had not made such remarks. Mason said he
could appreciate that Neff felt threatened both journalistically
and economically, but he said Neff appeared to have evidence
central to the case, including the original 1954 police reports.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dever, the lead prosecutor on the Sheppard civil case,
said that any First Amendment issues ``must be subordinated to our
search for the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Neff is the author of three books, including ``Mobbed Up,'' a
1989 biography of Jackie Presser, the Teamsters Union president who
was secretly an FBI informant. The book became the basis of the
film ``Teamster Boss.'' Random House will publish his book on the
Sheppard case, tentatively titled ``Chasing the Fugitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Esther Newberg, Neff's agent, said ``it is hideous that he would
have to turn over'' a decade of work.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors want material from Neff's interviews with Richard
Eberling, a window washer who worked for the Sheppards. DNA
evidence uncovered in 1998 by Terry Gilbert, the lawyer for the
Sheppard estate, implicated Eberling while appearing to exonerate
Sheppard. The prosecutor's office, which maintains that Sheppard
killed his wife, says this evidence should be inadmissible because
the crime scene was contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Eberling died while serving a life sentence for killing another
woman.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
