<SLUG> BC-BOND-CALENDAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY SET TO AUCTION BILLS THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Treasury's schedule of financings this week is confined to
Monday's regular weekly auction of three- and six-month bills and a
10-year Treasury inflation-pegged securities auction on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By the close of the New York cash market on Friday, traders
said, the rate on the outstanding three-month bill was 5.22 percent
and a six-month bill was 5.41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The following taxable and tax-exempt fixed-income issues are
scheduled for pricing this week:
</P>
<P>
   TAXABLE
</P>
<P>
   ONE DAY DURING THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler NA Holding, $2.5 billion of global debt
securities, each consisting of a two-year floater and a five-year
fixed rate. A1 by Moody's Investors Service. Deutsche Bank Alex.
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae, $4 billion of debt securities due in 2002 and $4
billion of debt securities due in 2010. Goldman Sachs, Merrill
Lynch and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Acceptance Corp., $2 billion of global 10-year
debt securities. A2/A/---. Merrill Lynch, Salomon Smith Barney and
Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
   Pefco, $200 million of notes due in 2010. Aaa/AAA/---. Chase
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Republic of Turkey, $1 billion of global debt securities,
expected as a 30-year and possibly a 10-year maturity. B-1/B/---.
Morgan Stanley, Dean Witter and Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
