<DOCNO> NYT20000109.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WINECOFF10-COX     01-09 1629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINECOFF10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bringing the famous Winecoff fire picture into sharper focus
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Arnold Hardy never met the poor woman who streaked
through his viewfinder in a flash and then vanished into the cold
December night more than half a century ago. He was an old man
before he knew for sure what happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   In another sense, though, he's always known: His photograph made
her an enduring emblem of the Winecoff Hotel fire, one of the
saddest episodes in Atlanta history.
</P>
<P>
   Now 77, Hardy is retired from the X-ray equipment manufacturing
firm that he founded and sold to his son. He lives comfortably in
Stone Mountain with his wife, Lorraine, in a house where the only
visible reminders of his prize-winning picture are some framed
awards in the den. The camera was stolen years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He takes a seat at a polished dining room table and places
half-moon glasses under his wispy white eyebrows. He opens a brown
leather valise _ his Winecoff scrapbook _ and a hint of mustiness
escapes from the yellowed clippings and congratulatory telegrams he
received after becoming the first amateur photographer to win the
Pulitzer, journalism's highest honor.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he ever thought of himself as a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   THE NIGHT OF THE FIRE
</P>
<P>
   When the Winecoff burned in 1946, Hardy was a 24-year-old
veteran with a physics degree from Centenary College, in his native
Shreveport, La. He had moved to Atlanta to take a job as a
laboratory research assistant at Georgia Tech, where he enrolled in
some graduate courses. Photography was a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   That year he bought a new camera, a $200 Speed Graphic that
folded into a box carrying case. To pay for it, he figured he could
earn some free-lance money shooting athletic events at Tech. Just
before Thanksgiving, he applied as a stringer at one of the
newspapers (he can't recall whether it was the Journal or
Constitution). The photo editor seemed interested until he saw the
camera, which was half the size of the large-format contraptions
most of the pros lugged around back then.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't use a toy like that to shoot pictures for the
newspaper,'' he blurted. ``Come see me when you get a real
camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy remembered those words a couple of weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Friday night. He had a date with an attractive
brunette. They stayed out late. By the time a bus returned him to
his Midtown rooming house, it was past 3 a.m. Saturday _ the fifth
anniversary of Pearl Harbor. He was undressing for bed when he
heard sirens screaming down West Peachtree Street. He phoned the
fire department and tried a line straight out of a B movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Press photographer,'' he lied. ``Where's the fire?''
</P>
<P>
   The Winecoff. He called a cab and grabbed his ``toy'' camera.
</P>
<P>
   The 195-room hotel on Peachtree Street was completely booked
with more than 280 registered guests, most of them Christmas
shoppers or teen-agers in town for a state meeting of the Hi-Y and
Tri-Hi-Y service organizations. Built in 1913, the Winecoff
advertised itself as ``fireproof,'' an insurance term meaning that
the steel-and-brick frame of the 15-story structure would not burn.
The furnishings were another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after 3:15, an elevator operator smelled smoke coming
from the fourth or fifth floor. (In their 1993 book, ``The Winecoff
Fire,'' Sam Heys and Allen B. Goodwin suggest that it was set by an
ex-con angry over being tossed from a poker game.) When Hardy
arrived _ the first photographer on the scene _ the windows were
glowing like jack-o'-lanterns. The hotel had no fire escapes or
sprinklers, and the fire department ladders couldn't reach past the
seventh floor, so scores of people were trapped in the inferno.
Bodies were thudding onto the pavement as people jumped or fell
from ropes made out of bedsheets.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy had five flashbulbs _ four after one of them burst in the
chilly air. He took three pictures. Then, with his final flash, he
trained his lens on the mezzanine, where bodies were bouncing on
the awning and striking the marquee. He noticed a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked to me like she was holding onto a rope, trying to
climb down, and then she lost her grip,'' Hardy says. ``It didn't
look to me like she jumped.''
</P>
<P>
   He clicked the shutter.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to take any more pictures, he turned his attention to a
drugstore across Peachtree, where a fireman and police officer were
discussing whether to call the owner and get the first-aid supplies
inside. Hardy suggested they break down the door. When they
hestitated, he kicked in the plate glass himself and was promptly
arrested. The desk sergeant at the station booked and released him
almost as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy went back to Tech and developed his film in a darkroom at
the laboratory where he worked. It was about 6 a.m. when he saw the
image of a dark-haired woman in a free fall, her white panties
glaringly visible as her skirt billowed around her head.
Remembering his encounter with the newspaper photo editor, he
decided to call The Associated Press instead. The wire service's
Atlanta bureau paid him $300 (a $200 bonus came later) and
dispatched the dramatic picture around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In Buckhead, the father of the young woman Hardy had taken out
that weekend looked at his Journal. The photo _ captioned: ``Woman
Hurtles to Death in Winecoff Fire'' _ took more than a quarter of
the front page.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was that boy's name?'' he asked his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnold Hardy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it looks like he had quite a night after he left you.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few weeks, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the fire, Hardy went back to the drugstore and
paid the owner for the broken glass. ``He really blistered me,'' he
says. ``He said we should have called him, he would have been there
in an hour. An hour? People were dying in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner changed his tune a week later in court. Hardy's
photograph had made him a minor celebrity by then, and an AP
reporter and cameraman accompanied him as he faced a complaint of
breaking and entering. The owner told the judge that he wouldn't
dream of pressing charges against such a fine young man.
</P>
<P>
   THE `JUMPING LADY'
</P>
<P>
   AP thought it only fitting that Hardy investigate what had
happened to the woman in the photo. There was a critical patient at
Grady that some of the reporters thought had to be her. But when
Hardy arrived at the hospital to see her, he was met by an AP man
who had already shown her the picture and been told in no uncertain
terms that she was not the ``jumping lady,'' as the papers were
calling her. Hardy made no further effort to contact her.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, it was her.
</P>
<P>
   According to Heys, who co-wrote the book about the fire, the
woman was Daisy McCumber, a 41-year-old secretary at the Fulton Bag
and Cotton Mill (the scene of last year's big blaze in Atlanta).
She was not registered at the hotel but was spending the night
there with a girlfriend visiting from Florida. Heys and Goodwin
identified her from photos, contemporary accounts and interviews
with relatives and her nurse at Grady.
</P>
<P>
   McCumber never admitted it publicly. ``I think she was
embarrassed to have her underwear showing like that,'' Heys says.
``That would have been scandalous at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   McCumber's account of her fall differed from Hardy's
recollection. In 1953, she told a reporter about her struggles for
one of the many stories that have been written about Winecoff
survivors over the years. The photo never came up, but McCumber did
say that she had jumped from the 11th floor when she saw the flames
closing in. She wasn't sure how she landed.
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, Hardy received a letter from a New Jersey man who
said he had witnessed the moment. Claud Beckham said he had been
moonlighting downtown for Southern Bell when he heard the fire
engines, hurried to the Winecoff and saw McCumber's plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they took her away, she was breathing but bleeding
profusely,'' wrote Beckham (who died last spring). ``We were
certain that she wouldn't survive the ride to the hospital. The leg
that was straight down in your picture was almost totally broken
off at her ankle; her foot was hanging on by a small scrap of
skin.''
</P>
<P>
   McCumber suffered a broken back, broken pelvis, broken ribs, a
fractured hand, compound fractures of both legs and a brain injury.
She underwent numerous operations and eventually had a leg
amputated. ``I think I would rather die than go through all of it
again,'' she said 6 1/2 years after the fire.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't want to talk about it anymore when Heys tracked her
down for a 40th anniversary story in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   McCumber died in 1992 in Jacksonville, Fla., where she had lived
in a nursing home. The following year Heys and Goodwin identified
her in their book as the woman in the photograph.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Hardy could recall hearing her name.
</P>
<P>
   NO MORE PRIZES
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the fire, AP offered Hardy a job. He turned it
down. His whole attitude toward news photography was changing _ and
it wasn't just because of his suspicion that he'd never be able to
top himself. One incident did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an industrial fire in Atlanta,'' he says. ``I went
out there and hung around a while; there wasn't anything worth
shooting. But the next day my picture appeared in the paper with
some caption about the Winecoff photographer looking for another
prize.''
</P>
<P>
   Captions, always those damned captions.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy didn't want people to think of him as some kind of
ambulance-chaser. He retired his press card.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only pictures I've taken since then,'' he says, ``have
been family and vacations.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 1707EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
