<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Jan. 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A shift of the jet stream will bring some changes to the weather
pattern across the nation on Monday and during the rest of the
week. A series of potent disturbances will flood into the
Northwest, bringing windswept heavy rain to coastal sections and
heavy snow to the interior mountains. Meanwhile, a rapidly
developing storm will bring wet weather to the Northeast on Monday
with drier conditions arriving in its wake for the remainder of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a stream of moist Pacific air ahead of a cold front
will take aim on the Oregon coast, causing heavy rain in western
sections. As the moist air intercepts the Cascades, it will ascend
and cool, setting the stage for very heavy snow. Snow levels will
average near or slightly below pass level. Locally heavy snow will
also affect many west-facing slopes of the northern and central
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and scattered showers will stream into northern
California while southern sections stay mainly sunny and mild.
Farther east, air warming by compression upon descending the
eastern Rockies will bring mild, gusty winds to the Colorado Front
Range. As the wind weaves through the complex terrain, local gusts
near 70 mph are possible.
</P>
<P>
   A period of heavy rain will dampen sections of the Northeast on
Monday as low pressure over Ontario draws moisture from the
Atlantic Ocean into its circulation. The rain will reach the New
England seaboard by evening. Colder air sweeping around the low
will traverse the Great Lakes late Monday night and Tuesday,
bringing locally heavy snow squalls.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Uncertain Record
</P>
<P>
   Not a single snowflake has been recorded this season in the
official observations for Boston that are taken at Logan Airport.
Previously, the record for the latest date without any snow was
Dec. 22, 1998. However, there have been many reports of flurries
near the airport this season, some as early as Nov. 11. The
automated system that takes official observations may not be
sensitive enough to detect light flurries that are apparent to the
human eye. Observation systems have changed many times in the last
century, adding uncertainty to the direct comparison of weather
records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 1708EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000109.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ETAILERS-AD-COLUMN-2T     01-09 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETAILERS-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AGENCIES BRACING FOR INTERNET BUSINESS SHAKEOUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Mass., Ill., Ore., Mich., Ga.)  (rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Madison Avenue is bracing for the Internet version of
Darwinism, a winnowing process that could be called
SurvivaloftheFittest.com.
</P>
<P>
   After a record advertising blitz during the fourth quarter,
particularly among electronic commerce Web sites anxious to
stimulate holiday sales, agencies are wondering whether the new
year will bring a shakeout. The e-tailers that spent the most on
campaigns in mainstream national media did not necessarily attract
the most shoppers, according to preliminary data, a setback
threatening to jeopardize the continued flow of money from clients
to agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the Wild West, but now people are getting
educated,'' said Donny Deutsch, chairman and chief executive at
Deutsch Inc., which handles dot-com clients like Ashford.com,
Britannica.com, Expedia and MyFamily.com from its offices in New
York and Marina del Rey, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lessons are being learned,'' Deutsch added. ``And it's a lot
of learning.''
</P>
<P>
   One lesson involves timing. Many dot-coms, including
MyFamily.com, a geneology Web site, decided to wait until the first
quarter to introduce campaigns rather than add to the plethora of
ads that saturated television and radio, magazines and newspapers
in the weeks before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth quarter had a bunch of companies lighting their
solid rocket boosters, fueled by cheap venture capital, and hoping
to get into space,'' said Jay Walker, founder and vice chairman at
Priceline.com in Stamford, Conn., the auction Web site for airline
tickets, hotel rooms and groceries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, it was more like fireworks,'' he added, ``going a
thousand feet high and exploding instead of reaching orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the space race, Priceline.com waited until last week to
bring out its first corporate image advertising, a humorous
campaign by Hill, Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos in Boston, part of
the Interpublic Group of Companies. The commercials are centered on
the company's spokesman, the actor William Shatner, who spoofs his
erstwhile second career as a recording artist to warble corny
parody songs about Priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson involves so-called targeting, aiming ads more
precisely for improved efficiency and effectiveness. For instance,
there is an increase in the use of local media rather than more
extensive _ and expensive _ national pitches.
</P>
<P>
   To help generate awareness for Career Mosaic, an Internet job
search site (www.careermosaic.com), for example, ``we're looking at
newspapers in certain high-volume markets like New York, Chicago
and San Francisco,'' said Diane Epstein, group account director at
the company's agency, Merkley Newman Harty in New York, part of the
Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to focus initially on our core markets,'' she added,
referring to an upbeat campaign carrying the theme ``Happy in a
career. Happy in life,'' which began on Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of targeting is a change in plans by Stamps.com,
which is shifting from general market advertising to more narrowly
focused appeals to the small-office and home-office consumers most
likely to buy postage over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company moved its account, with billings
estimated at $15 million, to Draft Worldwide in Chicago, an
Interpublic agency that specializes in direct marketing, from
Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore., which created a tongue-in-cheek
general campaign that featured the comedian Bob Newhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loved the work Wieden &AMP; Kennedy did,'' said Chris Hylen,
chief marketing officer at Stamps.com in Santa Monica, Calif. ``It
took us from nowhere to the 65th-most trafficked site on the
Internet and worked very effectively in saying who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we felt we needed to be more direct,'' he added,
``with a mix of direct-response television, the type of ``1-800''
commercials that Draft does for marketers like American Express;
targeted marketing events in big cities, and online partnerships
with AOL and Quicken.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson from the fourth quarter dot-com deluge is that
haste often makes waste, as in hastily rushing a campaign into the
market can waste precious ad dollars. So Internet marketers are now
testing elements of their campaigns before exposing them widely to
potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking it slow,'' said Arley Baker, corporate
communications director at Earthlink Networks in Pasadena, Calif.,
an Internet service provider scheduled to start its first national
campaign on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Commercials and billboards by the Los Angeles office of BBDO
West, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group, were
tested ``in a dozen markets for four months,'' he added, ``to make
sure our message is fine tuned before going out on a national
basis.'' The test results included increased awareness of the
Earthlink brand and additional sign ups for its Internet access
service.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the campaign to run through this month, ``then
we'll go back to see how it does,'' Baker said. ``If everything in
our first flight goes well, we have the potential to spend $50
million to $60 million over the coming year.''
</P>
<P>
   Another dot-com that tested its campaign was AutoTrader.com, a
Web site for buying and selling used cars, which will start
advertising on Jan. 30 with a commercial by Doner in Southfield,
Mich., to run during Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We did an extensive amount of pretesting prior to
production,'' said Clark Wood, vice president for marketing at
AutoTrader.com in Atlanta, ``and we were extremely pleased with the
results.'' The tests included briefly running the Super Bowl spot
last month on cable television, then benching it until Super
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIV is to have the most dot-com sponsors ever,
despite the highest prices ever for commercial time _ up to an
average of $3 million for each 30-second spot. The list includes
AutoTrader.com, Britannica.com, Computer.com, Hotjobs.com,
MicroStrategy, Monster.com and Pets.com.
</P>
<P>
   One or two dot-coms that identified themselves in the last
couple of months as Super Bowl advertisers _ including
Angeltips.com, an online marketplace for entrepreneurs _ have since
reversed course, announcing they would back out of the game. That
led to speculation the Darwinian struggle is intensifying, claiming
its most visible victims _ with perhaps more to come.
</P>
<P>
   But pulling out of the Super Bowl is not easy. The dot-coms were
told months ago by ABC _ the network owned by the Walt Disney Co.
that will broadcast the game _ that they would have to pay in
advance for time bought during the Super Bowl. And the process by
which the sponsor lineup changes is complicated. The network has to
agree to release advertisers from their commitments; they cannot
simply try to resell the commercial time on their own.
</P>
<P>
   For all programming on ABC, ``we're writing more and more
dot-com business through the first quarter,'' said Marv Goldsmith,
president for sales and marketing at the ABC Television Network in
New York, ``the quarter that's traditionally the softest in network
television.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're already getting feelers for the second quarter,'' he
added, ``though we're not ready to release inventory yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmmmm. Perhaps all the dot-coms that waited for the cluttered
fourth quarter to end before opening their wallets are going to
produce another cluttered quarter or two as 2000 begins.
</P>
<P>
   Roll over, Darwin, and tell Madison Avenue the news?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
