<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ALTERNATIVE-PAPERS-ME     01-09 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-PAPERS-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITALISM FINDS VALUE IN THE OLD VOICES OF THE COUNTERCULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were to reconstruct the 1999 to-do list of The Nashville
Scene's editor and publisher _ two 40-something Southerners who
have invested passion and an undisclosed amount of cash in the
small alternative weekly _ it would read something like this:
</P>
<P>
   _ Badger the town's lone daily, The Tennessean.
</P>
<P>
   _ Let the prize-winning investigative reporter loose on another
local institution (maybe the police, now that he has shaken up a
major nonprofit hospital).
</P>
<P>
   _ Collect advertisements from Exit/In, the Bluebird Cafe, 328
Performance Hall and other clubs featuring singer-songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy a stake in some other newspapers. (Try Lexington, Ky., and
New Orleans. Maybe The Village Voice?)
</P>
<P>
   By last week, the publisher, Albert Del Favero Jr., and the
editor, Bruce Dobie, could check off every item. Well, almost.
Margot DuBos, owner of Gambit Weekly in New Orleans, said she was
having too much fun to sell. But if they lost New Orleans, they
gained a piece of New York's Village Voice.
</P>
<P>
   By joining David Schneiderman, the publisher of The Voice, and
Arthur Howe, the former publisher of Philadelphia's City Paper, as
owners of The Voice and the five other Stern Publishing weeklies,
the two Tennesseans have become bit players in the crowd scene of
media investors, and among those who believe that alternative
weeklies, perennial prodigals, are reservoirs of value.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, alternative newspapers have changed hands in
Hartford, St. Louis, Cleveland, Kansas City and Lafayette, La. _
and that was before Stern Publishing was sold. After years of being
accused of selling out by their passionate, political writers and
readers, many publishers of alternative weeklies are basking in the
comforts of capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the times, but the cash-flow multiples, that are
a-changin'. ``You have a whole bunch of money in private equity
looking for a home,'' said Robert Broadwater, a managing director
at the investment banking firm of Veronis, Suhler &AMP; Associates.
``These people have decided that media properties are good
investment vehicles. You have recurring revenue and predictable
cash flow.''
</P>
<P>
   The sassy fringe of the newspaper industry is now getting
attention. Some alternatives have profit margins that can match
those of some dailies: margins at The L.A. Weekly and City Pages in
Minneapolis exceed 20 percent, according to their owners; The
Village Voice's margins are about 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   They have the kind of young, educated audiences coveted by
advertisers, music companies in particular. ``Say you want to
target a college market'' that might be interested in alternative
rock, said Fran Aliberte, executive vice president for sales at
WEA, the distribution arm of Time Warner Inc.'s Warner Music Group.
``You're talking about Static X, Owelsey, artists like that.'' The
weeklies ``target those albums to the people that we feel will be
the early adopters of those artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Put that kind of advertising together with ads for extreme
sports contests, body piercers and futon stores, and it adds up to
about $450 million in annual advertising revenue _ double the
amount five years ago, according to Richard Karpel, president of
the Association of Alternative Newsweeklies.
</P>
<P>
   That is just 1 percent of the estimated $45 billion that
advertisers spent on daily newspapers in 1999. But supporters of
alternative papers are just as irreverent about the business of
daily newspapers as their columnists are about daily journalism.
Pointing to a drop in dailies' circulation (down 10 percent the
last decade, to 56.1 million from 62.3 million), Howe said: ``What
other business franchise loses that many of its core customers
every year? It tells me something is broke.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the circulation of alternatives is up from three
million in 1990 to more than seven million in 1999. The Association
of Alternative Newsweeklies had 64 members in 1990; this year, it
has 120.
</P>
<P>
   This activity has attracted some attention in the financial
community. The money-management firm of Weiss, Peck &AMP; Greer and the
Canadian bank CIBC chipped in a large portion of the more than $150
million paid for the Stern properties.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Mindich, the publisher and chairman of the Phoenix
Media/Communications Group, said the alternatives' lucrative niche
is their lure. ``We have, collectively, been able to deliver to our
constituency what they want,'' he said, adding that advertisers and
investors are accepting the notion that free newspapers have value.
</P>
<P>
   Broadwater, who handled the sale for Stern, agreed.
``Historically, free circulation was denigrated,'' he said. ``But I
believe free circulation is a growing trend across all media. The
Web is training the next generation that you don't pay for
content.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DuBos, publisher of Gambit Weekly, said last week that more
than 100 outlets in New Orleans want regular deliveries of the free
paper _ requests she cannot yet fulfill.
</P>
<P>
   Given her reception in New Orleans, she started another Gambit
Weekly in Baton Rouge last year. Mindich has created local versions
of his Boston Phoenix in Portland, Me., Worcester, Mass., and
Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lacey does not buy his newspapers in one region but
wherever he finds them. Then he often makes major changes. Lacey,
executive editor of The New Times Inc., the largest chain of
alternatives with 11 newspapers, has also alienated some in the
industry who feel he has a buy-and-fire ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey, however, points to a recent purchase, The Riverfront
Times in St. Louis, and says, ``All the writers and editors are
still there.'' He added, ``What we did was come in and expand the
staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Now mainstream newspaper companies are in the mix. A Lafayette,
La., weekly, The Times of Acadiana, was sold last year to The
Advertiser, the town's daily, which is owned by Thomson Newspapers.
The Hartford Advocate and four nearby weeklies were sold to Times
Mirror's Hartford Courant.
</P>
<P>
   The question, Karpel said, is whether new owners can maintain a
weekly's local feel. As Dobie of Nashville said, ``In Chicago, what
has worked is an extraordinarily literary narrative style. In
Nashville, what works is serious news stories. In San Francisco, it
is' `Katy bar the door, we're going to napalm City Hall.' The term
alternative. means we are going to write and edit a product that
works in our market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
