<HEADER>
A0951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CONSUMER-SHOW10-COX     01-09 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-SHOW10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plastic pooch hot dog at electronics show
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ At an electronics show featuring displays from
15,000 manufacturers, engineers, software developers, importers and
distributors, perhaps the most popular booth featured a toy: Sony's
AIBO robot dog.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 International Consumer Electronics Show wrapped up
Saturday after drawing about 90,000 people to the Las Vegas
Convention Center to display and view products for the consumer
electronics market.
</P>
<P>
   While the show featured the latest in home entertainment,
computing, telephone products, electronics for cars and just about
everything else run by electricity, attendees said they didn't see
anything startlingly new or groundbreaking. Most of the products
displayed were variations and advancements on products already on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, I haven't seen anything really new,'' said Vic
Jones, who runs a home theater company in Ontario. ``I've basically
been looking at smaller niche items I can add to the lines we're
already carrying.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of break-out products to stir their imaginations,
many show attendees gathered around a Sony display to watch a
demonstration of Sony's AIBO, a plastic pooch that interacts with
its owners and other objects. Sony says the robot dog, which sells
for about $2,500, learns from its environment so that each dog is
unique.
</P>
<P>
   Though this year's electronics show didn't produce any
blockbuster product introductions, attendees found lots to talk
about.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the hottest topics were networking and the exploding
interest in music that can be downloaded in digital form from the
Internet. Speakers and panelists at the electronics show agreed
that the next bug push in home electronics will be in
``convergence,'' which means bringing different types of devices
together in systems so they can work with one another.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that a person who has a computer in one room should
be able to use the computer to set a video recorder in another
room, for example. Or someone with an electronic personal organizer
should be able to get the organizer to interact with a telephone
made by a different manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The big mystery of convergence is how the communication between
devices will be handled. There are several competing designs for
communication systems and no one seems to know which will become
dominant or if they all will coexist and cooperate in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Among the competing device connection systems being promoted are
the specialized wiring format called IEEE 1394 (also known as
firewire), radio frequency devices that communicate over short
distances using radio waves, and Universal Plug and Play formats
that use existing Internet formats to link devices.
</P>
<P>
   Portable MP3 players started showing up at last year's Consumer
Electronics Show, but this year they were everywhere. MP3 is a
technology that allows users to download music files from the
Internet for storage in digital form. The idea is popular with
young adults who use it to download and swap their favorite tunes.
Casio devoted one of the largest, loudest displays in the show to
promote its new line of wrist audio players. Computer peripheral
specialist, Creative Technology, won a Popular Mechanics design
award for its Nomad Jukebox, an MP3 player with enough memory to
store 100 hours of CD-quality music. But even the MP3 craze may not
last, according to Creative. The company has introduced a new
portable MP3 player that can be upgraded later if better ways to
download music take hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``MP3 just became popular in the last year or two, but it's
really 10-year-old technology,'' said Thong Le, a marketing
associate with Creative. ``There are already other ways that could
be used to download music faster in files that don't take up as
much storage space as MP3.''
</P>
<P>
   Other trends and developments apparent at this year's Consumer
Electronics Show were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Digital television is continuing to build but hasn't nearly
peaked. Most broadcast television signals are sent in analog form,
but satellite systems and cable providers are starting to provide
digital broadcasts. Networks like CBS and ABC are to carry digital
signals within six years. The Consumer Electronics Association,
show sponsors, said digital television sales reached 120,000 in
1999 and will reach 600,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Single-use devices are coming back. The personal computer is
the ultimate multi-use device, but because it tries to do just
about everything, it can be complicated to use. The next wave will
be simpler devices that do one thing well, such as small consoles
that send and receive e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ E-commerce is maturing. It became clear during the recent
Christmas shopping season that American consumers are becoming
comfortable shopping online. The consumer electronics industry is
moving quickly to shore up that business by offering things like
repair services and warranties geared to Internet buyers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Everything is smaller, faster and cheaper. Though brand new
concepts were scarce this year at the electronics show, there were
plenty of examples of improvements on old products. Digital
cameras, high definition televisions, DVD players and other
recently introduced categories are becoming affordable to the
typical middle class family. And established categories, such as
video recorders, are selling for a fraction of their original
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
