<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMCRITICS-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIE FOR BEST FILM, A FIRST FOR THE CRITICS' SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Being John Malkovich,'' the quirky comedy directed by Spike
Jonze, and ``Topsy-Turvy,'' Mike Leigh's loving 19th-century
backstage drama, shared the award for best picture handed out on
Saturday by the National Society of Film Critics. It was the first
time in the society's 34 years that two films had tied for the
award, reflecting what voters felt was an unusually strong field of
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The society, made up of 53 movie critics from New York, Los
Angeles and other cities, had less of a struggle voting for a best
director, giving the prize to Leigh. David O. Russell took second
place for his work on ``Three Kings,'' a dark comedy about three
soldiers during the final days of the Gulf War. Sam Mendes, a
first-time director whose ``American Beauty'' is considered a
strong Oscar contender, won third place, though the film's
cinematographer, Conrad L. Hall, won the society's top prize for
his lush, rose-dappled visuals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the nod for best picture, ``Being John
Malkovich'' was cited for best screenplay. Written by Charlie
Kaufman, the film follows the story of a puppeteer who discovers a
magical portal that allows adventurers briefly to enter the mind of
the actor John Malkovich. Second place was given to ``Election,''
by Alexander Payne and Jim Taylor, for their political satire set
in a suburban high school.
</P>
<P>
   The men's acting awards were dominated by one film: ``The
Insider,'' a drama about CBS News' handling of a potentially
explosive story on the tobacco industry. Russell Crowe, a handsome
leading man whose physical transformation into a downtrodden,
besieged tobacco executive impressed many critics, won best actor.
Runners up included Jim Broadbent, who played the prudish composer
William S. Gilbert in ``Topsy-Turvy,'' and Kevin Spacey, who
starred as a rebellious middle-aged father in ``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Best Supporting Actor award was won by Christopher Plummer
for his portrayal of the CBS newscaster Mike Wallace in ``The
Insider.'' Plummer edged out Philip Seymour Hoffman, the ubiquitous
young character actor who placed second for his roles in both ``The
Talented Mr. Ripley'' and ``Magnolia.'' In third place was another
young talent, 11-year-old Haley Joel Osment, who played an eerily
unsettled boy in ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In women's roles, Reese Witherspoon won a small upset by winning
best actress for her depiction of an overeager climber in
``Election.'' The runner-up was Hilary Swank in ``Boys Don't Cry,''
a film about a real-life Nebraska girl, Brandon Teena, whose
gender-bending led to her rape and murder; Ms. Swank played Ms.
Teena and has often been mentioned as a leading Oscar candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Chloe Sevigny, who played Ms. Swank's love interest in ``Boys
Don't Cry,'' was voted best supporting actress. Julianne Moore was
second in that category for her work in four separate films,
including ``Magnolia'' and ``Cookie's Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   The society has a history of unorthodox votes _ it selected the
sexy thriller ``Out of Sight'' as last year's best film _ and its
assessment of the year's best foreign-language film was no
exception. In a close vote the society selected ``Autumn Tale,''
directed by Eric Rohmer, as the best film, over ``The Dreamlife of
Angels,'' by Erick Zonca. Dropped into third place, however, was
``All About My Mother,'' by the Spanish filmmaker Pedro Almodovar,
which has been an almost unanimous choice as best foreign film by
other film societies, including the New York Film Critics Circle
and the Los Angeles Film Critics Association.
</P>
<P>
   In nonfiction films, the group selected ``Buena Vista Social
Club,'' a look at Cuban musicians, directed by Wim Wenders, as the
year's best, followed by ``Mr. Death: The Rise and Fall of Fred A.
Leuchter Jr.,'' directed by Errol Morris. ``Mr. Death,'' about an
execution expert who becomes an unlikely Holocaust denier, was
followed by ``American Movie,'' a look at a would-be filmmaker
whose big screen dreams are thwarted by his low-rent life. It was
directed by Chris Smith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
