<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RETHINKING-CRITICISM-     01-09 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETHINKING-CRITICISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISIONS COLUMN: CRITICS SHOULD LOOK AT ART BUT ALSO AT
THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms)  
By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a critic, what do you most want to see happen this year,
someone asked me during the holidays? Whereupon I began to
formulate what I hoped would be an eloquent response, both analytic
and prophetic, only to be stopped short. No, my friend said, I mean
what as a critic would you like to change about the way you and
critics in general work? How you think, feel and write?
</P>
<P>
   I'd start by saying that I'd like us to ask questions as
vehemently as we sling judgments. We're still inclined to believe
that critical authority comes mostly from assertion or virtuoso
displays of intellectual mastery. What about intelligent questions
asked forthrightly? What about admitting sometimes that we're not
sure we're asking all that needs to be asked? And what about
ambivalence? Well expressed ambivalence is as interesting in
criticism as mixed motives in fiction or microtones in music.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism is supposed to be a kind of adult education. And it's
not just the readers who are to be educated (and entertained and
unsettled and even moved). Sometimes, given a short deadline or a
new subject, you have to cram the way you used to cram for exams.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than that now. The amount of cultural material
that comes our way _ trash, treasures, ephemera, alien matter _ is
overwhelming. New forms pop up. Old, even ancient traditions we
once knew nothing about are suddenly center stage. We've all had a
particular kind of intellectual training. We've inherited canons
and then lovingly constructed our own personal cultures.
</P>
<P>
   And like most adults (audiences, scholars and plenty of
artists), we're not necessarily eager to re-educate ourselves. It
takes time to study some discipline that didn't exist 20 years ago
when you were on the cutting edge of things. And it takes nerve to
expose yourself to the uncertainties, the humiliations even, of
learning new ways of reading, seeing and listening. Learning is as
much a process of surrender as of mastery.
</P>
<P>
   Our devices of resistance include the well wrought sneer,
complete with thesaurus-worthy adjectives and literary references.
There's the ``Aren't I witty, detached and generally more fun than
what I'm writing about?'' stance. There's the high-rhetoric
denunciation, bolstered with theories about civilization's
debasement and accounts of one's own lonely, valiant struggle to
uphold certain values. And there's the ``Ah, but how undisciplined
and ultimately how boring'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   Read closely whenever you see the word ``boring'' used by a
critic, including me, who has just encountered new or deliberately
unsettling material (the ``Sensation'' show at the Brooklyn Museum
of Art, say, or a culturally foreign foreign movie). Sometimes
boredom is just boredom. But ``boring'' is a smoke-screen word,
too, as when people loftily declare that they find pornography
boring. This is sex-crazed America, for heaven's sake. What are the
odds that most people's first response to pornography is sheer
boredom?
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time the culture was more cohesive and more
exclusionary. A critic could be like an actor who played the same
character week after week in a series. The specifics changed but
the framework stayed pretty much the same. Now if you write for a
newspaper or magazine with a reasonably wide readership, your
position keeps shifting around.
</P>
<P>
   Take the term ``popular music.'' Preposterously enough, it is
now supposed to include jazz, folk, gospel, some new music and some
world music. (``Classical,'' despite efforts to extend it to jazz
and some new music, still holds fast to its traditional
boundaries.) Never mind that composers on all fronts have sampled
one another's goods and raided one another's turf for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Most critics have a specialty, an art music they know intimately
and love passionately. How do they write, as they periodically do,
about forms they enjoy but give less time and thought to? If you
are an opera fan, how do you listen to jazz singers, and vice
versa? What standards do you judge them by? What bias (or
ignorance) marks your listening? When does the personal _ age, sex,
ethnicity, where you grew up and what you grew up listening to _
shape what you present as objective criticism? How do you write
``objectively'' about music meant to be danced to when you are too
old to want to dance to it or to look good dancing to it? (I know I
must have liked singers as silly as Christina Aguilera when I was
as young as she and her fans are. I just cannot remember their
names at the moment.)
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, in the 1970s, I accepted an assignment from Ms.
magazine to write about Dolly Parton and her success in moving from
the country and western ghetto to mass market popularity. I decided
to use the piece to learn more about country and western music than
I'd ever been willing to before. With the help of more
knowledgeable friends, I gave myself a music seminar, starting in
the 1920s and moving up to the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   I was an outsider to the music, being Northern, urban, bourgeois
and black. And to my surprise, for I thought myself above such
failings, I responded with exactly that blend of excitement and
condescension I had spent years lambasting in certain white blues
and soul-music critics. I cared only for the purest, the simplest
and, therefore, most heartfelt music. The closer the singers and
instrumentalists got to Nashville, to big studio arrangements and
songs that had something in common with Tin Pan Alley pop, the more
appalled and disdainful I became.
</P>
<P>
   I felt pity, too. These people were poor and working class, so
of course arrangements larded with violins plus a lessening of that
authentic rural twang would appeal: they represented upward social
and musical mobility. I had heard sentiments like these before,
when some critic would bemoan those violins that Charlie Parker and
Billie Holiday insisted on recording with, or when they declared
that middle-class aspirations in soul music (a voice too sweet, a
style too embellished) were bogus and unappealing.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this rather mortifying cultural education, I had
come to like some of those Nashville strings very much. Not all, of
course. But often all those Vivaldi violins drive me mad, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
