<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BUTTERFLY-BOOK-REVIEW     01-09 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTTERFLY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUTTERFLY ECONOMICS': WHEN ECONOMIC THEORY FAILS, CONSULT AN
INSECT
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where are those famous and irritating rational individuals of
classical economic theory who always maximize their own overall
well being or, in the jargon of the discipline, their ``utility''?
Nowhere, says Paul Ormerod in his useful and sensible new book,
``Butterfly Economics: A New General Theory of Social and Economic
Behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Such individuals don't exist, argues Ormerod, who has been head
of the economic assessment unit at The Economist and a visiting
professor at the Universities of London and Manchester and whose
first book was ``The Death of Economics.'' For one thing, few
people possess the skills to act completely rationally. More
important, he says, people are not isolated machines with fixed
tastes but rather social organisms who interact with and are
influenced by other individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Hence humans act unpredictably, Ormerod continues. At Christmas
they flock after toys like Cabbage Patch dolls or Nintendo Gameboys
in numbers that no manufacturer can anticipate. They turn films
like ``Anaconda'' and ``The Full Monty'' into unexpected hits. They
choose inferior technologies like VCRs and QWERTY keyboards over
superior alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   They drive up the price of stocks and currencies irrationally.
They become criminals in times of affluence and go straight when
times are bad. Their patterns of marriage and fertility often have
nothing to do with the economic conditions that theoretically ought
to influence them.
</P>
<P>
   How do we model the behavior of such creatures? Ormerod
illustrates how economists have been trying for a century or more,
vainly assuming that individuals have fixed tastes and live in
economies that operate like machines. Most egregiously, these
economists have failed to put their models to empirical tests, with
the inevitable result that the models have proved inadequate for
predicting.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Butterfly Economics'' Ormerod introduces a new kind of
model based on a view of society as a living organism and
underpinned by the mathematics of nonlinear probability. As he
writes, his image of the butterfly ``draws upon popular ideas of
chaos theory, in which the beating of the wings of a butterfly can
in principle cause a tornado on the other side of the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   His central image is based on a series of experiments with ants
carried out in the mid-1980s by entomologists. Two food sources
were placed equidistant from and on opposite sides of a nest and
kept equal in size no matter how much the ants took from each.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the experiments there was, by design, absolutely no reason
for the ants to prefer one of the sources to the other,'' Ormerod
writes, ``so we might start by expecting that the ants would split
evenly between them.'' But instead, partly because ants can signal
one another as to where food sources lie, the distribution
fluctuated wildly, even swinging at times from an 80:20 ratio to a
20:80 one. And when an economist modeled the behavior of the
colony, the resulting graph oscillated unpredictably in a pattern
resembling the fluctuations of a business cycle plotted over many
decades.
</P>
<P>
   But what do ants really have to do with the behavior of economic
man? Plenty, Ormerod argues. After showing how conventional
economic models have failed either to explain or predict how
industrial growth has been achieved in the West, he builds a
simplified model based on the principles of the ant experiment,
using companies instead of ants. And while the model doesn't
explain why growth occurs in a functioning economy, it reproduces
the pattern of that growth with an accuracy surpassing any
classical model, even suggesting why industrial growth in the
United States has surpassed that of any other region in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butterfly Economics'' is written for ``members of the general
public,'' as the author puts it. It is accessible and even
entertaining, avoiding the mathematics on which its ideas are based
(except in the appendices), although at times in his effort to be
lightly anecdotal Ormerod wanders somewhat far from the point.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance he proves his point a little too effectively.
Illustrating how people are generally ill-equipped to make rational
economic judgments, he introduces what he calls the Monty Hall
problem, in which a game-show contestant is asked to choose among
three doors, behind two of which are rubber ducks. Behind the third
is $10,000. When the contestant picks door A, the host, knowing
where the money lies, opens door C, revealing a rubber duck. The
contestant is then given the option of sticking with door A or
switching to door B.
</P>
<P>
   While most people stay with A, the correct strategy is to switch
to B because, Ormerod reasons: ``There is a 1 in 3 chance of the
money being behind door A, and a 2 in 3 chance of it being behind B
and C together. If you know there is zero chance of it being behind
C _ because Monty has opened it up for you _ then there is a 2 in 3
chance of it being behind B.''
</P>
<P>
   Can this really be the case? No wonder the problem tends, in
Ormerod's words, ``to lead otherwise sane and rational citizens to
the heights of frenzied argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in every other respect ``Butterfly Economics'' is
penetratingly lucid. It argues with particular strength that
governments ought to stop trying to control and predict what they
can't and start concentrating instead on enhancing the process by
which markets make important decisions, or, in the terms of
Ormerod's informing experiment, how ants choose to go to one food
source or the other.
</P>
<P>
   Ormerod even illuminates to what extent Marx was wrong in
predicting the end of capitalism's growth, and why Marx's mother,
in an anecdote the author insists is true, wrote to a relative,
``If only little Karl had made some capital rather than just
writing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ormerod not only writes about capital, but also points to a way
it may at last be understood.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BUTTERFLY ECONOMICS: A New General Theory of Social and
Economic Behavior'
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Ormerod.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated with Diagrams. 217 pages. Pantheon Books. $24. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
