<HEADER>
A0979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-METROPOLITAN-MUSEUM-F     01-09 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METROPOLITAN-MUSEUM-FUNDS-ART-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN MUSEUM EXPANDS FUND RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the Metropolitan Museum of Art's ambitions have
grown, the target of its fund-raising drive, which in 1994 was set
at $300 million, has ratcheted higher and higher. With an
announcement to be made Monday, the Met has more than doubled its
goal, to $650 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Met's initial fund-raising campaign was for construction
work that included renovating and expanding its Greek and Roman
galleries and establishing a $100 million endowment for curatorial,
educational and conservation projects. In 1997 the museum increased
its goal to $400 million to expand the Greek and Roman galleries
project, among other endeavors, as well as to increase the museum's
endowment.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the museum is to announce that it hopes to raise
another $250 million for further renovations and investments, for a
total of $650 million.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe de Montebello, director of the Met, said that $450
million had been raised, including $50 million that had been
dedicated to the latest effort.
</P>
<P>
   Since the museum cannot expand into Central Park because of an
agreement it made with the city in the 1970s, it has been scouring
its building for air shafts and stairwells, neglected storage rooms
and unused areas surrounding skylights _ any scrap of overlooked
space _ that could be used to enlarge a gallery or create a new
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a campaign of ingenuity,'' de Montebello said.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a campaign that for the first time in the museum's
history includes $50 million earmarked only for acquisitions. Since
1997, when the museum was hard hit by the loss of more than $10
million from Reader's Digest Association stock dividends, 25
percent of which were budgeted for acquisitions, the Met has been
looking for alternative sources of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a good chunk of acquisitions money, which is the
lifeblood of the place,'' said John Rosenwald Jr., vice chairman of
the museum and executive chairman of its fund-raising campaign.
``It has deflated the myth that the Met is huge and rich and
doesn't need anything.''
</P>
<P>
   New York state has contributed $6.1 million for projects like
the Greek and Roman galleries. The city has committed $14.8 million
toward those galleries and projects like a new Center for Imaging
and Photography.
</P>
<P>
   For the newly broadened campaign the city has committed another
$30 million for rehabilitating the Great Hall, cleaning and
relighting the facade, redesigning the exterior fountains, doing
structural work on the Egyptian wing, and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   One of the campaign's biggest undertakings will move the
restaurant from the south side of the museum to the terrace along
Central Park at the western edge of the glassed-in Charles
Englehard Court, which is part of the American Wing.
</P>
<P>
   The former restaurant area will become a Roman sculpture court,
following a plan from 1910, when the museum opened that portion of
the building. (In April the Met opened its 140-foot-long
neoclassical barrel-vaulted Greek galleries along the south
corridor of the Great Hall.)
</P>
<P>
   Plans also call for preservation work on the Cloisters, the
Metropolitan's branch for medieval art in Fort Tryon Park, made
from the reconstituted remnants of centuries-old chapels,
cathedrals and monasteries from Spain and France. The building,
which suffers from water damage, needs to be stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an urgent need,'' de Montebello said. ``It can't be
delayed any longer without risking the works of art.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many places in the Met now being refurbished had not been
touched for decades. The Great Hall, or lobby, was last redesigned
in 1968, when the museum had fewer than 2 million visitors a year;
it now must accommodate more than 5 million a year. For the last
three months the museum has been repositioning the admissions and
information desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're experimenting with different configurations to see how
they work,'' de Montebello said. ``The idea is to keep it
uncluttered and very user-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   In looking for space for new galleries, museum officials
discovered all kinds of forgotten places, like a storage area for
European metalworks beneath the Great Stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went down there, I realized it's a turn-of-the-century
arched, all-brick space that looks like a crypt in a Byzantine
church,'' de Montebello said. The space will become an additional
Byzantine gallery. ``Demolition has already started,'' he added.
``We're leaving the bricks exposed. It will be a magical, romantic
place when it opens later this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grace Rainey Rogers Auditorium, where thousands of museum
visitors come each week for concerts and lectures, has not been
renovated since 1954. Plans include upgrading the acoustics,
installing new lighting and sound-system equipment and replacing
the seating and stage floor.
</P>
<P>
   By using former air shafts the museum plans to enlarge and
renovate its Thomas J. Watson Library. Designed in 1965 for what
was then a collection of 300,000 books, catalogs and periodicals,
the library would expand into a courtyard next to its reading room
to accommodate its 450,000 titles and a new electronic resource
center providing access to other museums worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never-ending,'' de Montebello said. ``By the time we
finish this, we'll have to start all over again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
