u f BC-L.A.TIMES-EDITOR-MEDI     01-09 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.TIMES-EDITOR-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. TIMES PROMOTES EDITOR WHO CRITICIZED PROFITS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of the rebellion in the newsroom of The Los Angeles
Times after the disclosure of its profit-sharing agreement with the
Staples Center sports arena, Michael Parks, the newspaper's editor,
has given day-to-day responsibility for the paper to one of the
critics of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Wolinsky, who had been one of four managing editors, was
promoted to executive editor. The announcement was greeted with
applause when announced last Friday, said Henry Weinstein, a Times
reporter. Wolinsky will have ``overall responsibility for The
Times' newsroom operations,'' a news release said.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Wolinsky said the changes were ``the
result of Michael's introspection following Staples.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not just Staples,'' he added. ``It's his estimation
of everything we've seen since then and what's wrong with the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of the unusual arrangement to share with the
Staples Center the profits from an issue of the paper's Sunday
magazine devoted to the opening of the arena infuriated The Times'
newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of their fury was summed up by John Morton, an
industry analyst, who wrote recently that the deal broke two
newspaper ``golden rules.'' First, that ``readers should always
know what is and is not for sale in the newspaper.'' Second, that
``a newspaper should never have an economic, political or other
interest in enterprises or institutions that are subject to news
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks had been widely criticized for failing to scuttle the
agreement, to kill the Sunday magazine or to inform readers of the
arrangement. According to both Wolinsky and Weinstein, Parks told
the staff last Friday that he had considered resigning in recent
weeks but had rejected the idea, saying he thinks he can play a
positive role.
</P>
<P>
   In a long reconstruction of the events surrounding the Staples
Center deal, The Times' media critic, David Shaw, quoted Parks as
saying, ``I underestimated the impact of the Staples arrangement on
our credibility, on the journalistic ethos that we foster, on our
standing in the community and in the profession. And for all those
things, I have profound regret.''
</P>
<P>
   The news release said Parks had also appointed Ardith Hilliard,
the editor of the newspaper's San Fernando Valley edition, as
associate editor and assistant to the editor. She will be
responsible in part for ensuring that the newspaper's new set of
guidelines for contacts between the business and editorial sides of
the paper are followed.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last Friday, Wolinsky said the Staples Center
controversy ``made us look at the basic values of journalism in the
newsroom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really in a back-to-basics mode here,'' Wolinsky said.
``All these other concerns about increasing revenues and developing
new products _ that's fine for the paper. It's not fine for the
newsroom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
