u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      01-09 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Monday, Jan. 10. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS-II (Tijuana, Mexico) _ Second of two parts on how
drugs and crime have corrupted Mexico. By Tim Golden.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-WEBBER (London) _ The British composer Andrew Lloyd
Webber won an international bidding war on Sunday for ten of
London's leading playhouses and variety halls in a $145-million
deal making him a dominant owner in the world's largest theater
district. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Duba-Yurt) _ Russia's acting president,
Vladimir Putin, may have suspended air and artillery strikes on
Grozny to mark Orthodox Christmas and the end of Ramadan, the
Muslim holiday. But there is no moratorium here. In fact, fighting
raged in Chechnya's mountains and lowlands on Sunday, as both sides
decided this was a perfect time to clash. Trying to turn the
Russian-controlled areas of Chechnya into a battlefield and destroy
the confidence of Russian troops, several hundred Islamic rebels
were reported to have surrounded the headquarters of the Russian
commandant in Argun, a town east of Grozny, which the Russians had
assumed they had under firm control. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   NY-OIL-WELLS (Bolivar, N.Y.) _ If they ever make a movie about
the oil producers of New York state, they would have to call it
``Midget.'' Some 135 years after the state's first oil started
flowing from a hole near here, the state's producers are trying to
suck the last drops from wells producing an average of a quarter of
a barrel a day. Now, the few hundred people still employed in the
industry face a threat they say could bring state oil production to
an end. Environmental authorities are requiring them to spend
thousands of dollars a well plugging holes that have been abandoned
for decades. The result is a collision between the heritage of the
industry's earliest days and the real-life environmental
consequences of the present.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-FINANCE (Washington) _ How he is handling the campaign
finance matter: flying straight into the political flak,
fighter-pilot style. By Alison Mitchell. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   SOLDIER-SENTENCE (Washington) _ The roommate of Private
Winchell, the gay soldier beaten to death at Fort Campbell, was
sentenced to 14 years in prison late Saturday for obstructing
justice. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
