<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-ROOSEVELT-REVIEW-N     01-09 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROOSEVELT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ELEANOR ROOSEVELT': THEY CALLED HER `ELEANOR,' AND HER STORY IS
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Time, channel are for New York area. Check local listings.
Program notes at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now the outlines of Eleanor Roosevelt's life and worthy works
are so well known that a television account of them, even at two
hours, promises little news. That expectation is fulfilled in
Monday night's ``American Experience,'' which tells the oft-told
story with due sympathy for a young woman's quest to find her own
strengths and with ample appreciation of how she used them.
Although unstartling, this affectionate biography should enhance
the reputation that Mrs. Roosevelt won over the decades and that
has survived in the years since her death in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up with a mother who was disappointed in her looks, her
shyness and her social prospects and with a father whose alcoholism
sent him to an asylum. Her potential was awakened at an English
boarding school where, Alfre Woodard, the narrator, says she was
``taught to be independent and politically aware.''
</P>
<P>
   Although her marriage in 1905 to the up-and-coming Franklin D.
Roosevelt was a love match, it brought his young wife under the
domination of his mother, Sara, a tough old bird who tried with
considerable success to run the young couple's lives. As children
came, the younger Mrs. Roosevelt found that being a mother was no
more fulfilling than being a daughter-in-law; working outside the
home in behalf of immigrants and the needy proved far more
rewarding. (Her record as a mother was not brilliant; her five
children managed to accumulate 19 marriages among them.)
</P>
<P>
   The much-explored peeks into Franklin Roosevelt's long affair
with Lucy Mercer, his wife's social secretary, and into Mrs.
Roosevelt's relationship with Lorena Hickok, an Associated Press
reporter, are covered with understanding for all parties and
discretion as to the details. As the program puts the situation
politely, after Mrs. Roosevelt learned of the Mercer affair, the
Roosevelts ``never lived together as husband and wife again.''
</P>
<P>
   But in other ways the two grew closer after Roosevelt was struck
by polio yet resolved to continue his political career. Whatever
the connubial restraints, the program assures us that they proved
to be ``extraordinary political partners.'' Mrs. Roosevelt became a
sort of ambassador for her husband and a player on her own, joining
in reform movements for many causes (including some, she would
discover, run by Communists), writing her famous newspaper column,
``My Day,'' and even endorsing products. (Her first client was the
Simmons Mattress Co.)
</P>
<P>
   She is credited here with orchestrating the recital of Marian
Anderson, the black contralto, at the Lincoln Memorial after the
Daughters of the American Revolution had denied her permission to
sing in Constitution Hall. It was a tribute to the breadth of Mrs.
Roosevelt's causes and the nature of her associations that she
attracted the attentions of J. Edgar Hoover. Her biographer,
Blanche Wiesen Cook, reports that the first lady's 3,000-page FBI
file reflected Hoover's intense dislike and suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of Roosevelt's death in 1945, his wife had long
since found her own voice. She traveled endlessly, headed the U.N.
committee to draft a Universal Declaration of Human Rights, opposed
Sen. Joseph McCarthy, campaigned for Adlai Stevenson and even had a
little-known late-life crush on a much younger man, Dr. David
Gurewitsch, to whom she wrote: ``What I have in the few years I
have left is yours before it is anyone else's.'' That was not to
be, but the affection and regard that she had won from the nation
endured.
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE AMERICAN EXPERIENCE: Eleanor Roosevelt'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A film by Ambrica Productions Inc. Judith Vecchione, executive
producer; written and directed by Sue Williams; produced by Kathryn
Dietz and Sue Williams; Alfre Woodard, narrator; Howard Sharp,
editor; Tom Phillips, music; Geoffrey C. Ward, senior creative
consultant. ``The American Experience'' is produced by WGBH/Boston.
Margaret Drain, executive producer; Mark Samels, senior producer;
David McCullough, series host.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000109.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0995 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-PBS-SCHEDULE-SFCHRON &LR;      01-09 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBS-SCHEDULE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS: PEOPLE BLUNDERING ON SCHEDULES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. &LR;   &LR; _ Any critics worth their bile are angry
about something by the time the midseason press tour rolls around,
so let's go beat up on Steven Gray, PBS vice president for
scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   The bone of contention is a real femur _ PBS' stubborn
insistence on running its best programs at the worst possible
times.
</P>
<P>
   Remember ``An American Love Story,'' all those hours about a
biracial family forever fixing breakfast? PBS carried it in
September, just as the commercial networks were flooding the
airwaves with their new, lavishly promoted, fervently reviewed
wares.
</P>
<P>
   Or ``Not for Ourselves Alone,'' the Ken Burns two-parter about
the rugged early days of the American feminist movement? PBS sailed
that one in the first hectic weekend of the November sweeps,
against corpulent miniseries on NBC and CBS and ABC's lovely remake
of ``Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to find the appropriate words for PBS' tactic. But
``insane'' is a good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``An American Love Story'' chugged along without provoking much
comment, and ``Not for Ourselves Alone'' rang up a 2.1 rating,
attracting 3 percent of the homes where TV sets were in use those
nights. It was the worst rating ever for a major Burns documentary,
about as popular as a Susan B. Anthony dollar.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, PBS found itself spitting into a gale. Then, right
after ``Not for Ourselves Alone,'' PBS tossed 10 hours of its ``New
York'' documentary saga onto the air, also in the teeth of the
November sweeps. The result was a 2.8 rating, which Gray insists
``isn't bad for public television.''
</P>
<P>
   But how many more people might have watched in, say, December,
when the commercial networks had embarked on their long winter's
naps. PBS has no need to strut itself for advertising advantage in
sweeps months. No one expects its member stations to shut down
their transmitters, but the public would be better served by a bare
minimum of common sense and programming acumen from the Public
Broadcasting Service.
</P>
<P>
   Gray was a spectator here in Pasadena as PBS' interim president,
John Swope, fielded routine questions from the press. As soon as
the Swope session ended, though, several critics made beelines for
Gray, their stingers locked in and loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Gray put up a defense. Not all major PBS programs air in
September or sweeps months, he said. PBS tries to schedule some
sort of event programming each month and doesn't want to turn timid
in the big sweeps months, November, February and May, when
commercial television audiences are measured to set advertising
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a sweeps period, we don't want to not be there,'' he
said. ``We don't want to be there with nothing but repeats, and we
don't want to be weak.''
</P>
<P>
   This argument didn't go far, so Gray pointed out that PBS
scheduling is ``not my decision alone. We're a consortium of
several hundred stations.'' Also, Gray said he's virtually helpless
in December, March, August and sometimes June, which are PBS pledge
months stocked with specially packaged self-help shows and concerts
_ ah, John Tesh _ adored by local PBS stations.
</P>
<P>
   We hadn't noticed previously that the PBS schedule was so
jam-packed with viewing delights, but never mind.
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested that the highest-profile PBS shows ought to be
set aside for pledge periods. Really bad idea. Imagine: we'll
return to ``The Civil War'' after 30 minutes of unbearable begging,
cajoling, wheedling, whining and shameless guilt trips from our
cash-starved member stations. No thanks.
</P>
<P>
   But PBS could still scour its schedule for more opportune nights
to showcase a Burns documentary, a lavish science series or an
``American Experience'' excursion into the life of a Douglas
MacArthur or Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Gray backed down enough to concede that ``I wish `Not for
Ourselves Alone' had not been on against sweeps competition. If we
had it to do over again today, things might be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think that through these experiences, we are learning,
and our member stations are learning, that we have windows of
opportunity we need to take better advantage of ... It's going to
be slow progress, the stations deciding they want to make a change
in the way we've traditionally gone about scheduling.''
</P>
<P>
   And with a conspiratorial wink, Gray suggested we watch to see
how Burns' next big project is scheduled. That presumably would be
his 20-hour history of jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds better. But when a PBS executive promises slow progress,
you can be assured it's a promise that will be kept. The ``slow''
part, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
