<SLUG> BC-COKE-MANAGEMENT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New head of Coke shuffles managment team
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola President Doug Daft continued his series of
management changes Sunday by announcing new executives to head the
company's Africa and Middle East operation and its Minute Maid Co.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Short, 46, will become president of the newly named
Africa and Middle East Group less than a week after Carl Ware was
promoted from heading the African operation to taking charge of the
newly created global public affairs and administration division.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Knauss, 48, will be the new president and chief executive
officer of Minute Maid, replacing Stephen Jones, who was named
Coke's chief marketing officer Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are swiftly taking steps to put in place the leadership
team that will take our business to new levels,'' Daft said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage Digest, said Daft
still has at least one other major issue to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question now is will he name a No. 2, when and who? My
expectation is we won't have long to wait to see those questions
answered,'' Sicher said.
</P>
<P>
   Sicher was referring to the naming of a president when Daft
leaves that job to become chairman and chief executive officer in
April. That's when the current chairman, M. Douglas Ivester, is
scheduled to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street expects Daft to give the No. 2 job to Jack Stahl,
who is currently in charge of the company's operations in North
America and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after Daft announced three major management changes
including Ware and Jones, he was rewarded with an 8 percent rise in
the company's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Knauss, who returns to Minute Maid after heading Coke's Southern
Africa division, will be replaced by Doug Jackson, 39.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, currently Daft's executive assistant, will report to
Short, who will now oversee all of Africa and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Two people will replace Short, who briefly headed the company's
Middle East and North Africa division after serving as president of
Coke's India division.
</P>
<P>
   John Guarino, 40, now will head the Middle East and North Africa
division. He also will report to Short.
</P>
<P>
   Alex von Behr, 40, becomes president of the India division. He
will report to Sandy Allan, recently appointed president of the
renamed Asia Pacific Group.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Allan will now have responsibility over Japan, one of the
company's most important markets. Previously, the head of the
company's Japanese operation reported directly to Daft.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
