<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECOMMERCE-MEASURING-N     01-09 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-MEASURING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT FIGURES WILL SHED LITTLE LIGHT   ON HOLIDAY ONLINE
SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Commerce Department will announce estimates of
U. S. retail sales for December, putting a solid number on the 1999
holiday sales season.
</P>
<P>
   Those wishing to gain a better sense of the e-commerce holiday
results _ to see if the E-Christmas lived up to all those
commercials _ are out of luck. Rather, policy makers, investors and
analysts will have to resort to their own crystal ball
formulations, cobbled together from shards of statistics and
economic assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   These are the mathematical gymnastics that produced pre-holiday
estimates of e-commerce sales ranging from $4 billion to $15
billion, a statistical chasm that has yet to close in the
post-holiday reporting.
</P>
<P>
   With so much attention focused on e-commerce in general, and
this holiday season's online results in particular, why is the
Commerce Department seemingly ignoring an area of such intense
public interest? The answer is that it is, in fact, developing a
means of tracking Web sales. But it is working on the issue at a
pace that does not exactly call to mind the phrase ``Internet
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Department officials say that in March, they will
release total e-commerce sales figures for the fourth quarter of
1999. That trickle of information will give the public at least a
general sense of holiday e-commerce sales, but officials said they
expected such reports to grow in scope and frequency in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all flying blind about the exact impact and breadth of
e-commerce,'' said William M. Daley, the secretary of commerce.
``So we're trying to respond quickly'' to the need for more
reliable data.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the Commerce Department ``has had to move
cautiously down this road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will remember if the private estimates are off,'' Daley
said, ``but clearly people will have a right to be angry if the
government is fooling them.''
</P>
<P>
   The first e-commerce sales report will provide a simple tally of
Internet retail sales, based on a survey of roughly 2,000 Web
merchants. That is a far cry from the monthly retail reports
released by the Census Bureau, which break down sales totals of
traditional retailers by categories like shoes, liquor and
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau officials said they hoped to achieve a similar
level of detail with their e-commerce results, but are pleased they
have reached even this modest level of statistical success. Three
obstacles in particular have slowed the effort, beginning first
with the issue of how to categorize retailers who appear, disappear
or change their product offerings with dizzying regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a question of taxonomy,'' said Lee Price, chief
economist with the Economics and Statistics Administration. ``It's
one of evolving taxonomy. Amazon used to just sell books. Now they
sell a much more varied selection. You have to figure out how to
capture that.''
</P>
<P>
   Projecting data from 2,000 respondents so it represents the
entire universe of e-commerce spending also presents analytical
dilemmas, Price said. For example, analysts must weigh the data
from those who failed to respond, just as they weigh the results of
those who responded. And in an industry in which retailers are
sprouting quickly in every category, determining the relative
importance of merchants is a daunting task.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the hurdle of actually collecting the data.
``The last thing in the world some of these e-tailers want to do is
bother with sending that information to us, and making sure it's
encrypted and protected,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, the response has been good. The Census Bureau
culled the e-commerce data from questions asked in its monthly
retailing survey, which is sent to 12,300 companies. Of that total,
7,500 companies responded _ 2,000 of which indicated they were
involved with Internet retailing. Notably, the Commerce Department
cannot compel companies to respond. ``We're relying on the kindness
of strangers,'' said Elliot E. Maxwell, an e-commerce adviser to
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and executives said this method would provide much more
reliable information than is now available. ``This will do a lot to
cut down on all the bull about how much people spend online,'' said
Jerry Colonna, managing partner of Flatiron Partners, an Internet
venture capital firm. ``Was it a billion or a trillion this
Christmas? I've heard every number.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Colonna said, the figures will do little to sate the
thirst for more immediate data on Internet sales. ``This will be
important for seeing long-term trends,'' he said. ``But for the
day-to-day investors in the trenches, it's mostly irrelevant.
People are looking for more real-time data.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Bartlett, an e-commerce analyst with the investment
firm Dain Rauscher Wessels, agreed. ``Knowing the fourth-quarter
sales total for '99 isn't going to help me predict the fourth
quarter of 2000,'' he said. ``But as the industry gets more mature
and we see more long-term trend lines, then it becomes securities
analysis 101. Those are exactly the things you look at.''
</P>
<P>
   For the short term, perhaps the greatest benefit of the Commerce
Department's Internet sales data will be to finally assign an
authoritative number to the size of the digital economy. That is a
figure that could prove pivotal this year as politicians ponder the
future of a tax-free Internet _ and its effect on the 30,000 tax
jurisdictions now barred from levying new taxes on Web sales.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the prospect of Internet taxation is enough to raise
questions among some executives about the government's motivation
in seeking e-commerce data. ``I have this sinister feeling that the
only reason the government wants this data is for tax planning
purposes,'' said Steve Jurvetson, managing director of Draper
Fisher Jurvetson, a venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just say that it's good for the world to know, private
industry will figure it out much more efficiently because there's
so much economic incentive to do so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, there is little question that entrepreneurs see
opportunity in the data confusion. An entire industry has developed
around the Internet sales forecasting arena, with firms like
Forrester Research, Jupiter Communications and others vying for
statistical pre-eminence. But the inconsistency of those numbers is
what rankles executives and policy makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have our secret sauce of ways to come up with the
important numbers,'' said Jack Staff, chief economist with Zona
Research, an Internet research firm. ``The bottom line is, there
are a number of ways of going at the numbers right now, and each of
them has advantages and disadvantages.''
</P>
<P>
   The flaws in each of the various statistical approaches will not
prove fatal, he said, even with the appearance of the Commerce
Department data. ``It'll take at least three years for the
government data to be highly usable,'' he said. ``But there's a
whole segment of the Internet industry that's devoted to the
numbers, and it'll be fundamentally changed once better numbers
come along. And that's as it should be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
