<HEADLINE>
COKE NAMES EXECUTIVES AND REORGANIZES DIVISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another wave of appointments designed to put his imprint on
Coca-Cola, Douglas N. Daft, the president, named new executives
Sunday to head the company's African and Asian operations. At the
same time, he reorganized the divisions along geographic lines.
</P>
<P>
   Donald W. Short, most recently the president of Coke's India
division, will lead the Africa and Middle East group. The Middle
East had been combined with Coke's Asian business. The previous
president of the Africa group, Carl H. Ware, Coca-Cola's
highest-ranking black executive, had announced his retirement in
November but is now staying on as executive vice president for
corporate affairs and government relations.
</P>
<P>
   Donald R. Knauss, until recently the president of Coke's South
African division, was named president and chief executive of the
company's Minute Maid division. In October, Stephen C. Jones was
selected for the post, but he was promoted to chief marketing
officer by Daft on Friday. Knauss joined Coke in 1994 and
previously was an executive with the Frito-Lay division of PepsiCo,
Coke's archrival, and also with Tropicana, now also part of
PepsiCo.
</P>
<P>
   Coke said it was changing the name of its Asian operations from
the Middle and Far East group to the Asia Pacific group. The former
Africa group will have three divisions with the addition of the
Middle East territory.
</P>
<P>
   The company also named three division presidents. They are Doug
Jackson, a 39-year-old South African who will run the company's
business in Southern Africa, based in Johannesburg; John Guarino, a
40-year-old American who will become president of the Middle East
and North Africa division; and Alex von Behr, a 40-year-old Briton
who will take Short's spot as president of the India division. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 1919EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
