<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GATEWAY-SUPPLIERS-NYT     01-09 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATEWAY-SUPPLIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATEWAY TO USE CHIPS BY ADVANCED MICRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gateway Inc., the computer maker that last week
blamed supply problems with Intel Corp. for an earnings shortfall,
plans to announce on Monday that it will again use microprocessors
produced by Intel's archrival, Advanced Micro Devices.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway executives said that the new machines using Advanced
Micro's chips would be available through its stores, World Wide Web
site (gateway.com) and toll-free number (800-846-4208).
</P>
<P>
   It was only last year that Gateway switched from buying some
microprocessors from Advanced Micro to relying on Intel exclusively
for microprocessors, the electronic brains of computers. But last
week, when it cited supply problems as it reduced its earnings
forecast, it described Intel's shipments of chips and computer
boards as ``severely constrained, spotty and unreliable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gateway executives said then that they would not remain so
dependent on a sole supplier and would seek another source of
chips.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, that decision led inevitably to Advanced
Micro. While a handful of companies produce microprocessors
compatible with Intel's, Advanced Micro has been the most
aggressive in terms of meeting, and at times beating, Intel in
absolute performance. And it has the broadest product line of all
Intel's rivals. Last week, Advanced Micro said it was producing an
800-megahertz version of its Athlon microprocessor, giving it, for
now, the fastest chip on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is, this solves their supply problem,'' Charles Wolf,
an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read, said of Gateway. The move, he
said, ``is in part buying insurance, to make sure they have enough
processors.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're also sending a message to Intel: `In the future,
treat us better.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said that Gateway's supply problem suggested Intel was
having difficulty meeting production goals for its newest chips and
was allocating them to its most important client, which would be
the Dell Computer Corp., not Gateway. ``Dell has never dual-sourced
on processors,'' he said. ``They're a lot bigger than Gateway and
they've been a loyal customer forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Gateway win was an important one for Advanced
Micro, which for the first time in years is fielding a product line
that can compete head to head with Intel. Previously, Advanced
Micro has either lagged in performance or been unable to produce
its fastest chips in high volumes. But these problems appear to
have been addressed. In addition to Gateway, PC makers that have
said they will use Athlon processors include Compaq Computer, IBM
and CyberMax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gateway's decision to use the AMD Athlon in its Select PC
series enhances AMD's credibility and demonstrates that the Athlon
is gaining acceptance at the high end of the desktop computer
market,'' said Nathan Brookwood, an analyst with Insight 64.
``AMD's win at Gateway reinforces the position of the AMD Athlon
processor as a legitimate challenger in the performance segment.''
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro also plans to announce on Monday that Pionex, an
East Coast computer maker whose machines are sold through
resellers, is offering commercial desktop computers and
workstations based on the Athlon processor. Via Technologies, based
in Taiwan, will also begin shipping a chipset using Athlon,
Advanced Micro said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
