<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ROS-LEHTINEN-PROFILE-     01-09 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROS-LEHTINEN-PROFILE-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI CONGRESSWOMAN DELIGHTS IN BEING VILIFIED BY CASTRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ People usually grimace and squirm when they are publicly
vilified, painted as traitors and mocked as vicious animals. But
for Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, a Florida Republican and a
fist-shaking anti-communist, it's the next best thing to a shot of
Cuban coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the new year, Granma, the state-run newspaper in
Cuba, ran a full-page article that denounced Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, in
head-spinning Marxese, for her involvement in the Elian Gonzalez
case. ``The ferocious wolf disguised as a woman,'' the giant
headline read.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Cuban government started showing a documentary on
state-run television, morphing her image ever so slowly into that
same ferocious wolf, a ``loba feroz,'' as they called her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, who was born in Cuba, was so touched by the
gesture that she immediately ordered a new vanity license plate:
LOBA FRZ. ``I wish I had a vowel there, like Vanna White,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased as punch,'' Ms. Ros-Lehtinen said over a bagel and
a cafe con leche at a cafe here one morning. ``I've been trying for
so many years to get him to pick on me,'' she said, referring to
Fidel Castro. ``I don't know why now, and I don't know why twice.
Something I've been saying has really gotten to him lately because
I've been attacking him forever. Heck, he's the reason we're all
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because Elian, the 6-year-old boy whose father wants
him sent back to Cuba, is living with relatives in her district in
Miami's Little Havana now, and Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, a slim, hiply
coiffed bundle of energy, has seen fit to fling rhetorical
lightning bolts Castro's way as often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Immigration and Naturalization Service decided
that Elian's father, as his legal guardian, had a right to be
reunited with his son in Cuba. Ever since, Miami has been in an
uproar. A congressional subpoena has been issued to try to prevent
immigration officials from sending him home by Friday. And a state
judge is deciding whether to grant temporary custody of the boy to
his great-uncle here.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, 48, was involved in the case from the start.
Soon after a fisherman found Elian, his little body peeking out
from under a bobbing inner tube, on Thanksgiving day, the boy's
relatives called her to pay a visit and find out what to do.
Elian's mother was among those who died when the boat carrying them
from Cuba sank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there just about the day he was released,'' she said.
Her cell phone rings yet again with another interview request.
```Burden of Proof.' Doesn't everyone shout on that show?'' she
asks her aide. ``No. No. Tell them no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be on national news everyday,'' she said, after
clicking off the phone. ``But I go for local radio. I'm a local
gal.'' Besides, she's got to pick up her two daughters at school.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since Elian's release, his relatives have invited her back
several times. She showed up twice around Christmas, once with a
monster truck for sweet-faced Elian and toys for the other kids in
the family. She also attended Elian's birthday party at a local
park with her 12-year-old daughter, Patty, and her father, and she
keeps in touch with the family's lawyers to monitor the case.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen shrugs off her critics, who say she and other
politicians have turned the case of a little boy who lost his
mother into a political circus. ``I've visited many families in my
district, sometimes the media comes and sometimes it doesn't,'' she
said. ``I don't pick which one is the celebrated case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything,'' she added, ``these cases invite opposition. I
don't need help to solidify my base.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Most members of Congress get lots of attention for the pork they
bring home or the roads they help build. That happens in Miami,
too. But Ms. Ros-Lehtinen's bread-and-butter issue is reminding the
U.S. government that Castro is a dictator.
</P>
<P>
   ``These years with Clinton have really hurt our cause,'' said
Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, a former state legislator who was elected to
Congress in 1989. ``He's brought us no help.''
</P>
<P>
   Battling Castro isn't just politics for her, it's also personal.
Ms. Ros-Lehtinen was born in Havana in 1952 and was just a year
older than Elian when she came to this country at age seven. The
year was 1959, Castro had overthrown the government in January and
thousands of Cubans, including Ms. Ros-Lehtinen's family, were
fleeing the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, she met her husband, Dexter Lehtinen, a former U.S.
attorney here, during her stint as a state legislator. Like so many
extended Cuban families, hers is tight-knit. Her mother and father
live right across the street and help take care of her daughters
when she is in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Her constituents are smitten. She has run unopposed during her
last three elections. Janitors and yard workers and businessmen
recognize her on the street, something that can't be said for most
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The waiter, who it turns out arrived here from Cuba four years
ago, asks if she wants more coffee, then leans toward her and nods
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kid can't go back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope not,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope nothing,'' he said. ``It can't happen. That kid is too
important to the exile community.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At a Little Havana senior center, her fans rush her with flowers
and well-wishes. ``Elian, Elian,'' they shout. She slips from
Spanish to English and back again, whatever the moment requires. A
few old Cuban men play Cuban music on the stage and Ms.
Ros-Lehtinen, who admits to having two left feet, shuffles around.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one talks about Elian's mother, about her sacrifice, so he
could reach liberty in this beautiful country,'' she tells the
crowd in Spanish. It is something they love to hear.
</P>
<P>
   But, away from the hubbub, here in the cafe, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen
tones down the rhetoric and shows a pragmatic streak. How can the
community justify separating a 6-year-old from his father, who by
all accounts was a good parent?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never said in any way that Elian should be here or Elian
should be with the father,'' she said. ``All I've ever said and
continue to say to this day, is that the family wants a fair,
impartial court procedure. This is a nation of laws, and we should
be ruled by that, and we shouldn't rely on secretive administrative
decisions. The family has the right like anybody else to have their
day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become such a huge issue,'' she said, ``but we have to
get back to the basics that this really is about a 6-year-old
child.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, and in Cuba, where politics, passion and memories make
for a volatile brew, it's never quite that simple, and she knows
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge may very well decide to send Elian back,'' Ms.
Ros-Lehtinen said. ``If the family had had a fair, impartial and
free open hearing, then we would understand that decision. Now it
has gone so far beyond that, that I don't know what would happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
