<HEADER>
A1009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      01-09 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMISTS DEBATE SOLUTION FOR MICROSOFT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Prominent experts in the Microsoft antitrust case
replayed their arguments at the American Economic Association's
annual conference over the weekend, and some proposures that
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson might impose if the
case reaches a penalty phase.
</P>
<P>
   One penalty proposed on Saturday by Robert E. Hall, a Stanford
University economist, was a multibillion-dollar fine representing
the amount that he estimated the Microsoft Corp. tacked onto the
price of its Windows software because of its monopoly power.
</P>
<P>
   In a second proposal, Steven J. Davis, a University of Chicago
economist, did not suggest a specific penalty but said that
whatever penalties Jackson decides, he should let Microsoft keep
``bundling'' Internet browsers with other software in its Windows
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you share the view that Microsoft engaged in
anticompetitive practices, one has to think very hard about
remedies that restrict complementarities,'' Davis said, referring
to the practice of offering separate software in a single package
at a price that undervalued some elements, like Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any remedy that restricts Microsoft's ability to compete in
complementary software,'' Davis said, ``would raise prices to
consumers, lower profits and reduce incentives to innovate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall describes himself as an independent expert, serving neither
the Justice Department nor Microsoft in the federal antitrust
trial, in which Jackson has issued findings of fact that Microsoft
engaged in anticompetitive practices intended to give its Explorer
an unfair advantage over Netscape and other competing Web browsers.
Davis is a paid consultant for Microsoft. Nearly all the others who
spoke here were on one side or the other in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting the results of a mathematical model, Hall said
Microsoft overpriced Windows, taking advantage of its market power.
But the overpricing did not offer the prospect of enough profit to
encourage personal computer makers to develop an operating system
of their own and offer it to customers in place of Windows, along
with alternatives to Microsoft's browser.
</P>
<P>
   With their own operating system, manufacturers could nullify
pressure from Microsoft to favor Internet Explorer over Netscape
and other browsers, a key issue in the antitrust case. Hall
calculated the overpricing at $11, from a price of about $60 for
Windows software. Thus, if PC makers had their own operating
system, they could lower the price of a computer by $11 each, he
said, saving purchasers about $6 billion over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the creation of this artificial barrier were Microsoft's
only wrongdoing, then the damages owed to past purchasers of
computers are a similar number,'' Hall went on, suggesting a fine.
``More aggressive punishment of Microsoft, such as breaking it up
into competing entities that lowered shareholder value by more than
$6 billion may fail the standard of fitting the punishment to the
crime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 1937EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
