<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-CARE-DEATHS-COX     01-09 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE-DEATHS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By Don Melvin
</P>
<P>
   dmelvin(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Two employees of CARE USA have been shot to death in Sudan and
two others
</P>
<P>
   are missing, the Atlanta-based relief and development
organization announced
</P>
<P>
   Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, which took place between Jan. 2 and Jan. 5, is the
second
</P>
<P>
   fatal shooting involving CARE employees since the New Year
began, and it
</P>
<P>
   served to highlight the increasing dangers humanitarian workers
face when
</P>
<P>
   they try to improve living conditions in countries torn by civil
strife.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, Ibrahim Ishag Abaker and Mekki El Ekheir Mekki, and
two
</P>
<P>
   others set out Jan. 2 from the town of Bentiu, about 450 miles
south of
</P>
<P>
   Khartoum, Sudan's capital. They drove a truck carrying food and
medical
</P>
<P>
   supplies, and were bound for Mayoum, where they planned to open
a new health
</P>
<P>
   clinic.
</P>
<P>
   After they failed to arrive, a search and rescue team composed
of
</P>
<P>
   employees of CARE, the United Nations and the government of
Sudan was sent to
</P>
<P>
   the area. The truck and Mekki's body were found Jan 5 along the
road to
</P>
<P>
   Mayoum. Abaker's body was found a few miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The two other men _ on a CARE staffer, the other a private
contractor _
</P>
<P>
   have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   The area in which they were traveling is nominally controlled by
the
</P>
<P>
   government of Sudan, but it is close to the front lines of
Sudan's
</P>
<P>
   long-running civil war, said Peter Bell, president of CARE USA,
in an
</P>
<P>
   interview Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to government forces and forces of the Sudanese
People's
</P>
<P>
   Liberation Army _ which is the main rebel group _ splinter
groups not necessarily
</P>
<P>
   affiliated with either side also operate in the region, Bell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a hazardous area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are shocked and sickened by this terrible news, and our
hearts go out
</P>
<P>
   to the families of the dead and missing,'' said Jonathan
Mitchell, regional
</P>
<P>
   director in East Africa for CARE International, the umbrella
association of
</P>
<P>
   national CARE organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he was ``appalled by the blatant disregard for the
principle
</P>
<P>
   of protection for humanitarian workers exhibited by whoever
committed this
</P>
<P>
   crime,'' and called on Sudanese authorities to redouble their
efforts to find
</P>
<P>
   the missing men and to investigate the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The incident came close on the heels of an ambush shooting Jan.
2 in
</P>
<P>
   Somalia, in which S. Mohammed Hussein, a CARE engineer, was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said CARE is extremely concerned for the safety of its
staff in various
</P>
<P>
   countries of the world. But he noted that this was the first
such incident
</P>
<P>
   CARE has suffered in 20 years of work in Sudan, and said he had
no reason to
</P>
<P>
   believe CARE workers had been specifically targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That having been said, as long as CARE is going to work in
situations of
</P>
<P>
   conflict, we are going to run risks,'' Bell said. ``The deaths
of these three
</P>
<P>
   workers only underlines the sacrifices that our staff are
prepared to make in
</P>
<P>
   order to relieve suffering. Many of them are real heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Abaker, a team leader for CARE, is survived by a wife and five
children.
</P>
<P>
   Mekki, a driver, left a wife and six children. Both men were
Sudanese, and
</P>
<P>
   each had worked for CARE for about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said that CARE delayed the announcement of the incident for
several
</P>
<P>
   days in to try to avoid jeopardizing the return of the two
missing men, and
</P>
<P>
   to avoid having the incident become a political issue in Sudan
when so few
</P>
<P>
   facts were known.
</P>
<P>
   CARE has been aware of the increasing dangers to its workers,
Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he sent to all CARE country officers a new set of
guidelines for
</P>
<P>
   staff safety and security. The new guidelines were not in
response to the
</P>
<P>
   most recent incidents in Africa, but were approved in November
by the board
</P>
<P>
   of CARE International at its meeting in Cambodia, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, CARE staffers will need more training on safety and
security
</P>
<P>
   matters, he said. But he said there was no indication that the
staffers in
</P>
<P>
   either Somalia or Sudan did anything wrong, or that their deaths
could have
</P>
<P>
   been avoided other than by having CARE abandon those areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the families has in fact been visited by senior care
staff in the
</P>
<P>
   countries, and they have _ as I have myself, by e-mail to our
country
</P>
<P>
   offices _ expressed our gratitude for their service and for
their
</P>
<P>
   willingness to make the ultimate sacrifice in pursuit of CARE's
mission,''
</P>
<P>
   Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
