<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LOBSTER-THEATER-REVIE     01-09 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBSTER-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALI'S DISNEY MOMENT, FEATURING MELTING LOGIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the chronic New York theatergoer there are
certain names whose very presence on a cast list provokes a purr of
anticipation. They make opening a Playbill like sitting down with
the menu in your local bistro and discovering that your favorite
special, which doesn't come around nearly enough, is at last being
served again.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Hecht is one of those names, at least for this chronic
theatergoer. She is a rarity on the American stage these days: a
young actress who combines professional agility with a quirky
individual style that feels as personal and specific as
handwriting. Though she has served time in the upholstered prison
of sitcoms (``Friends,'' ``The Single Guy''), she glows brightest
in live performance, bringing to mind the early careers of, say,
Sandy Dennis, Barbara Harris or, from a later generation, Swoosie
Kurtz.
</P>
<P>
   So it is gratifying to report that Ms. Hecht, seen last season
as the perpetually distracted heroine of Diana Son's ``Stop Kiss,''
is back on the boards in the Playwrights Horizons production of
``Lobster Alice,'' a thick slice of whimsy by Kira Obolensky. It is
doubly gratifying to report that after her triumphs as the dithery
neurotics of ``Kiss'' and Christopher Kyle's ``Plunge,'' Ms. Hecht
here assumes a more focused, aggressive persona without sacrificing
her very particular charms.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hecht plays a Hollywood secretary named Alice Horowitz whose
life is turned inside out by an encounter with Salvador Dali in
1946. She is also the principal reason to be of this show, which
has been staged by Maria Mileaf with a level of insight and visual
sophistication that the script itself rarely lives up to.
</P>
<P>
   The evening features a top-of-the-line production (with sets by
Neil Patel and astonishing mutating projections by Jan Hartley),
inspired music and sound effects by the invaluable David Van
Tieghem and a stylishly loose portrait of all-American uptightness
by Reg Rogers as Alice's romantically challenged boss, a Walt
Disney animator.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for a play that plunges its characters into a vortex of
mind-scrambling surrealism, ``Lobster Alice'' has a deeply
conventional heart. Its formula evokes, to its disadvantage, the
more spontaneous-feeling screwball movies of the 1930s, in which
repressed and timid souls learned how to live, laugh and love
through the stimulation of some madcap muse, usually an anarchic
heiress.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance the Carole Lombard type is replaced by Salvador
Dali (played by David Patrick Kelly), who in the wake of
``Fantasia'' has been commissioned to devise an animated ballet for
the Disney studios. The man overseeing the project, John Finch (
Rogers), is simultaneously working on the cartoon film of ``Alice
in Wonderland.'' ``Lobster Alice,'' which was inspired by a brief
and little-known chapter in Dali's career, accordingly presents a
world in which rigid logic and protocol melt like all those clocks
in Dali's ``Persistence of Memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Such cultural material has been shaped into heady theater by
dramatists from Tom Stoppard to David Ives. Ms. Obolensky has an
ingenious conceit here, but she works it doggedly. The oppositions
of order and chaos, of tradition and iconoclasm are set up with
textbook neatness, just as the Freudian slips planted throughout
the dialogue pop out like road signs.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, every time the play starts to float into some
ether of the subconscious, the gravity of its self-conscious script
pulls it earthward. Even as the view through the windows of John's
Burbank studio magically turns from tidy photo-realism to Dali
dreamscape, the play consistently registers as too, too solid. It
is telling that in a fantasy sequence in which Dali and Finch fight
it out in the style of cartoon adversaries it is Von Tieghem's
sound effects, all those boings and sproings, that get your
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the conception of Dali, whom the play
presents as a cute pet eccentric. In the works of Richard Foreman,
Kelly has provided wonderful studies in what Dali called concrete
irrationalism, but here he is too much the captivatingly wacky
foreigner, suggesting Maurice Chevalier with an Italian accent and
a scatological obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Only when he is cozying up to Rogers' alarmed middle-class prig
does he hint at the sexual danger the character is meant to convey.
The evening is at its most confident when Dali is offstage, and it
might have been better to have left him as a presence much talked
about but never seen.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers and Ms. Hecht both offer shrewd and winning exaggerations
of period styles. You sense that their characters' sense of sexual
identity has indeed been shaped by the movies.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Mileaf makes the most of their awkward artificiality,
especially in a compellingly uncomfortable seduction scene.
Everything in that moment works together: the stiffness and
tentativeness of the dialogue, the geometric absurdity of the
actors' postures, the abrupt shifts in emotion-matching lighting by
Frances Aronson.
</P>
<P>
   It is Ms. Hecht, however, who has been given the play's one
fully realized character, and she expands upon it with delicious
detail. Alice Horowitz is a Jewish variation on a familiar American
archetype: the small-town Midwestern girl who would rather be
practically anything other than ordinary. As she puts it: ``I am a
slave to the interesting. ... Why else do I study Chinese, Finch?''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in postwar costumes (the excellent work of Ann
Hould-Ward) whose discreet touches of flash whisper a craving for
attention, she brings to mind another Alice, Booth Tarkington's
socially ambitious Alice Adams, especially as played by Katharine
Hepburn in the 1935 film. You get the feeling that this Alice has
watched Ms. Hepburn and borrowed a few vowel sounds and speech
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   But the loopy inflections Alice Horowitz brings to even simple
phrases, not to mention the pauses that open up like black holes in
midsentence, are all her own and reveal more about her than she
ever intends. Ms. Hecht's performance is impeccably contained. But
it is Alice, far more than the mystical Dali, who provides the most
vivid map of the shifting underground paths in the human mind.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LOBSTER ALICE'
</P>
<P>
   By Kira Obolensky; directed by Maria Mileaf; sets by Neil Patel;
costumes by Ann Hould-Ward; lighting by Frances Aronson; original
music and sound by David Van Tieghem; projections by Jan Hartley;
production manager, Christopher Boll; production stage manager,
William Joseph Barnes. Presented by Playwrights Horizons, Tim
Sanford, artistic director; Leslie Marcus, managing director; Lynn
Landis, general manager. At Playwrights Horizons' Wilder Theater,
416 West 42nd St., New York.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jessica Hecht (Alice Horowitz), Reg Rogers (John Finch),
David Patrick Kelly (Salvador Dali) and Derek Richardson
(Thorton). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
