<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAN-FRIENDLY OWNERS  
 HILL'S AWESOME ARSENAL
</HEADLINE>
   (With BKN-NOTEBOOK-MAGIC) 
(rk) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Pat Croce in Philadelphia to Larry Miller in Utah, the NBA
has no shortage of hands-on owners who hug their players and mingle
with their ticket-buying public. Mark Cuban, the prospective owner
of the Mavericks, should fit right in.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old co-founder of Broadcast.com has been e-mailing
Maverick fans on the team's Web site for weeks, intimating that he
will quickly put his stamp on the team. Cuban last week reached a
preliminary agreement to buy a controlling interest in the team for
a reported $280 million. According to a news release from the team,
the Hillwood Development Corp., led by Ross Perot Jr., will retain
a minority share of the Mavericks after completion of the proposed
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   A Pittsburgh native, Cuban became one of the country's richest
people last year when Yahoo, the California-based Internet company,
bought the four-year-old Broadcast.com for about $6 billion.
Cuban's personal take was about $1.5 billion. He is the guy who
invented streaming radio technology, in which subscribers can hear
live sports events broadcast over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's stock market plunge, he was said to have lost
$600 million in net worth. Informed of his projected loss, Cuban
was said to have merely smiled and shrugged his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   His purchase means two things for the league. One, franchise
values are not going down. Given that the Nets were sold for a
league-record $227 million in 1998 and the Mavericks will bring
close to $300 million, what will a playoff-bound NBA team
dominating its own sports market bring?
</P>
<P>
   Also, more and more people who spent their college years surfing
the Net _ long ago, these people were referred to simply as
``computer geeks'' _ are continuing to morph into free-spending,
fan-friendly owners. It is all the fault of the Blazers owner Paul
Allen and his Microsoft partner.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban has already met with Don Nelson, the Mavericks' coach and
general manager, who said he would not return as coach next season.
Entering the weekend, Dallas had lost five in a row and 9 of 10 to
drop to 9-23 this season under Nelson, whose coaching and personnel
decisions have come under scrutiny. The coach is just a few
victories short of 900 in his career but has a winning percentage
of only .300 with the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's Awesome Arsenal
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill did not make a 3-pointer all last season and had made
only 22 in his first five years. But the Pistons' All-Star forward
made a concerted effort to work on the mechanics of his jump shot
during the off-season, and now it has become part of his awesome
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting 40 percent from beyond the arc, Hill has already
connected on 16 3-pointers this season. Always hailed as an
incredible athlete who could slash and score at will, he has
suddenly blossomed into a consistent jump-shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Street &AMP; Smith's anointed Hill this past week as a possible most
valuable player based on his numbers and the fact that Detroit had
won six straight games.
</P>
<P>
   Hill parlayed back-to-back 42-point games at Orlando and Atlanta
into a 31-point performance against Milwaukee on Thursday night. He
scored 19 points in the fourth quarter against the Bucks, knocking
down two crucial 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't have the best player in the NBA, we certainly have
the best noncenter,'' Pistons coach Alvin Gentry said of Hill.
``But the great thing about him, it's all about winning. He doesn't
care if he has to score 46 points or four points; whatever he needs
to do to win the game is what he will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill is averaging a career-high 27.5 points, 6.5 rebounds and
5.8 assists. He is making 48.5 percent of his shots. Named to the
U.S. Olympic basketball team this past week along with Ray Allen
and Alonzo Mourning, he is gradually becoming the league's most
versatile and productive player.
</P>
<P>
   All that is missing is a signature playoff performance for a
player on a team that has yet to escape the first round during his
career. Hill can exercise an escape clause in his contract this
summer and sign with another team. Depending on how far the Pistons
advance and whether he sees a championship in his future, he may
get antsy soon.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he stays or goes, with an improved outside shot and his
team finally on a roll, Hill's market value is soaring. And he
still has more than half a season in which to catch Shaquille
O'Neal, Tim Duncan and Kevin Garnett in the MVP voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's playing great,'' Hill said last week. ``We have to
continue to maintain this and not get too full of ourselves. It's
only a couple games that we've played well. In the past, we just
felt like we were never going to get it going. But this year, we
expect to do better. We expect to win.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
