<SLUG> BC-SOLDIER-SENTENCE-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY TO INVESTIGATE EVENTS BEFORE KILLING OF GAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Exclusive)  
(See also SOLDIER-DEATH) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the sentencing of a second soldier in the
killing of a gay private, the Army plans to investigate whether
officers at Fort Campbell, Ky., overlooked the daily harassment
that trial witnesses said the private faced before his beating
death, an Army official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Army is expected to announce on Monday that it has approved
a request by Fort Campbell's commander, Maj. Gen. Robert T. Clark,
to conduct an investigation into the events surrounding the killing
of the private first class, Barry Winchell, last July.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, by the Army's inspector general, could lead
to further disciplinary actions against soldiers and officers at
the base.
</P>
<P>
   A military court sentenced Winchell's roommate, Spc. Justin
Fisher, to 12{ years in prison on Saturday evening as part of a
plea bargain that allowed him to avoid more serious charges of
being an accomplice to the murder and helping cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, a 26-year-old soldier from Lincoln, Neb., pleaded guilty
to two counts of obstructing justice, three of making false
statements and one of providing alcohol to a minor during the
beer-soaked evening that led to Winchell's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Pvt. Calvin Glover, 19, was convicted and sentenced
to life in prison for bludgeoning Winchell to death with a baseball
bat.
</P>
<P>
   The killing has reverberated throughout the military and
political establishments and has become an issue for both parties
in the presidential primary campaign. It has renewed the debate
over the Clinton administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy,
which allows gay men and lesbians to serve in the military provided
they keep their sexual orientation to themselves and do not engage
in homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   After Glover's conviction, President Clinton said the policy was
``out of whack,'' and Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered
the Pentagon's inspector general to investigate whether gay men and
lesbians face harassment on military bases because of their sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's inspector general, Lt. Gen. Michael Ackerman, would
focus on what appeared to be a highly charged environment at Fort
Campbell in the months leading up to Winchell's killing.
</P>
<P>
   In Glover's trial, soldiers testified that Winchell repeatedly
experienced taunting with anti-gay slurs and that superiors did not
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   One sergeant, Michael Kleifgen, even testified that he had
questioned Winchell about his sexuality, a clear violation of the
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's inspector general is expected to investigate other
aspects of discipline and leadership at the post, including why
soldiers were allowed to drink excessively and openly at their
barracks with little apparent oversight or intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safe to assume they'll look into whether there were
violations of the `don't ask, don't tell' policy,'' the Army
official said Sunday. ``They'll also look into some of the other
elements of what the Army calls `command climate.'''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of allowing gays to serve openly in the military have
repeatedly cited the murder of Winchell as evidence that the
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy has failed, because, in practice,
gay service members continue to face harassment.
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses, Winchell, a machine gunner in the 101st
Airborne Division, kept his sexual orientation to himself, fearing
discharge under the policy, but still found himself subjected to
relentless harassment. Some soldiers in his unit testified that
they reported the taunting to Fort Campbell's inspector general,
but that nothing came of it, something that will likely be an
element of the Army's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The day before the slaying, Glover goaded Winchell into a fist
fight and lost the fight. That prompted Glover, egged on by Fisher,
to retaliate by attacking the private with a bat while he slept.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's sentencing, Winchell's parents and
representatives of an organization that provides legal advice to
gay men and lesbians in uniform criticized the plea bargain with
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Winchell's mother, Pat Kutteles, called it ``a travesty.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to testimony, it was Fisher who first began to
circulate rumors about Winchell's orientation after taking him to a
bar in Nashville, Tenn., frequented by transvestites. Fisher also
provided the baseball bat and helped clean up evidence after the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the killing, a military policeman reported
seeing Fisher covered in blood and shouting ``Let him die! Let him
die,'' as an ambulance carried Winchell to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At court-martial on Saturday, Fisher tearfully apologized for
his part in the killing and asked for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry for the part I played in this,'' he said,
addressing Winchell. ``I know you are in a better place. I hope you
know that if I could go back to the morning it happened, I would
have changed it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army initially charged Fisher with helping commit
premeditated murder and acting as an accessory after the fact,
charges that could have led to life in prison. As part of an
agreement that included his cooperation in the investigation,
prosecutors dropped those charges and agreed to cap his sentence at
12{ years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army dropped the two charges directly related to the
crime, despite overwhelming evidence against him,'' Michelle
Benecke, co-director of the Servicemembers Legal Defense Network,
an organization in Washington that provides legal aid to gays in
the military, said Sunday. ``That's the troubling part.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Benecke said the Army's decision to order an inspector
general's investigation came too late and fell short of what was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army needs to do more than a review,'' she said. ``Army
leaders need to take action and make changes in the command climate
at Fort Campbell and elsewhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
