<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CARE-DEATHS-COX     01-09 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE-DEATHS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CARE confirms deaths of workers in Sudan; two still missing
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two employees of CARE USA have been shot to death in
Sudan and two others are missing, the Atlanta-based relief and
development organization announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, which took place between Jan. 2 and Jan. 5, is the
second fatal shooting involving CARE employees since the New Year
began, and it served to highlight the increasing dangers
humanitarian workers face when they try to improve living
conditions in countries torn by civil strife.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, Ibrahim Ishag Abaker and Mekki El Ekheir Mekki, and
two others set out Jan. 2 from the town of Bentiu, about 450 miles
south of Khartoum, Sudan's capital. They drove a truck carrying
food and medical supplies, and were bound for Mayoum, where they
planned to open a new health clinic.
</P>
<P>
   After they failed to arrive, a search and rescue team composed
of employees of CARE, the United Nations and the government of
Sudan was sent to the area. The truck and Mekki's body were found
Jan 5 along the road to Mayoum. Abaker's body was found a few miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   The two other men _ one a CARE staffer, the other a private
contractor _ have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   The area in which they were traveling is nominally controlled by
the government of Sudan, but it is close to the front lines of
Sudan's long-running civil war, said Peter Bell, president of CARE
USA, in an interview Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to government forces and forces of the Sudanese
People's Liberation Army _ which is the main rebel group _ splinter
groups not necessarily affiliated with either side also operate in
the region, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a hazardous area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are shocked and sickened by this terrible news, and our
hearts go out to the families of the dead and missing,'' said
Jonathan Mitchell, regional director in East Africa for CARE
International, the umbrella association of national CARE
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he was ``appalled by the blatant disregard for the
principle of protection for humanitarian workers exhibited by
whoever committed this crime,'' and called on Sudanese authorities
to redouble their efforts to find the missing men and to
investigate the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The incident came close on the heels of an ambush shooting Jan.
2 in Somalia, in which S. Mohammed Hussein, a CARE engineer, was
killed. Bell said CARE is extremely concerned for the safety of its
staff in various countries of the world. But he noted that this was
the first such incident CARE has suffered in 20 years of work in
Sudan, and said he had no reason to believe CARE workers had been
specifically targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That having been said, as long as CARE is going to work in
situations of conflict, we are going to run risks,'' Bell said.
``The deaths of these three workers only underlines the sacrifices
that our staff are prepared to make in order to relieve suffering.
Many of them are real heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Abaker, a team leader for CARE, is survived by a wife and five
children. Mekki, a driver, left a wife and six children. Both men
were Sudanese, and each had worked for CARE for about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said that CARE delayed the announcement of the incident for
several days in to try to avoid jeopardizing the return of the two
missing men, and to avoid having the incident become a political
issue in Sudan when so few facts were known.
</P>
<P>
   CARE has been aware of the increasing dangers to its workers,
Bell said. Last week, he sent to all CARE country officers a new
set of guidelines for staff safety and security. The new guidelines
were not in response to the most recent incidents in Africa, but
were approved in November by the board of CARE International at its
meeting in Cambodia, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, CARE staffers will need more training on safety and
security matters, he said. But he said there was no indication that
the staffers in either Somalia or Sudan did anything wrong, or that
their deaths could have been avoided other than by having CARE
abandon those areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the families has in fact been visited by senior CARE
staff in the countries, and they have _ as I have myself, by e-mail
to our country offices _ expressed our gratitude for their service
and for their willingness to make the ultimate sacrifice in pursuit
of CARE's mission,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Melvin writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
