<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEBATES-ASSESS-2TAKES     01-09 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES-ASSESS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CANDIDATES DEBATING MORE, COMPETITION PICKS UP BEHIND THE
SCENES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. _ They posted security guards at the doors to the
press room during the presidential debates at the University of New
Hampshire last week. Not to fend off angry readers, but to keep the
candidates' spin people at bay.
</P>
<P>
   During past debates, overeager campaign staff members would
invade the room to make pitches for their candidates as harried
journalists were trying to watch and write. ``They would complain
because these people wouldn't leave them alone,'' said Erika Mantz,
a spokeswoman for New Hampshire Public Television, a sponsor of the
Republican and Democratic forums here. ``So we made the decision to
keep the filing room a sterile environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Protecting the press corps from young campaign aides brandishing
stacks of freshly photocopied, point-by-point debate analyses might
not sound like democracy's most dangerous assignment. But that such
a task is necessary at all is a measure of how fiercely competitive
the rituals of presidential debating have become, and of the degree
to which the campaigns have developed sophisticated machinery to
try to turn these crucial encounters to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   These days, opportunities abound to glimpse the backstage
maneuvers _ Ms. Mantz even had to chase out a man from the Bradley
campaign wearing the press credentials of a female reporter _
because the candidates are debating and debating and debating some
more. Already they have bickered and parried in places like Nashua,
N.H., and Des Moines, Columbia, S.C., and Phoenix. They have stood
behind lecterns and sat around tables, answering questions about
public policy and personal preferences asked by famous moderators,
audience members, e-mailing viewers and even one another.
</P>
<P>
   Last week alone, four debates were held in three states, and a
fifth is scheduled for the Republicans on Monday night in Michigan.
Before the New Hampshire primary on Feb. 1, at least four more will
be held, and campaign officials in both parties report having
received invitations to dozens of others in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do every debate that is on the list, this will be the
most debated Republican primary of all time,'' said William Dal
Col, campaign manager for publisher Steve Forbes. ``I say, let's
go. Let's have at it.''
</P>
<P>
   This gung-ho attitude is not shared by every campaign, for all
the televised, off-the-cuff conversing carries a different level of
risk for, say, a candidate trying to protect a lead in the polls.
Early on, for instance, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas skipped the
first candidates' forums, though he has participated in the last
five. Others have embraced the debates more enthusiastically. Vice
President Al Gore has even offered to stop running commercials and
participate instead in twice-weekly debates with former Sen. Bill
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've accepted over 40 invitations,'' said Chris Lehane, the
spokesman for the Gore campaign. ``If you want to hold a debate in
your house, we'll be there.'' (The Democrats have met in televised
debates five times, with three more on their schedule.)
</P>
<P>
   Even if, as Bradley has asserted, Gore's offer is a ploy to
steal some of the thunder from Bradley's well-publicized advocacy
of campaign finance reform, there seems little doubt as to why the
proposal might strike a chord with voters, and why as a consequence
the candidates are debating so often. At a time when so much of a
political campaign is tightly scripted, officials involved in the
process say, a debate is one of the few remaining vehicles with the
potential to spark something like a burst of spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Brown, executive director of the Commission on
Presidential Debates, a nonpartisan group established in 1987 to
oversee the formal general-election presidential encounters, said
she thinks that the electorate is hungry for unfiltered exposure to
the candidates. Not only have the debates begun in earnest earlier
than in previous years, but she said she is also hearing this year
from more and more upset voters who want to watch the debates but
do not have cable television, on which most of the debates are
being broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single thing that sets a debate apart is that the
citizenry believes it still belongs to them,'' Ms. Brown said.
``There are no handlers, no props, and they find that enormously
appealing. That is why the viewership for debates is so high.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The country as a whole might not yet be concentrating heavily on
campaign 2000, but it is in full swing in New Hampshire, Iowa,
South Carolina and Michigan, all of which hold their caucuses or
primaries this month or next. And one sign of how full is the
popularity of the debates. For example, on New Hampshire Public
Television _ one of four local and national stations to carry the
debate _ more than 40,000 New Hampshire households tuned in
Thursday night to the GOP encounter, with Tim Russert of NBC as
moderator. Mary Norris, the station's coordinator of broadcast
services, said the program was one of its most-watched of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Already, the debates have produced moments that have helped to
illuminate the campaign, such as the Iowa forum in which Bush
declared that Jesus Christ was the political thinker who most
deeply influenced him, and the installment of ``Meet the Press'' on
which Bradley refused to shake Gore's hand on his proposal to
eliminate campaign commercials. Another memorable moment came last
week when Gore first seemed to accept the idea of a litmus test on
gays in the military and then backed away. &UR;  &LR; They are the kinds of
moments the debates' producers live for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal from the beginning was to find a creative way to make
sure it didn't become a press conference,'' said Beth O'Connell,
executive producer of special events for NBC News. Last month she
produced the Republican debate in Iowa moderated by the NBC anchor
Tom Brokaw and his local counterpart in Des Moines, John Bachman.
They were applauded by television critics and others for keeping it
lively: It was during that debate that Bush made his now famous
allusion to Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By the time the six Republican and two Democratic candidates
arrived in Durham for the encounters sponsored jointly by the
Manchester Union Leader, New England Cable News and the public
television station, they were full-fledged debating veterans. So
were the organizers. ``You could say that we started planning this
four years ago,'' said Charles Perkins III, the Union Leader's
executive editor. They had decided to make it a traditional format,
with a moderator and three reporters asking the questions.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   No matter what format, though, the two parties' encounters at
the podiums already were taking on distinct personalities. The more
crowded Republican field was becoming more raucous, the more
intimate Democratic contest growing a bit testier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite edgy,'' said Peter Jennings, the ABC newsman, who
refereed the Democrats here last Wednesday night. He wondered, he
said, if the palpable antagonism between the candidates could be
picked up by the cameras. ``The thing I was dying to tell the
audience was how much goes on backstage,'' Jennings said. ``Gore
has dressing room A; Bradley wants to have dressing room A.
Everything's got to be equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the pre-debate elbowing for position was grueling,
according to those who put together the shows. The angles of the
cameras, the size of the candidates' holding rooms, the number of
aides who could be with the debaters backstage: all had to be
argued out with the candidates' handlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my fourth primary; each one has had its own
challenges,'' said Carole Paling, the executive producer of the
Durham debates. ``But this one surprised me in terms of the
boldness of their suggestions as to how we should produce the show.
When I have a cavity I don't tell my dentist how to drill.''
</P>
<P>
   The haggling even got down to the ways the candidates' voices
would be amplified: The campaigns lobbied for wireless microphones.
``It was a comfort thing,'' a slightly exasperated Ms. Paling
recalled. She had to explain the apparatus was not practical,
especially for the Republicans, because six candidates would
require the use of 12 separate frequencies. ``And with 12
frequencies, someone in the audience would have picked one up in
their dental work,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The intense preliminaries might actually have served the
process. By the accounts of some experienced political junkies, the
hourlong Durham debates made for taut television. ``I don't know if
it was the format or the press people, but you didn't just get
those pre-packaged, bite-sized answers,'' said Maurice Carroll, a
former political reporter who is now director of the Polling
Institute at Quinnipiac College in Hamden, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Carroll paid the proceedings a higher compliment: ``I
passed up the Rangers to watch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
