<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SOLDIER-DEATH-880&AMP;ADD     01-09 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLDIER-DEATH-880&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER OF SLAIN SOLDIER CONTINUES TO SEEK JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (See also SOLDIER-SENTENCE) 
(lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Somewhere in the long season of grief for her
murdered son, it dawned on Patricia Kutteles that she will never be
finished with the U.S. Army, where her son Barry found a home that
proved his undoing, and where he left her a cause that she now
pursues as his only true memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized it won't ever end till I die,'' Mrs. Kutteles said
recently. She spoke of her struggle to absorb, first, the brutal
barracks bludgeoning of her son; then, the shocking discovery that
he had been taunted for months with epithets; and now, her
deepening despair at military justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life is now at the whim of the Army,'' the mother said,
showing the tightly folded flag that she was given at the funeral
along with the Army's official regrets for the loss of her son,
Pfc. Barry Winchell.
</P>
<P>
   His murder last July at Fort Campbell, Ky., is being cited as
proof of the failure of the military's ``don't ask, don't tell''
policy toward gays.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kutteles spent much of the summer and autumn at the army
base, grasping for details about her son's months of harassment and
his death in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   She attended the court-martial of his confessed murderer, Pvt.
Calvin Glover, who beat her son on the head with a baseball bat as
he slept in the barracks. Glover, 19, who was taunted to act after
he had challenged Winchell to a fight and lost, was sentenced last
month to life imprisonment but with the possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   This means, Mrs. Kutteles has learned, that she will have to be
vigilant after the first decade of imprisonment to speak at parole
hearings against any early release from the military justice that
she has learned to distrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, it'll never end,'' said Mrs. Kutteles, a 50-year-old
registered nurse. She sat chain-smoking in her home near the edge
of the Kansas City's beltway, worrying about the surprising ways of
the Army. ``I'll have to go to years of hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Mrs. Kutteles is anguished at the leniency being
extended to Glover's accomplice, Spc. Justin Fisher, 26, who
witnesses said spread the rumors about Winchell's private life,
goaded his killer with taunts and handed him the bat, even washing
the blood off afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher, in exchange for testifying against Glover, saw the
most serious charge _ accomplice to murder _ dropped. He faces 12
and a half years for obstruction of justice, making false
statements, and providing alcohol to a minor _ a ludicrous
footnote, in Mrs. Kutteles' view, to the frequent drinking bouts at
the barracks that, the murder investigation showed, went on with no
interference from base commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've fought to find out _ and I don't care whether
Barry was gay or not _ leaves me worried about the safety of all
the young men and women the Army is supposed to be looking after,''
Mrs. Kutteles said. ``I can't bear to hear that Army recruiting
song: `Be all that you can be in the Army.' My son tried to be all
that he could be and he got murdered.''
</P>
<P>
   In her frustration, Mrs. Kutteles and her husband, Wally, who is
Barry's stepfather and a veteran of the Korean War, planned to try
to force the issue into a civilian court by pursuing a wrongful
death suit. They said they would take the step to protect the
rights of other soldiers and to defend their son's memory.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kutteles angrily said her son was still being defamed and
points to stories she has been gathering from members of the
service who say harassment of gays continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making a mockery of his death,'' Mrs. Kutteles said.
She knew her son as a confiding young man who told her about
several girlfriends. ``I think he was just trying to find out who
he was,'' she said of reports that Barry began dating a Navy
veteran who apparently had undergone a sex change and was a dancer
at a nightclub in Nashville, Tenn. ``He, or she, is a very nice
person,'' Mrs. Kutteles said of the dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Her son was first taken to the club by his Fort Campbell
roommate, Fisher, who, witnesses testified, later spread rumors
that Winchell was gay. In violation of the ``don't ask'' policy,
some sergeants then began investigating the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said Winchell, caught in this spiral, did not complain
about the persistent harassment for fear of being dismissed from
the Army under the ``don't tell'' part of the military policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry was so proud of himself as a soldier,'' his mother said.
``They called him `Top Gun,''' she said of his awards for
proficiency as a machine gunner in the 101st Airborne Division. He
never once mentioned his troubles, she said, but in frequent chats
would focus on her mundane cares and would offer a bit of
Army-slang advice about always being persistent in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear him now, over and over, telling me, `Suck it up, Mom,
and drive on,''' she remembered. ``Everything I'm doing is for him:
Suck it up and drive on.''
</P>
<P>
   After the slaying, other gay servicemen and women have come
forward to complain about harassment. Gays continue to leave the
military at a rate that has nearly doubled since the inception of
the ``don't ask'' policy in 1993, according to the Servicemembers
Legal Defense Network, a gay-rights group that monitors military
justice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Kutteles stays in touch with the organization, saying that
the case might have been treated by the Army as a classic
drunken-brawl crime but for the information the group received
about a hate crime rooted in homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SLDN helped immensely in finding out what really went
on,'' she said, accepting its cause as her own even though she has
no clear idea about her son's private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter to me one way or the other, and Barry would
know that,'' she said. ``And I think he would have told me as soon
as he figured it out.''
</P>
<P>
   What particularly grieves Mrs. Kutteles is a sense that the Army
has been waiting for this case to fade away. She received no reply,
she said, to a letter in October to Secretary of Defense William
Cohen that warned of continuing harassment of gays and
``blasphemies to the memory of our son.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold the Army just as responsible as the two who were
tried,'' she said. ``Oh, no, this will never end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
