<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-NFCGAME10-COX     01-09 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCGAME10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vikings take win over Dallas
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The first step toward purging the emptiness of
last year's playoff failure was successful, albeit shaky for the
Minnesota Vikings on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the NFC Wildcard game, the Dallas Cowboys made like
last year's Atlanta Falcons _ unfazed by the maniacal Metrodome
crowd or the home team's status as favorites. After a solid first
quarter, the Cowboys turned into this year's Falcons, and Minnesota
capitalized on Dallas' stumblebum effort to earn an underwhelming
27-10 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was the best therapy for a team that admittedly has not
gotten over the Falcons' upset in last year's NFC Championship
Game. The Vikings advance to meet the top-seeded Rams in St. Louis
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get out of the first round to get ourselves sort of
settled,'' said receiver Randy Moss, who had five receptions for
127 yards and a touchdown. ``We started slowly and I was thinking,
`Man, when are we going to get started?' But we were able to remain
composed and overcome that.''
</P>
<P>
   They were duly aided by the Cowboys' sloppy effort.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had three turnovers, including a fumbled punt by Deion
Sanders that set up a Minnesota field goal. The Cowboys twice had
third-down penalties that extended Vikings drives. In one case,
Sanders was playing to the crowd instead of counting the number of
teammates on the field. Dallas had 12.
</P>
<P>
   Those type of mental errors plagued the Cowboys all day.
Quarterback Troy Aikman (22-for-38, 286 yards) had three third-down
passes dropped. Said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey: ``If you make that
many mistakes _ turnovers, dropped passes, mental mistakes _ you
don't give yourself a great chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's chances were enhanced when running back Robert Smith
took charge while quarterback Jeff George struggled. Smith set a
Vikings postseason record with 140 yards on 28 carries, but it was
his reception and run in the second quarter that seemed to lift the
Vikings' spirits while demoralizing the Cowboys'.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas led 10-3 in the second quarter, when, on third-and-25
from the Cowboys' 26, George completed just his second pass of the
game, a little hitch to Smith in the left flat. With only George
Teague between him and the goal line, Smith gave the Cowboys'
safety an impromptu stutter step _ ``I don't know where that move
came from,'' Smith said _ and sprinted up the sideline for a
game-tying touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits Robert in the flat and he takes and 8-yard gain and
turns it into a touchdown,'' Minnesota coach Dennis Green said.
``That's what you have to be able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point, Dallas did not muster much offense, then became
clueless on how to defend Moss. On third-and-8, Chris Warren
dropped a first-down opportunity, forcing a Dallas punt. Five plays
later, George connected with Moss on a 58-yard touchdown that put
the Vikings ahead 17-10 with 28 second left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith, who had a 65-yard run in the game's first drive,
became a virtual nonfactor after halftime. The Vikings stacked the
line of scrimmage and dared the Cowboys to beat them passing.
Dallas couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Rahib Ismail, Aikman's only reliable receiver, had receptions of
46 and 25 yards to set up an Emmitt Smith 5-yard touchdown. Ismail
finished with eight catches for 163 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's receivers weren't too sure-handed, either. Jake Reed
dropped a pass that would have put the Vikings inside the 5 yard
line; they settled for a Gary Anderson field goal. Moss let a
touchdown pass slip through his hands. And Chris Carter had only a
few balls thrown his way _ one was a diving reception that was
overturned on replay.
</P>
<P>
   Carter did catch a 5-yard touchdown pass from George early in
the fourth quarter to all but assure the Vikings another chance to
get over last year's Falcons loss. The 17-point lead was more than
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was last year, but we wouldn't be honest if we
didn't say we won't get over it until we get to the Super Bowl,''
defensive lineman Jerry Ball said. ``We don't dwell on that. We're
concentrating on who's in front of us. But we know how terrible it
felt to lose last year against Atlanta when we expected to go to
the Super Bowl. We still have a ways to go, but at least we've
gotten started.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
