<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-IRELAND-PHONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH PHONE CONCERN MAY GET SECOND OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Telecommunications is considering a bid for
Ireland's second-largest telephone company, the Esat Telecom Group,
possibly rescuing it from a hostile offer from Telenor of Norway,
executives close to the talks said here Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Esat, a telephone concern that has benefited tremendously from
Ireland's recent economic boom, said last week that it was in talks
with several unidentified companies about being acquired in hopes
of thwarting Telenor. Esat's rapid growth and small size attracted
Telenor, which is eager to expand beyond Scandinavia. Last month,
Telenor increased its bid for Esat in hopes of keeping a company
like British Telecommunications from spoiling its expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to British Telecommunications said that if the
company decided to proceed with an offer, it would bid about $2.1
billion. The executives stressed that the company had not yet
settled on its plans and could still decide to abandon the effort.
</P>
<P>
   British Telecom would have to at least match Telenor's offer of
$1.9 billion for Esat, which values each American depository share
of the Irish concern at $85. Originally, Telenor had bid for Esat
jointly with Telia of Sweden, with which it had planned to merge,
but that deal collapsed last month. Telenor has forged ahead with
its bid independently, raising it to $1.9 billion from $1.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors still seem convinced that Esat will be
sold to a third party at a premium over Telenor's bid. On Friday,
ADR's of Esat closed up $2.375, at $91.125, $6 above Telenor's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Esat's battle to stave off Telenor's hostile bid, the
two companies are partners in a mobile phone joint venture. Both
companies own 49.5 percent each of Esat Digifone, Ireland's
second-largest mobile phone network. It is unclear whether British
Telecommunications could gain control of the mobile unit because
both companies have the right of first refusal to the remaining 1
percent in the partnership, which is owned by Demot Desmond, an
Irish businessman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 2021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
