   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Jan. 10 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLES-CHOICE (Los Angeles) -- Daily News entertainbment
reporter covers the 26th annual People's Choice Awards, hosted by
Don Johnson and his ``Nash Bridges'' co-star Cheech Marin.
</P>
<P>
   LA-MAYOR-BANNERS (Los Angeles) -- Mayor Richard Riordan has
challenged plans to put up street banners throughout Los Angeles
with provocative meesages on race relations and other controversial
issues because of their potential to offend. Riordan vigorously
objected to one banner with a message about white suburban kids
shooting a black man. Others deal with various aspects of race
relations, gender issues etc. By Sherry Joe Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD-ZACARIAS (Los Angeles) -- After 34 years working for the
nation's second-largest school system, Los Angeles Unified
Superintendent Ruben Zacarias is leaving with many regrets and a
prediction for the future: the district will split unless there is
marked improvement. By Sherry Joe Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   LA-HEALTH (Los Angeles) -- Los Angelenos may live in the land of
sunshine, health food and 24-hour gyms, but a high percentage don't
feel so good. In The Los Angeles area, more people describe their
health as just fair or poor than in any other of the nation's 50
largest cities, except Fresno, according to a new study from the
Public Health Research Group of Portland, Maine. By Steve Carney.
</P>
