u i BC-BRITAIN-WEBBER-(TRIMS     01-09 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-WEBBER-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL MAKES LLOYD WEBBER DOMINANT OWNER OF LONDON THEATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British composer Andrew Lloyd Webber on Sunday won
an international bidding war for ten of London's leading playhouses
and variety halls in a $145 million deal making him a dominant
owner in the world's largest theater district.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Webber, author of a dozen hit musicals including ``Cats,''
``Evita'' and ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' member of the House of
Lords and proprietor of three other West End theaters, said he was
moving into his new role to protect the stage from business
interests less concerned with what appears behind the footlights
than on the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is vital that the theater be in the hands of people who
know and love the theater,'' Lloyd Webber, 51, said in an interview
in his Belgravia townhouse. ``Otherwise our lifeblood is taken away
from us, and there's no room anymore for the old-fashioned producer
who will back shows that take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The composer said that he was not motivated by any desire to
control showcases for his own productions. While he expected to
realize profits from the new holdings, he said: ``I would like to
think that we will be more sympathetic to shows that deserve a
break to survive. There are lots of shows that don't look good on
paper and appear not to be good business where we'll say, `Let's
get behind this and hope it pays off.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's action marked another dramatic step in a revolution in
British stage ownership that began this summer when the ten Stoll
Moss Theaters houses and the eight stages owned by Associated
Capital Theaters (ACT) were put up for sale, and Apollo Group,
owner of 23 theaters across the country, was purchased for $255
million by SFX Entertainment, the American company that is a
worldwide promoter, producer and operator of live events.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people begin to talk about being able to stage shows well
because they have a vertically integrated company, you begin to
worry,'' Lloyd Webber said.
</P>
<P>
   While the composer's work today is no longer considered to be
the kind of artistically daring theater he professes to want to
sponsor now, it was, he argued, at the time. ```Cats' on paper was
the worst idea conceivable, but we got it on stage because Bernard
Delfont, an old-fashioned showman, took a bit of a flier on it. Can
you imagine a bunch of bankers sitting around saying, `Why don't we
put our money on a big musical about the wife of an Argentine
dictator?'''
</P>
<P>
   Among the theaters in Sunday's deal are the London Palladium,
the Garrick, Her Majesty's, the Lyric and the Theatre Royal Drury
Lane. They are part of the Stoll Moss group that was put up for
sale in August by Janet Holmes a Court, 56, who said she was
returning home to Australia to enter politics and attend to family
businesses developed by her husband, Robert, a well-known
international investor who died in 1990, leaving no will.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Webber's privately owned Really Useful Group was joined by
NatWest Equity Partners, a firm taking a 50 percent stake in the
new theater company that will be run by Richard Johnston, the
current chief executive of Stoll Moss. The Really Useful Group will
put the two theaters it owns outright _ the Palace and the New
London _ and the house whose ownership it shares with the New
York-based Nederlander Group _ the Adelphi _ into the new business.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 groups from Europe, the United States and Australia
became involved in the confidential Stoll Moss auction before the
choice came down to Lloyd Webber and Max Weitzenhoffer, a wealthy
Oklahoma entrepreneur with an interest in London theater who had
been a backer of some of the composer's shows. In the press release
announcing the transaction Sunday night, Lloyd Webber noted his
pleasure at bringing the theaters ``back into British ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Mackintosh, 53, the British impresario who once was a
producer of Lloyd Webber musicals but in recent years has become
the composer's rival, was portrayed in press reports this fall as
his chief competitor for the Stoll Moss properties. Last month,
however, he said he was not a bidder. Mackintosh already owns three
West End theaters and will most likely take control of two of those
bought by Lloyd Webber _ the Gielgud and Queen's _ because he owns
the leaseholds on them that expire in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Holmes a Court was said to be seeking $165 million for the
Stoll Moss properties, a figure that many investors, particularly
those with no established presence in London, found discouraging.
Theater purchases are sometimes derided as trophy hunts rather than
sound investments, but Lloyd Webber defended the $145 million final
figure, saying, ``We feel certain that at that price, with our
other theaters and other savings, it will work for us, though we
went to the limit of that.''
</P>
<P>
   His own company rang up losses in 1997 after making excessive
investments in foreign productions of his ``Sunset Boulevard,'' but
a year later Lloyd Webber took full control, replaced his
management and the company returned to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Though the West End has been thriving in recent seasons from the
boom in London tourism and entertainment, running theaters remains
a volatile venture. Many of the city's playhouses are grandly
ornamental Victorian and Edwardian buildings that call for urgent
renovation and involve high costs because of the antiquity of much
of the physical plant.
</P>
<P>
   Theater owners here, however, enjoy revenue-generating
advantages over their counterparts in New York because of more
demanding terms for producers, larger bar business, paid programs,
greater control of ticketing operations, and a tradition known as
personal property or ``p.p.,'' whereby the proceeds from the first
dozen tickets sold to every performance go directly to the owner
with no service deductions.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Webber said he foresaw massive changes in theatergoing
because of the anticipated move of ticket purchasing to the
Internet. ``If the time comes that these Internet companies want to
try to take over the theater business, they'll have to do it with
us, and that was a huge argument behind my management's thinking
about doing this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Webber was in an ebullient mood Sunday as he left his
house to answer a press photo call at one of his new theaters. He
said he was headed for the London Palladium, currently running
``Saturday Night Fever,'' and would take special care not to pose
in front of either the Piccadilly or the Theatre Royal Drury Lane.
The show at one, he pointed out, was ``Spend, Spend, Spend,'' and
at the other, ``Dancing on Dangerous Ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
