<HEADER>
A1078 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-VIKINGS-H     01-09 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-VIKINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MINNEAPOLIS _ Good start, poor finish, with plenty of mistakes
sprinkled throughout. Sound familiar?
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys played Sunday's NFC wild-card game like many
of their others this season. The Cowboys looked impressive for a
quarter, then flailed hopelessly as they succumbed to the Minnesota
Vikings 27-10 at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith would make three defenders miss for a 65-yard gain
to the three. The Cowboys would then fail to get the final three
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman would complete a third-and-eight pass to Jason
Tucker, who would get to the Minnesota six. Tucker would then
fumble the ball through the end zone, resulting in a touchback for
the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's game symbolized our whole season,'' Smith said. ``We
can put it together one week, look totally lost the next. It's been
like a roller coaster _ up and down, up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost, confused, dazed _ all describe how the Cowboys looked at
times Sunday. There were the three timeouts they were forced to
take in the first 10 minutes because of miscommunication and
personnel problems. There was a 12-men-on-the-field penalty on a
punt return. There were passes that went one way when receivers
went another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to do one thing; he did something
else,'' said Aikman, describing one of the failed pass attempts to
Chris Warren.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were the blown coverages. On one third-and-one
play, the Dallas defense let Cris Carter catch a five-yard
touchdown pass with nobody around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get off blocks and make plays,'' Cowboys
linebacker Randall Godfrey said. ``Surely I didn't come off blocks
and make plays I was supposed to make today, and a lot of other
guys didn't. But this thing can be corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   Just not this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defense went in with the goal of preventing the
long pass to Randy Moss or Carter. And Dallas pretty much
accomplished that, save one 58-yard touchdown pass to Moss. In
fact, Vikings quarterback Jeff George was 0-for-4 in the first
quarter and didn't complete a pass to a wide receiver until midway
through the second.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Vikings' short passing game _ underneath routes
and screens to the running backs _ that was the most dangerous.
With Minnesota trailing 10-3 and facing third-and-25 at the Dallas
26, running back Robert Smith caught a screen in the flat and
waltzed into the end zone untouched. Running back Leroy Hoard
caught a 10-yarder on third-and-six to keep a field-goal drive
alive in the third quarter. And in the fourth quarter, Smith had a
32-yard reception on third-and-five to set up Carter's touchdown
catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the ball, they were so concerned with the guys
outside (Moss and Carter), they took off,'' George said of the
Dallas secondary on his TD pass to Smith. ``Robert is so smart. He
took off for the flat. I don't know if he knew I was coming to him,
but he was all I had. I just kept the ball in his hands and let him
do his magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also frustrated the Cowboys with his elusive running,
carrying the ball 28 times for 140 yards, an average of five yards
per attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game, if you would have told me we'd only give up
(199 net yards passing), I'd have chalked that up as a win,''
Dallas safety George Teague said.
</P>
<P>
   Moss caught five passes for 127 yards and a touchdown. Carter's
only catch was his five-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody would have told me they'd only have (199 yards)
passing, I'd have done cartwheels on the plane,'' Dallas cornerback
Deion Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   But even a spectacular defensive performance _ and this one
wasn't _ wouldn't have been enough to save the Cowboys from their
mistakes. Dallas fumbled three times, with two of the mistakes
leading to 10 Minnesota points and the other keeping the Cowboys
from scoring at least three.
</P>
<P>
   The first error came after a three-and-out series by the Vikings
on their first possession. Sanders fumbled the punt, which was
recovered at the Dallas 30 by Vikings linebacker Dwayne Rudd. Four
plays later, Gary Anderson kicked a 47-yard field goal to tie the
game at 3 with 7:01 elapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just not acceptable in a game of this caliber,''
Sanders said. ``And it started a series of turnovers by this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The next one came early in the second quarter after linebacker
Dat Nguyen had tipped a third-down pass to force a Minnesota punt.
On the ensuing possession, Aikman connected with fullback Robert
Thomas on a third-and-two pass. As Thomas was stretching for the
first down, Rudd stripped the ball, which safety Anthony Bass
recovered at the Dallas 23.
</P>
<P>
   Four plays later, George connected with Smith on the 26-yard
touchdown screen. Teague had a chance to make a tackle inside the
10, but rather than step up to meet Smith, he let the running back
juke past him into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's fumble, the Cowboys' third, came in the fourth quarter
on the ninth play of what had been the most productive Dallas drive
of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get an offense, especially our offense, back on the
field, that's always a good feeling,'' Rudd said. ``Turnovers in
the playoffs are huge. When you get a chance to put our offense
back on the field with turnovers, it's tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   As was the case when the teams played in November, the Cowboys'
offense got off to a quick start, with Emmitt Smith breaking three
tackles to race 65 yards to the three on the fourth play from
scrimmage. But the Cowboys, who have had red-zone problems much of
the season, were able only to kick a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   After the Vikings evened the score at 3, Dallas sustained a
seven-play, 79-yard drive on its next possession. Smith capped it
with a five-yard touchdown run with five minutes left in the first
quarter, but the Cowboys never scored again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was pretty much reminiscent of the year we've had,''
Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
