<HEADLINE>
SURFING THE TUBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY 
Question: Whatever happened to Steve Fisher, the coach of
Michigan's Fab Five? Answer: He's now coaching the Mediocre 5 at
San Diego State. Only at SDSU could they have a great facility in
Cox Arena and an attractive city like San Diego to lure kids from
the East Coast and still be a sub-.500 program. Utah at San Diego
State, ESPN, 9 p.m. 
TUESDAY 
Sure, the Kentucky-Auburn game two hours later may be the better
matchup, but how it's hard to resist tuning in an Indiana game in
the hopes of a Bobby Knight meltdown. Indiana at Michigan State,
ESPN, 4 p.m. 
WEDNESDAY 
With UCLA struggling and an NCAA bid far from automatic this
season, this game takes on added importance. Not to mention the
crosstown rivalry and bragging rights. UCLA coach Steve Lavin may
need an extra coat of oil for this game if the Bruins play like
they did at Washington. UCLA at USC, Fox Sports Net, 7:30 p.m. 
THURSDAY 
When they built Staples Center, it was supposed to give the Kings a
better chance to survive in the NHL. A better facility with luxury
suites and increased attendance would give the team more revenue.
However, it hasn't made the Kings a better home team. And playing
one of the better teams in St. Louis doesn't help matters. St.
Louis Blues at Kings, Fox Sports Net, 7:30 p.m. 
FRIDAY 
The Lakers may be best in the West, but can they beat the beast
from the East? Take off from work a little early and grab some dip
and chips as the teams with the two best records in the NBA square
off. Lakers at Indiana Pacers, Channel 9 and TNT, 5 p.m. 
SATURDAY 
These two teams received byes for the first week of the NFL
playoffs, and yet it's not beyond the realm of possibility that
Jacksonville and Tampa Bay could be upset. The Bucs defense has
been strong all year, but the team's offense could be a question
mark. Meanwhile, Jacksonville won the AFC Central, but will be
without the services of All-Pro left tackle Tony Boselli. Miami at
Jacksonville, Channel 2, 9:30 a.m.; Washington at Tampa Bay,
Channel 11, 1 p.m. 
SUNDAY 
The NFL's two best quarterbacks begin postseason action as Curt
Warner and the Rams and Peyton Manning of the Colts play host to
playoff games. Minnesota at St. Louis, Channel 11, 9:30 a.m.;
Tennessee at Indianapolis, Channel 2, 1 p.m. 

