<DOCNO> NYT20000109.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-GOV-ART-980(2TA     01-09 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOV-ART-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUG OF WAR ON BUDGET THREATENS A GOVERNOR'S RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Times headline seemed almost a
parody, a ``Saturday Night Live'' spoof come to life: ``Davis Hails
First Year in Office as Total Success.'' But in fact, for Gov. Gray
Davis of California, much of the last year has been a string of
media superlatives, legislative achievements, fiscal luck,
political popularity and, yes, success.
</P>
<P>
   He won new reading programs for students and training for
teachers, exit exams for high school graduates and a plan to reward
schools for improved performance. He signed a half-dozen gun
control bills, including a toughened ban on assault weapons, a ban
on cheap handguns, a requirement for trigger locks on new handguns
and a limit of one handgun purchase a month per person.
</P>
<P>
   He approved a package of measures granting patients in health
maintenance organizations new rights to contest decisions on care.
</P>
<P>
   He even raised a record $8 million in campaign contributions in
the eight months after taking office, building a war chest aimed at
deterring any serious challenge to his re-election in 2002. In all,
not bad for a 57-year-old cautious but ambitious career politician
who was long scorned as the dullest, most unprepossessing player in
the California political pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been underestimated my whole life, and I don't want it to
change,'' Davis said with a self-mocking chuckle in an interview in
his office late last week. ``It's my greatest strength. You know,
this whole business is exceeding expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the expectations are higher. When Davis proposes his second
state budget on Monday, the news will still be good: An expected $3
billion surplus in the roughly $65 billion budget will mean more
money for education, including college loans, bonuses and
fellowships for teachers, more summer-school sessions for
underperforming students and a tenfold increase, to 70,000, in the
number of teachers to be given extra training in reading, algebra
and other skills.
</P>
<P>
   In all, aides say, he will propose spending about $257 million
more on education than is required by law, more than twice the
level of extra spending he proposed last year.
</P>
<P>
   But a state Legislature that has learned to take Davis' pledge
of moderation seriously will be demanding far more on a host of
fronts. Democrats, who control both chambers, want more spending on
mental health and the homeless, while Republicans want to halve
tuition at the University of California and California State
University systems.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful teachers union, which backed Davis strongly, is
sponsoring a fall ballot measure aimed at raising the state's
per-pupil spending _ which now lags in the bottom third _ to the
national average at a cost of nearly $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he would oppose that measure because it would require
a tax increase, which would break his campaign vow ``to do my level
best within the resources that the economy provides.'' He has also
vowed to veto every new gun control measure that comes before him
until those passed last year have had some time to be tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm vetoing those bills,'' the governor said. ``They're
wonderful bills, but we've done enough for this year. Let's wait
until the prosecutors and the police come back to us'' and are
prepared to deal with more.
</P>
<P>
   The smart money in Sacramento predicts some rough sailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, he's had such a good first year, it's going to be
tough,'' said Richard Ross, a veteran Democratic political
consultant who is friendly to Davis but does not work for him.
``Listen, repeating is tough. I'm sure he's quite aware of it, and
he's seeing now that it's almost harder to govern in times of
plenty. The list of demands will always exceed the results.''
</P>
<P>
   The shrewdest of Davis' liberal legislative scourges is the
leader of the state Senate, John Burton of San Francisco, who has
called for a major effort to address the problems of the mentally
ill who were deinstitutionalized and swelled the homeless
population in cities like his.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment the other day on Davis' first year, Burton
puckishly proposed: ``Why don't you just rewrite Time?'' referring
to the news magazine's depiction of Davis last fall as ``The Most
Fearless Governor in America,'' a headline that prompted gales of
derision in the capital, where Davis stays close to the 50-yard
line on almost every issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known the guy since 1972,'' Burton said, ``so I don't get
disappointed and I don't get upset. He is what he is, and I am what
I am and it's no big deal to me. I think last year there was some
feeling around, but there was a tremendous willingness and desire
on our part to help him be successful. I think this year will be a
little bit different. He'll have his point of view, we'll have
ours, and we'll try to work it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis himself acknowledged some rocky moments with his
legislative colleagues, as in a celebrated eruption last summer
when the governor, frustrated that legislators were sending him a
raft of health care bills that might be costly or contradictory,
declared, ``Their job is to implement my vision.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, legislative leaders groused that Davis, famously
disciplined in the details of fund raising and electioneering, had
been slow to fill appointive posts and occasionally seemed
underprepared in policy discussions.
</P>
<P>
   But no one has accused Davis, a former lieutenant governor,
controller and assemblyman and the first Democrat to lead the state
in 16 years, of not doing his political homework.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he and his chief political adviser, Garry South, have
what amounts to a unified field theory of California politics,
which holds that the only way to win and govern successfully
statewide is as a resolute moderate, able to win support not only
in the coastal urban centers but in the rapidly growing inland
suburbs and the Central Valley.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because Davis cut his political teeth as chief of staff to
former Gov. Jerry Brown, the last Democrat to lead California,
politicians in both parties assumed that his moderate stance in
last year's campaign was largely tactical, a page from the
playbooks of President Clinton and Prime Minister Tony Blair of
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, South notes, Davis has always been hard to pigeonhole,
the only Democrat in a staunchly Republican family, who was
inspired to enter politics after serving as an Army captain in
Vietnam and seeing how the war was being fought disproportionately
by minorities and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the candidates I have ever worked with, Gray is the
most anomalous blend of conservative beliefs and progressive
instincts,'' South said. ``He's a longtime vociferous supporter of
the death penalty. He was the only statewide Democratic elected
official in California in 1996 to support Clinton's signing of the
welfare bill. At the same time, he's a strong supporter of workers'
rights to organize, of health and safety regulations, with an
almost unequaled record on environmental protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis himself said simply: ``There's nothing government can do
to substitute for a growing economy. Twenty-five, 30 years ago I
might have thought differently, but now I'm convinced that
government has to do a few things and do them well.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he thought much of the recent federal devolution of
power to the states had worked well, especially in areas like
welfare, but he has continued to press hard, for example, for more
federal money for jailing illegal immigrants who commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis also said ``it would take me about an hour'' to simply
list California's biggest needs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what changes in the economy, or what unanticipated
problems might cause him to rethink his opposition to any tax
increase, the governor said: ``I don't want to go down that road.
What I tell people today is that we're experiencing the best
economy known in the history of man, and the problems that I
inherited, almost across the board, took 25 or 30 years to develop,
and we can't expect to solve them in one year.''
</P>
<P>
   Given California's size, and his success, Davis' name inevitably
surfaces as a potential vice presidential candidate, but he pledges
to serve out his term and expects to run for another.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just any state,'' he said. ``This is the
seventh-largest economy in the world, and I'm not going to trade
that in for the job of adviser, and that's what the vice president
is.'' Few doubt that Davis would prefer to wait for a potential run
for the presidency itself.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Davis seems to be savoring the rewards of his
gradualism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The times demanded that he basically leave well enough alone,
and any changes he was going to make be incremental,'' said state
Sen. Jim Brulte of Rancho Cucamonga, one of the capital's chief
Republican strategists, who praised the governor for incorporating
about seven major Republican proposals into his coming budget.
``And clearly that's his style, so that's a good match for
California. The first rule of a physician is `Do no harm,' and I
think Gray Davis has adopted that as a political axiom, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
