<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1094 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-FINANCE-1STLD-     01-09 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-FINANCE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN PURSUES AGGRESSIVE STRATEGY OF OPENNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to add 2nd take with fresh news from McCain's campaign trail.
Modifies 2nd and 4th grafs of 1st take for clarification.) 
(mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Faced with a campaign finance controversy at a
critical juncture of the presidential race, John McCain, the former
Navy aviator, has adopted the tactic of flying straight into the
political flak.
</P>
<P>
   In a strategy calculated to demonstrate that he has nothing to
hide, the Republican senator from Arizona released hundreds of
letters he has written to regulators as chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee, some of them benefiting campaign contributors.
He has also asked federal agencies to open their files of his
letters.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday, as in last week's debates, he was on television
again patiently dealing with questions about letters like the ones
he wrote to the Federal Communications Commission on behalf of
Paxson Communications and other companies whose executives have
been his contributors.
</P>
<P>
   His avowed goal is to persuade the public that the letters
demonstrate not some kind of political hypocrisy, but rather, as he
said today on the CBS program ``Face the Nation,'' a ``clear
pattern of my acting on behalf of my constituents and consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a risk as well: that the volume of letters, the
vast majority of them seemingly unconnected to any donors, might
leave the impression of a lawmaker constantly intervening on behalf
of business, if only to urge speedy action by federal agencies. Or
even that somewhere in the pile of correspondence there is
something his critics might turn against him.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain's insurgent candidacy, built largely on his cries for
campaign finance reform, this could be a make-or-break moment. It
comes far too close for comfort to his golden opportunity for an
upset of Gov. George W. Bush in New Hampshire. Yet his aides say
they believe there is also enough time, with three weeks to go
before that Feb. 1 primary, for him to recover.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator, who is neck-and-neck in the polls with Bush
in New Hampshire, appears to be the only one standing between Bush
and the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   So, taking advantage of the hyperkinetic pace of modern campaign
news cycles, McCain's counter-barrage of openness this weekend
marked an effort by the senator to bring the controversy to a close
with the Sunday talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   The risk that unknown problems in the volumes of records might
lie ahead is related to the complexity of the issues involved, and
the layers and varieties of campaign donations from companies,
lawyers and lobbyists, including donations to the senator's past
congressional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The letters McCain wrote touch on arcana that are often
difficult for the average voter to grasp. Often it is unclear
whether McCain was even aware of the details of the letters he
signed, or whether the staff that prepared them could have known
about campaign contributions _ which in any event sometimes came
after the letters were drafted.
</P>
<P>
   Was an airline's plan to offer service in Flagstaff, Ariz.,
anticompetitive, as the city managers thought? he asked the
Department of Transportation. (It was not, came the reply.)
</P>
<P>
   Please consider the views of FareSearch, a Tucson, Ariz.,
company that researches air fares, when studying the
ticket-purchasing practices of consumers who try to outsmart the
airlines on fares, he implored the General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   But other letters involved multibillion-dollar communications
mergers and substantial campaign contributions; and in some cases
it is hard to discern whether related contributions might have been
made, or by whom.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates doubtless will now face similar questions.
</P>
<P>
   While traveling through Des Moines, Iowa, on Sunday, former Sen.
Bill Bradley, a Democratic candidate, was asked whether he would
allow letters to federal agencies that he wrote while on the Senate
Finance Committee to be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly have no problem with that,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a senator I had a basic policy and that was I did not
intervene in regulatory matters,'' he said, although he might have
intervened on behalf of New Jersey, his home state, before agencies
like the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would write a letter to HUD saying give Newark (N.J.) the
grant but I did not intervene on behalf of people in a regulatory
process. I can't think of any time I did that in the U.S. Senate.
Somebody pulls up and finds one somewhere, I'd be extremely
surprised because I had that as a basic policy,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   It is often said that the outcome of campaign crises turns less
on specific allegations than on how a candidate handles them. So
the last few days have been instructive in taking the measure of
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   He has steadfastly refused to go into hiding. In fact, he did
not come off of the campaign trail for a moment. Nor did he
distance himself in any way from the press.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after a youth forum in New Hampshire
Sunday, McCain said, ``The worst thing you can do is get diverted
by something like this, which puts you off your game and causes
your wife to cry.'' His wife, Cindy, who was at his side, burst out
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   He has said repeatedly that he learned lessons from watching his
friend Bob Dole campaign in 1996 and that he thought Dole made a
terrible mistake when he locked himself away from reporters after
he caused a furor by saying that tobacco was not addictive.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his greatest assets was his relationship with the
media,'' McCain said recently, saying that Dole inexplicably cut
himself off from reporters who had covered him for years on Capitol
Hill, ``who knew him well and liked him. What do I mean by liking?
That they wouldn't sandbag him.''
</P>
<P>
   So, riding through South Carolina on Saturday afternoon on the
bus he calls the ``Straight Talk Express,'' McCain chattered to
reporters about how the New Hampshire cold aggravates the arthritis
in his bones broken during his captivity as a prisoner of war in
Vietnam. He discussed brands of long underwear. He accused a
reporter who had skipped covering one of his town meetings of being
AWOL and in need of court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   His television appearance Sunday allowed him to touch on broader
campaign themes. He was soon going after the size of Bush's tax
cut. ``Gov. Bush said that Washington is awash in cash,'' he said.
``We've got a $5.6 trillion debt.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was able to give a more nuanced view of the controversy
in South Carolina over the Confederate flag than Bush did in a
debate on Friday night, when he insisted that it should be a local
issue and resisted several opportunities to talk about his own
feelings about the flag.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McCain, too, said that he thought the decision about the flag
should be made locally. But he said of his own feelings: ``The
Confederate flag is offensive in many, many ways as we all know.
It's a symbol of racism and slavery. But I also understand how
others do not view it in that fashion. My forebears from
Mississippi fought under the Confederate flag. They were not slave
owners. And I'm sure that they considered their service _ one I
believe died at Shiloh _ was honorable.''
</P>
<P>
   There were signs Sunday that McCain might have turned the
corner, at least with the Sunday talk show pundits. Bob Schieffer,
the host of ``Face the Nation,'' said to him of the letters his
committee had released, ``I must say in all fairness, I've been in
Washington a long time, they look a lot like letters most committee
chairmen write to the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important question is whether voters, who have been
warming to McCain's themes and humor, accept his explanations.
</P>
<P>
   In Camden, S.C., on Saturday, Laura Rose, a 40-year-old nurse
who is leaning toward supporting McCain and had come to see him at
a barbecue, had not even heard of the regulatory matter. Her friend
Janice Cozzens, a 42-year-old artist, was dismissive of it. ``To
me, that's piddling little stuff,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And in New Hampshire Sunday, Stephen Connelly, 50, a Bell
Atlantic technician, said he saw McCain as a man of honesty. ``I
think that's a point of character, that he has said he has probably
been influenced by campaign money,'' Connelly said. ``I respect the
man for at least starting out by saying, `Me.'''
</P>
<P>
   But another voter, Elaine Langer, a retiree living in Hooksett,
N.H., said she had been leaning toward McCain until she decided
that his opposition to gun control was not strong enough. And she
said the letters he wrote sealed her decision to vote for either
Bush or Steve Forbes. ``I was a little disappointed,'' she said.
``I thought the way he talked he'd be more or less out of that kind
of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, McCain hopes to turn the debate in the Republican
presidential race to tax cutting and Social Security. He plans to
unveil his own tax-cut proposal on Tuesday, one that takes the
unorthodox approach of bringing class considerations, usually a
staple of Democratic politics, to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been going after Bush's proposal, saying it uses too
much of the federal surplus and gives too many benefits for the
wealthy. His own plan, he said Sunday, is ``going to give tax
relief to about 25 million Americans, low- and middle-income. It's
not going to give a lot of relief to the very rich.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
