<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-VIKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS' SMITH RUNS THE COWBOYS BACK HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Dallas Cowboys entered Sunday's game the way
all Vikings opponents do: by picking their pain and attempting to
escape at least one of the two dangers presented by the Minnesota
Vikings' balanced inside-outside offense. Dallas decided it would
focus on the outside threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys insisted, in so many words, that they would not be
riddled and ripped by the Vikings' top receivers, Cris Carter and
Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   But the riddle and rip came anyway _ but from the inside, in the
person of running back Robert Smith. He was the difference as
Minnesota beat Dallas, 27-10, before 64,065 fans in the Metrodome.
And his performance allowed the Vikings to advance in the playoffs
for a meeting with the Rams in St. Louis next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith rushed for 140 yards, a Vikings playoff record. He
averaged 5 yards a carry, helped the Vikings gain nine rushing
first downs, and enabled them to lead Dallas in rushing attempts by
38-16 and in rushing yardage by 175-111. In the second quarter, he
added a 26-yard catch-and-run touchdown on a screen pass.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and after Smith broke Dallas down, Moss (with a 58-yard
scoring catch just before halftime) and Carter (who had a 5-yard
scoring grab in the fourth quarter, concluding the scoring) offered
a riddle and a rip, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to expect that both our running game and passing game
would explode at some time in the game, so I don't know how they
went about choosing to play us,'' Smith said. ``It just didn't work
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota line _ center Jeff Christy, guards David Dixon and
Randall McDaniel and tackles Todd Steussie and Korey Stringer,
along with the blocking of the three tight ends _ was marvelous.
The line pounded the Cowboys, draining their stamina, especially in
the second half when Minnesota, already leading by 17-10, outscored
Dallas by 10-0. On defense, Minnesota took advantage of a variety
of Dallas mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   As for the quarterbacks, the Vikings' Jeff George (three
touchdown passes, no interceptions) outplayed Dallas' Troy Aikman
(no touchdown passes, one interception).
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, though, was hampered by dropped passes, broken routes,
missed assignments and mental miscues all day. Only Raghib Ismail
(8 catches and a game-high 163 receiving yards) made consistent
plays among Aikman's targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make that many mistakes, and there were different
types, those type of things don't give you a great chance to win,''
Chan Gailey, the Dallas coach, said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Green, the Vikings' coach, said: ``We feel real good
about the game. We ran the ball, and in the playoffs you have to do
that, along with not having turnovers and having field position.
Dallas clearly made some plays in the secondary, but the run was
there for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Smith is a big plus for us. He's running stronger. This
is the only time this year he's been healthy. He feels great, he
feels frisky and he wants the ball. He knows he can break tackles
and he can also use his speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith exhibited all of those skills against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, though, struck early.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith burst around left end for 65 yards to the Minnesota
3-yard line on the game's opening possession. But Dallas could not
get into the end zone and settled for a field goal. The Cowboys
then stopped the Minnesota offense on three plays, forcing the
Vikings to punt, but Deion Sanders muffed the reception at the
Dallas 30. That led to a Gary Anderson field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas was up by 10-3 at the end of the first quarter because it
had marched 79 yards on a drive capped by Emmitt Smith's 5-yard
scoring run. Its defensive plan looked sharp. Minnesota had not
gained any passing yards, and Robert Smith was being held in check.
</P>
<P>
   But early in the second quarter, Dallas fullback Robert Thomas
fumbled at his 23 and Robert Smith capitalized with his touchdown
on the screen play for a 10-10 tie. Then Moss, with 28 seconds left
in the half, beat cornerback Kevin Mathis in a jostling match on a
deep ball, a 58-yard touchdown strike by George. The Vikings were
ahead by 17-10 at halftime, and the Cowboys were deflated. Mathis
was called for pass interference on the play, but Moss and the
Vikings did not care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got open,'' Moss said. ``He had his hands up against my
chest. Once the ball started to come, I had to get him off me. This
was a game, with the way their safeties were playing, so deep and
out of the run picture, that somebody in the backfield had to get
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Smith did.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only do so much,'' Carter said about the way Dallas'
defense chose to defend against the pass rather than the run. ``And
you only get so many opportunities to make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas committed seven penalties, and a few of them were costly
ones that kept Minnesota drives in gear. Even late in the game,
when Dallas was trying to rally, driving from its 20 to the
Minnesota 19, receiver Jason Tucker took a third-and-8 pass to the
Minnesota 6, then fumbled the ball through the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep doing the same old thing you have always done,''
Sanders said of the Cowboys' play, ``you are going to get the same
old thing you have always got.''
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith said: ``We are an 8-9 team. Mediocre, up and down,
nothing consistent, and consistently bad at times, showing some
signs of brilliance and being a very good ballclub, but a team that
couldn't put it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota, however, is 9-2 in its last 11 games with George as
the starting quarterback. The Vikings have won four straight.
Minnesota is 11-6 now, but St. Louis is 13-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know about St. Louis is they have scored a lot of points
and won a lot of games,'' Robert Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Moss added about the matchup: ``They are supposed to be the
best. I think we are the best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
