<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SPENDING-CUTS-NYT     01-09 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPENDING-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PLANS $2.4 BILLION IN ACROSS-THE-BOARD CUTS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under orders from Congress, President Clinton will
cut $2.4 billion in federal spending by applying a scalpel to the
budgets of all government agencies and departments, the White House
said Sunday. Some of what he will excise from the 2000 budget is
special projects inserted for constituents by individual members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   About $1 billion will be cut from the Defense Department. In
addition, White House officials said, Clinton will cut $180 million
from the Transportation Department, $166 million from the
Department of Health and Human Services, $108 million from the
Education Department, $96 million from the Agriculture Department
and $91 million from the Department of Housing and Urban
Development. The remainder of the $2.4 billion will come from
smaller reductions elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ricci, a spokeswoman for the Office of Management and
Budget, said Clinton had tried to protect programs that he
considered particularly important.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ricci said he cut $477 million from more than 2,300 projects
for which Congress had earmarked specific amounts. Such projects
include roads, bridges and other public works, as well as weapons
systems and special programs at various hospitals, clinics,
schools, colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ms. Ricci said, the administration cut 5 percent
from spending for a Navy ship favored by the Senate Republican
leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi. In November, Lott got $375
million to begin building the ship, a $1.5 billion helicopter
carrier known as the LHD-8, though the Navy had not requested the
money. The ship will be built at the Ingalls shipyard in
Pascagoula, the largest private employer in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ricci said there will be no cuts in nutrition assistance for
low-income women and children, and no cuts in the Head Start
program for children from low-income families, or in child
immunization programs or child care or heating assistance for poor
people. Likewise, she said, there will be no cuts in the Superfund
program, for cleaning up toxic waste sites, or in the number of FBI
agents.
</P>
<P>
   But, Ms. Ricci said, Clinton will delete $100 million from
spending on buildings and laboratories at the National Institutes
of Health. She said the move could delay maintenance work, but
would not harm the quality of biomedical research financed by the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders of Congress and Clinton wrangled over
spending for most of last year. Many Republicans wanted to make
across-the-board cuts in federal spending. Clinton argued that such
automatic cuts were mindless. He and Congress eventually worked out
a deal that whittled down the size of the cuts to 0.38 percent of
each agency's appropriation and gave the president some discretion
on what to cut.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insisted that Clinton could carry out the law by
cutting wasteful or unnecessary spending.
</P>
<P>
   Federal spending is expected to exceed $1.7 trillion this year.
Only one-third of that amount was subject to the latest round of
cuts, which did not apply to benefit programs like Social Security,
Medicare and food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   A total of $191 million will be cut from 30 weapons systems,
White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also cut $192 million from salaries and related
expenses at federal agencies. But, Ms. Ricci said, the bulk of all
the savings, $1.7 billion, came from cuts in various government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ms. Ricci said, the Transportation Department is
cutting $63.5 million from federal grants to the states for highway
construction, and it is cutting $54 million meant for construction
of airports.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the department is cutting $61 million from specific
transportation projects earmarked by Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
