u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-SEAHAWKS     01-09 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-SEAHAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENT DOLPHINS SHUT DOWN SEAHAWKS AND KINGDOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Miami Dolphins did something Sunday they had not
done much of lately. They won a game.
</P>
<P>
   They shook off their late-season collapse, ignored the soap
opera swirling around the futures of quarterback Dan Marino and
Coach Jimmy Johnson and rallied to a 20-17 victory over the Seattle
Seahawks in the American Football Conference wild-card playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to win this game and I told the team
that,'' Johnson said. ``We had preparation this week like I haven't
seen in a long time. You lose games and your confidence gets
broken. But our guys got a reprieve getting into the playoffs. One
win can do a lot of things, especially a playoff win. Before the
game even started we were shouting, `Let's go to Jacksonville.'''
</P>
<P>
   And they will. The Dolphins advanced will play the Jaguars at
Jacksonville on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks, meanwhile, made the last game ever played in the
Kingdome a forgettable one.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams staggered into the playoffs, losing five of their
final six regular-season games to finish at 9-7. But in their first
post-season appearance since 1988, the Seahawks kept staggering.
They blew two leads against Miami, gained only 32 yards in the
second half and watched Marino engineer the type of 85-yard scoring
drive in the fourth quarter that he is famous for.
</P>
<P>
   After four Marino completions for 84 yards, the rookie running
back J.J. Johnson, playing with a sore leg, scored on a 3-yard run
with 4 minutes 48 seconds remaining in the game to give the
Dolphins their only lead, at 20-17. J.J. Johnson helped the
Dolphins dominate ball possession, gaining 86 yards on 27 carries,
and Miami made no turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan did a great job executing and he did a great job throwing
the ball,'' Jimmy Johnson said. ``We had to make some changes going
in because we knew it would be noisy. We did away with the shotgun,
went to the run, did away with turnovers and showed we could win at
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing with a lead, Miami's defense, which took charge of the
game in the second half, sacked the young Seattle quarterback John
Kitna on three consecutive plays to snuff out one possession.
Terrell Buckley, who had drafted by Seattle Coach Mike Holmgren in
Green Bay, intercepted Kitna's pass with 23 seconds left to seal
Miami's first road playoff victory since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was ours to win,'' Kitna said. ``But you give Dan
Marino too many opportunities and he's going to hurt you. That's
what he did. Now that we're out of it, I hope he gets the Super
Bowl he deserves and tops off his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino completed 17 of 30 passes for 196 yards and a 1-yard
touchdown to Oronde Gadsden. O.J. McDuffie and Tony Martin each had
five receptions. All but 28 of Marino's passing yards came in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to be conservative in the first half,'' said
Marino, whose team was held to 3 points in the first half. ``We
opened it up a little in the second half and I hit some plays. We
didn't turn the ball over and that gave us a chance to win at the
end. It worked perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna was 14 of 30 passing for 162 yards and a 9-yard touchdown
to Sean Dawkins, but he also had two interceptions and was sacked
six times. Seattle was held to 171 total yards and 41 on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Miami held the ball nearly 10 minutes more than
Seattle. Jimmy Johnson's game plan was designed as much to
neutralize the noisy Kingdome crowd as it was the home team. No
coach will ever have such a problem as the stadium will be
demolished in March and replaced with a new one by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren said his team's relative inexperience in postseason
games contributed to the loss, but not as much as simply being
outplayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inability to execute physically hurt us more,'' said
Holmgren, who took Seattle to the playoffs in his first season as
coach and general manager. ``Certainly, a lack of experience hurt
us, but it didn't determine the outcome of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Field position dictated the first-quarter results. Starting at
the Miami 47-yard line, Kitna moved the Seahawks quickly with four
completed passes, two to Mike Pritchard, the last the 9-yard
touchdown to Dawkins for the first score of the game. The Dolphins
responded with a 32-yard field goal by Olindo Mare and Seattle led
at the end of the first quarter, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   The only second-quarter points came in the final minute of the
half on a 50-yard field goal by Seattle's Todd Peterson after a
seven-play drive stalled. Ricky Watters touched the ball on six of
those plays, but he was tripped up by safety Shawn Wooden on
third-and-1 at the 32 for no gain to force the field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Playing despite a balky knee, Watters was the only ball carrier
for the Seattle offense in the half, carrying 15 times for 38
yards. He ran four more times in the second half for 2 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dolphins were so conservative with an equally
ineffective running game that the offense was limited to 69 yards,
half of Seattle's 139, and only 23 yards through the air.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson let Marino open things up in the second half, which
started with great field position when Peterson's kickoff went out
of bounds. Marino completed an 11-yard pass to McDuffie on the
first play, completed six passes on the drive and capped it with
the 2-yard touchdown pass to Gadsden for a 10-10 tie.
</P>
<P>
   But the tie lasted only as long as it took the rookie Charlie
Rogers to return the kickoff 85 yards for a touchdown. The Seahawks
were back on top, 17-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys could have crumbled at that point,'' Jimmy Johnson
said. ``But we came right back with some points.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami responded later in the quarter. Autry Denson, giving J.J.
Johnson a breather, ripped off runs of 18 and 11 yards. Mare nailed
a 51-yard field goal to cut the lead to 17-13. Wooden recovered
Mare's successful onside kick, but Miami could not score until
Marino put together the decisive drive late in the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
