<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-GAYS-NYT     01-09 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE GORE'S REVERSAL, CANDIDATES CRITICIZE `LITMUS TEST' FOR
JOINT CHIEFS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore faced new criticism Sunday
over his conflicting remarks last week on whether, as president, he
would require the Joint Chiefs of Staff to support allowing gays to
serve openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, Gore backtracked from his statement during a
debate on Wednesday that he would make support for such a policy a
requirement for his nominees for the Joint Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said he would simply require them to follow his
orders as commander in chief and not impose a ``litmus test'' on
their personal views.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the reversal, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a Republican
presidential candidate, Sunday criticized Gore's views, saying they
would have ``a terrible effect on the civilian-military
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what he's backed off to; I guess it depends,''
McCain said during an appearance on the CBS news program ``Face the
Nation.'' ``But his initial statement showed me an incredible lack
of understanding of the role of the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in an appearance before the New Hampshire State Republican
Committee, McCain elaborated, saying that questions about ``a
social agenda'' have no place in deciding who should lead the
military. ``The job of the chairman of the Joint Chiefs is to give
the president the best advice'' about military matters. He added,
``Don't ask, don't tell works. I'll support it; I'll continue to
improve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the NBC program ``Meet the Press,'' one of Gore's
campaign advisers, Bob Shrum, insisted that the vice president had
not significantly altered his position, which provoked criticism
from Republicans and retired officers who said Gore's initial stand
would have politicized the process of selecting chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., who appeared with Shrum on the
program, disagreed. ``He made a major mistake,'' said Nadler, who
is supporting Gore's opponent for the Democratic nomination, former
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey. ``He admitted it. He retreated. He
changed his position.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over Gore's position underscored the resonance of the
issue in this year's campaign. The Republican National Committee
had already produced a television advertisement saying that former
Gens. Colin L. Powell and H. Norman Schwarzkopf would not have been
able to pass ``Al Gore's litmus test.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadler and Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said they would press for
legislation to change the current ``don't ask, don't tell'' law,
which allows gays to serve in the military provided they do not
disclose their sexual orientation or engage in homosexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, who is one of three openly gay members of Congress, said
it was time to review the Uniform Code of Military Justice, noting
that it prohibited not only homosexual acts, but other acts, like
sex between unmarried heterosexual couples, that society viewed as
private issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that's a little outdated,'' said Frank, who also
appeared on NBC's ``Meet the Press.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who expressed support for allowing gays to serve but
stopped short of saying he would impose a ``litmus test'' on
appointees to the Joint Chiefs, declined Sunday to say how or when
he would order the Pentagon to allow gays to serve openly.
</P>
<P>
   But appearing on ``Fox News Sunday,'' he said the fact that
Congress had turned ``don't ask, don't tell'' into law made a
change more difficult than in 1993, when President Clinton was
forced to retreat from his campaign pledge to allow gays to serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to consult with people,'' Bradley said. ``You'll
definitely consult with the military. This is not something you're
going to do in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he supported the current policy and suggested that a
review of it would not be appropriate in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to change it, I don't think we talk about that
in a political campaign,'' he said. ``We talk about it after we
become the president and say, `I'll have a review of the policy.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
