<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-TAX-POLITICS-2TAKES-N     01-09 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S IDEAS ON TAXES AND SOCIAL SECURITY DEFY GOP THINKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MCCAIN-FINANCE) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After decades in which Republican presidential
candidates have reflexively promoted tax cuts as the key to
prosperity and electoral success, Sen. John McCain of Arizona is
betting that there is a more potent issue this time around: Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   His strategy casts McCain in a role that President Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore have played to the advantage of Democrats:
suggesting that too big a tax cut would be fiscally irresponsible,
disproportionately benefit the wealthy and endanger efforts to
shore up Social Security before the vast baby boom generation
retires. And it has set off a clash with his chief Republican
rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, over whether tax cuts have
lost their punch as a political issue, especially when the economy
is so strong.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few weeks, McCain has sought to highlight the
contrast between his plan, which would devote the bulk of projected
federal budget surpluses to overhauling the retirement system, and
the big tax-cut proposal by Bush, the Republican front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   It is a contrast that Bush has been equally happy to emphasize.
The result is a developing showdown between Bush's adherence to a
venerable Reaganesque approach of winning over the conservative
Republican base with a traditional tax-cutting message and McCain's
belief that voters are more worried about their long-term economic
security than about having a lower tax bill today.
</P>
<P>
   Questioning the wisdom of big tax cuts holds considerable risks
for McCain as he tries to defeat Bush in New Hampshire, a state
where Republicans are ardent tax cutters. And McCain's strategy in
effect wipes out one of Bush's greatest vulnerabilities in the
primaries: the suspicion among some conservatives that like
President Bush, who broke a pledge not to raise taxes, the Texas
governor is more moderate than he talks on fiscal issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain has allowed Bush to get to the right of him on fiscal
and tax policy,'' said Stephen Moore, director of fiscal policy
studies at the Cato Institute, a conservative research
organization. ``McCain has quite irresponsibly echoed Clinton's
objections to tax cuts in a way that could come back to haunt the
Republicans in the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some analysts say McCain may be astutely tapping into a
shift in national priorities. They say voters are less focused than
in earlier years on improving their current economic condition at a
time when jobs are plentiful and incomes are rising, and are
increasingly convinced that the benefits of the current prosperity
should be used to address tomorrow's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we seem to have moved from irrational exuberance
to rational responsibility, where tax cuts don't resonate as
strongly as they once did,'' said David C. John, a policy analyst
at the Heritage Foundation, a conservative research group. ``Part
of it is that in a time of prosperity the tax bill doesn't hit as
hard. But people also seem to have a real recognition that Social
Security is in trouble and that we should make hay while the sun is
shining.''
</P>
<P>
   Conceding that their efforts to enact a big tax cut over the
last few years have gone nowhere, Republican leaders in the House
this week said they would concentrate on passing a number of
smaller tax bills. And most polling on the issue in the last year
has found Social Security consistently outranking tax cuts as a
priority among voters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is by no means forswearing tax cuts. He plans to set out
a detailed proposal on Tuesday that his advisers say will benefit
lower- and middle-income taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers said the plan would expand the current 15 percent
bracket to higher income levels, reduce the so-called marriage
penalty paid by many two-income couples, provide tax breaks for
savings and expand the child credit. Like Bush's plan, they said,
McCain's would provide substantial benefits to people in the lower
middle class.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, they said, McCain's proposal would create a new
type of savings account, patterned after the Individual Retirement
Account, that would give the greatest benefit to people in the
lowest income tax bracket of 15 percent. Contributions up to $3,000
per taxpayer would be tax-deductible, with any gains subject to
ordinary income tax as long as the money remains in the account for
at least one year.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will also propose expanded education and retirement
savings plans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his proposal is likely to be no more than half as large
as Bush's plan, which the Bush campaign values at $483 billion over
five years. And rather than pay for his entire tax cut out of the
surplus, McCain plans to finance it in part by closing corporate
tax loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe,'' said Dan Schnur, McCain's communications
director, ``that a significant tax cut coupled with a Social
Security solution is much more efficient from both a policy and a
political standpoint than a huge tax cut that doesn't address
Social Security at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has repeatedly attacked McCain over the last week for not
backing a bigger tax cut, suggesting that McCain sounds more like
Vice President Gore than a Republican when it comes to tax cuts.
And he has asserted that unless the money is kept out of Washington
by cutting taxes, politicians will inevitably spend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush simply rejects the zero-sum mentality that says you
can't both save Social Security and cut taxes,'' said Ari
Fleischer, Bush's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In their debate on Friday, the two leading Republicans sparred
again on fiscal issues.
</P>
<P>
   McCain called it ``fiscally irresponsible to promise a huge tax
cut that is based on a surplus that we may not have.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the two had ``a fundamental disagreement,'' telling
McCain that the surplus ``will go to Washington under your idea,
and under my idea it goes into people's pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent official projections are for the surplus to
total $3 trillion over the next decade, of which $2 trillion would
come from excess Social Security revenue. The surpluses could
evaporate if the economy turns down or if Congress spends at higher
rates than now assumed. But preliminary estimates suggest that
updated projections scheduled to be released by the White House and
the Congressional Budget Office in the next few weeks could give
the candidates as much as $800 billion more to play with.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush, McCain has pledged to reserve the $2 trillion Social
Security surplus to shore up the retirement system. Like Bush,
McCain says the best way to do so is to create a system of private
accounts within Social Security that would allow workers to invest
part of their payroll taxes in stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain has gone beyond Bush in proposing to use 62 percent
of the non-Social Security surplus, more than $600 billion in the
next decade under current projections, to help finance the private
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's advisers said his plan would go much further in
assuring Social Security's long-term solvency than Bush's plan,
although they declined to provide any details to support their
assertion.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, the real debate over Social Security may not be
the differences between McCain and Bush over how extensive a system
of private investment accounts should be established. Instead, it
is far more likely to be between the general Republican position in
favor of privatization and the insistence of most Democrats that
individuals not be exposed to the risks of investing in the
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The debate could be especially complicated if the market
continues the volatile seesaw pattern that left even the most
seasoned investors off balance over the last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
