<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GATEWAY PLANS TO USE CHIPS FROM ADVANCED MICRO AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The computer maker Gateway, which has attributed an earnings
shortfall to chip-supply problems caused by Intel, plans to
announce Monday that it will again be using microprocessors
produced by Intel's archrival, Advanced Micro Devices.
</P>
<P>
   Only last year, Gateway switched from buying some chips from
Advanced Micro to relying on Intel alone. But last week the company
described Intel's shipments as ``severely constrained, spotty and
unreliable.'' Executives said that the company would not remain so
dependent on a sole supplier.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH TELECOM CONSIDERS ESAT BID
</P>
<P>
   British Telecommunications is considering a bid for Esat Telecom
Group, possibly rescuing it from a hostile offer from Telenor of
Norway, executives close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT SEEN IN THE COUNTERCULTURE
</P>
<P>
   After years of being accused of selling out by their passionate,
political writers and readers, many publishers of alternative
weeklies are basking in the comforts of capitalism, as the sale of
The Village Voice demonstrated last week. The sassy fringe of the
newspaper industry is now getting attention from private investors
who have come to believe that alternative weeklies, perennial
prodigals, are reservoirs of value.
</P>
<P>
   THE EVOLUTION OF SILICON VALLEY
</P>
<P>
   The Internet boom is bringing sweeping demographic changes to
Silicon Valley, according to an annual report card for the region,
which shows that in 1999 for the first time the number of nonwhite
residents surpassed that of whites. The influx of new immigrants is
also increasing an income disparity between skilled workers and
those in the service industries.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE HOLIDAY SALES STILL GUESSWORK
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the Commerce Department will announce estimates of
retail sales for December, putting a solid number on the 1999
holiday season. Those wishing to gain a better sense of the
e-commerce results, however, will be out of luck. Policy-makers,
investors and analysts will have to resort to their own
crystal-ball formulations, put together from shards of statistics
and economic assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   A new holiday survey of seasoned Internet users showed that a
majority bought more books online than in standard stores.
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITES SEEK PROFIT IN POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Internet start-ups are hoping to make money in
campaign politics, a world traditionally dominated by nonprofit and
volunteer groups. But as these commercial political sites strive to
cash in on campaign advertising, they are finding it difficult to
earn credibility with candidates and the public.
</P>
<P>
   A DIFFERENT MADNESS ALTOGETHER
</P>
<P>
   When John Hummer, co-founding partner of the venture capital
firm Hummer Winblad Venture Partners and Princeton's starting
center in 1969, created a collegiate competition for Internet
business plans, he figured ``March Madness'' had a nice ring to it.
The National Collegiate Athletic Association thought otherwise,
contending that the name infringed on a trademark reserved for the
NCAA basketball tournament. So the new name for the Hummer Winblad
tournament is the February Madness Start-Up Tournament: Nothin' but
the Net.
</P>
<P>
   PRICELINE EXPANDS TO CREDIT CARDS
</P>
<P>
   Priceline is set to announce a name-your-own- price credit-card
system Monday. But there is only one card issuer _ NextCard _
rather than competing providers as in most of Priceline's other
markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
