<HEADER>
A1125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-MEET-NYT &LR;      01-09 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-MEET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PUT THEIR DIFFERENCES ASIDE FOR ONE NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. _ While Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has been
scolded even by his own supporters for neglecting the voters of New
Hampshire last year, there were no signs of displeasure at a dinner
here Sunday night attended by more than 1,000 of the state's most
active Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was welcomed with a far more boisterous outpouring than any
of the five other Republican contenders who appeared, including
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who is leading Bush in some polls in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The audience reaction at the dinner at the University of New
Hampshire, a fund-raising event for the state's Republican Party,
is not necessarily representative of how Bush will perform in the
first primary in the nation on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But it demonstrated the degree to which many of this state's
Republicans appear to have rallied to his cause. In addition, many
have apparently forgiven him for being the only contender to pass
up speaking at the party's fund-raising dinner last year.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief address Sunday night, Bush stuck mostly to his
basic stump speech about cutting taxes, improving education and
restoring dignity to the White House. But the governor went out of
his way to praise the elected officials who endorsed him in this
state, as well as to fondly recall his trips to New Hampshire last
year, seeming to make the case that he had been here more than
people thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the memories of walking the Fourth of July parade in
Merrimack, Amherst _ or meeting people on the shores of Lake
Winnipesaukee in the summer,'' he said wistfully. ``I remember the
numerous town hall meetings like the one in Dixville Notch, where I
spoke to everybody in the entire town.'' (When Bush finally
ventured to Dixville Notch, in the far northern reaches of New
Hampshire last fall, McCain had already been there twice.)
</P>
<P>
   Although New Hampshire voters expect presidential candidates to
shower them with attention and more attention, they seemed
forgiving of Bush. ``Being the favored national candidate, he had
to spend time in the other states,'' said Stu Gilman, 42, a
software company owner in Weare, N.H., who sported a Bush sticker.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, who had upbraided one another in a frenzy of
debates in recent days, took care Sunday night to appear nice to
one another in front of the partisan audience. Several took aim at
the Democratic contenders, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen.
Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   McCain drew cheers when he castigated the two Democratic
candidates for saying they would expect their appointees to the
Joint Chiefs of Staff to support their positions allowing gays in
the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not qualified to be commander in chief of the armed
forces of the United States,'' McCain said, arguing that it is
inappropriate for a president to appoint military leaders who
follow their ``social agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond speaking about broad policy matters, the Republicans here
also sought to curry favor with voters in this state by trying to
find local common ground with New Hampshirites.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the wealthy publisher, opened his remarks with a
tribute to Nackey Loeb, the owner of the Union Leader of
Manchester, who died on Friday and was a revered figure among many
conservatives here. ``We mourn her passing,'' he said. ``Let us be
guided by her spirit.'' (It was also a gentle way for Forbes to
remind people that he received the newspaper's prized endorsement.)
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch of Utah also did his best to play up his
bonafides with the Loeb family, saying, ``I go back a long time
with Nackey.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain went further than anyone else in promising that his
attorney general would be former Sen. Warren B. Rudman of New
Hampshire, one of his top advisers and a popular figure in
Republican politics here.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the 6-year-old boy whom the Clinton administration
has decided to return to his father in Cuba, McCain said, ``I'd
have an attorney general of the United States, Warren Rudman, who
would be doing everything in his power to show we wouldn't send the
kid back.''
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, McCain, who is concentrating virtually his
entire campaign in this state, paid tribute to the University of
New Hampshire Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush stayed above the fray, his aides were quick to
pounce on McCain for focusing Sunday night on foreign policy _ not
his signature issue of campaign finance. His decision to not
discuss the issue comes after McCain has been pounded for days in
the press for sending letters to regulators on behalf of campaign
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting that on the issue of tax cuts and campaign
finance, Senator McCain obviously felt his position would not be
popular in front of a Republican crowd,'' said Karen P. Hughes,
Bush's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner, billed as ``A Salute to the Next President of the
United States,'' was designed as one last opportunity for this
state's Republican Party to cash in on New Hampshire's electoral
muscle only three weeks before the primary here. Most participants
paid $200 apiece; for $2,000, they met party luminaries at a
``millennium reception'' before the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   This was a particularly important audience for the candidates
because those who traveled to Durham Sunday night, near the coast
in the eastern part of the state, are the most active and loyal
members of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The folks in attendance tonight are the movers and shakers of
the Republican Party,'' said Mike Hickey, a telecommunications
executive in Manchester. ``So you're not going to see people
changing their minds tonight. But they'll come out with stronger
conventions about the candidate that they favor.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The evening was yet another opportunity for party loyalists in
this state to mingle with the White House hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Porter, a Harvard sophomore who is a Bush volunteer, stood
at the front door of the event, greeting supporters of the Texas
governor. But when he spotted Hatch, he ripped the ``Bush'' sticker
off his lapel, put his arm around the candidate's shoulder and
posed for a photograph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
