<P>
   (NYT12) ALLEGANY COUNTY, N.Y. -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- NY-OIL-WELLS --
Crude oil, water and rock fragments blow out of a newly-drilled
well bore moments after nitroglycerine was detonated at the bottom
of the well to fracture the oil-bearing strata and induce the flow
of oil in 1897. Well depths in the Allegany field typically ranged
from 1,000 to over 2,000 feet. Derricks standing over other wells
are visible downhill from this one. Some 135 years after New York
state's first marketable oil for sale started flowing from a hole
near here in western New York, the producers are trying to suck the
last drops from wells producing on average a quarter of a barrel a
day. (The New York Times/Courtesy of the Pioneer Oil Museum)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- METROPOLITAN-MUSEUM-FUNDS --
Philippe de Montebello, director of The Metropolitan Museum of Art,
which is planning major renovations. Since the museum cannot expand
into Central Park because of an agreement it made with the city in
the 1970s, it has been scouring its building for air shafts and
stairwells, neglected storage rooms and unused areas surrounding
skylights, any scrap of overlooked space, that could be used to
enlarge a gallery or create a new one. ``This is really a campaign
of ingenuity,'' says de Montebello. (Angel Franco/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- LOBSTER-THEATER-REVIEW-2 --
David Patrick Kelly as Salvador Dali and Reg Rogers as John Finch
in the Playwrights Horizons production of ``Lobster Alice.''
``Lobster Alice,'' which was inspired by a brief and little-known
chapter in Dali's career, accordingly presents a world in which
rigid logic and protocol melt like all those clocks in Dali's
``Persistence of Memory.'' (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- LOBSTER-THEATER-REVIEW --
Jessica Hecht and Derek Richardson in the Playwrights Horizons
production of ``Lobster Alice.'' Ms. Hecht plays a Hollywood
secretary named Alice Horowitz whose life is turned inside out by
an encounter with Salvador Dali in 1946. For a play that plunges
its characters into a vortex of mind-scrambling surrealism,
``Lobster Alice'' has a deeply conventional heart. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MOSCOW -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- RUSSIA-POLITICS -- This
photograph of Vladimir V. Putin, Russia's acting president, wearing
a judo outfit appears on the Russian government's Web site. A spate
of reports in the German press suggested this weekend that acting
President Vladmir Putin was decorated for his work as a KGB agent
in East Germany during the 1980s, and was even expelled from West
Germany at one point after being identified as a Soviet spy. (The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LOS ANGELES -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- CALIF-GOV -- For Gov. Gray
Davis of California, much of the last year has been a string of
media superlatives, legislative achievements, fiscal luck,
political popularity and, yes, success. Not bad for a 57-year-old
cautious but ambitious career politician who was long scorned as
the dullest, most unprepossessing player in the California
political pack. ``I've been underestimated my whole life, and I
don't want it to change,'' says Davis. ``It's my greatest strength.
You know, this whole business is exceeding expectations.'' (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) DUBA-YURT, Russia -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-2 --
A Russian soldier trudges through the muddy forward position of the
western group of Russian forces near the village of Duba-Yurt,
located just north of the Caucasian ridge, a stunning tableau of
rugged mountains, shrouded in mist. The Russians are trying to push
south into a gorge and destroy rebel bases on both sides. The
militants are struggling to move north toward Grozny and the
lowlands, hoping to regain the initiative and save their comrades
fighting in Grozny. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DUBA-YURT, Russia -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1 --
Russian soldiers near Duba-Yurt in Chechnya waiting to begin a
helicopter reconnaissance mission over mountains north of the
Caucasian ridge. The Russians are trying to push south into a gorge
and destroy rebel bases on both sides. The militants are struggling
to move north toward Grozny and the lowlands, hoping to regain the
initiative and save their comrades fighting in Grozny.(James
Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-REALNETWORKS -- Rob
Glaser, of RealNetworks and a former Microsoft executive announced
a deal last week under which the Universal Music Group will provide
music for use with his company's media-player software. With some
95 million registered users of its software, RealNetworks is
thought to have a commanding lead in the media-player market. But
lately the company's success has whetted the competitive appetite
of Glaser's former boss, Bill Gates. (Marty Katz/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- NEWSMAGS-ENTERTAINMENT-MEDIA
-- Joel Stein, a 28-year-old magazine columnist, likes to pepper
his columns with bawdy humor, tasteless one-liners and something
that can best be described as a sort of polished vulgarity. If you
think Stein writes for Penthouse, Maxim magazine or the local
campus newspaper, think again: He is a humor columnist for Time
magazine who considers himself a ``celebrity journalist,'' writing
pieces readers seem either to enjoy or despise. (Fred R. Conrad/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MIAMI -- Jan. 9, 2000 -- ROS-LEHTINEN-PROFILE -- Rep.
Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, 48, a Florida Republican and a fist-shaking
anti-communist, with some of her local constituents in Miami. Ms.
Ros-Lehtinen has been involved in the Elian Gonzalez case from the
start. A former state legislator who was elected to Congress in
1989, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen shrugs off her critics, who say she and
other politicians have turned the case of a little Cuban boy who
lost his mother into a political circus. ``I've visited many
families in my district, sometimes the media comes and sometimes it
doesn't,'' she says. ``I don't pick which one is the celebrated
case.'' (Laura Kleinhenz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ANNANDALE-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. -- Jan. 9, 2000 --
NIGERIAN-AUTHOR -- As Nigeria takes its first steps toward
democracy after a long spell of political repression, writer Chinua
Achebe is not in place to tell the tale. He has been unable to move
back to Nigeria not just because the country was, until recently,
in the grip of a corrupt dictatorship, but also because the civil
order, including a health-care system that can tend to his needs,
have all but collapsed. Now 69, he waits for things to fall into
place in Nigeria. And he waits to go home. ``I have chosen a
particular story, or maybe that story has chosen me.'' ``I just
find it useful, fruitful to be in that community, as a writer, as a
human being. There is so much to do.'' (G. Paul Burnett/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
