<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, January 10, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Greg Ambrose at 415-777-7219 or
the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running in
main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BIOSCOPE _  &LR;   &LR; The lobby of the Westin St. Francis Hotel should buzz
this week with talk of genes and proteins, worms that could teach
humans a thing or two, and sheep that might be coaxed into
producing drugs in their milk.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz will emanate from the Chase H&AMP;Q Life Sciences
conference, an annual event that gives biotech executives from 250
firms four days to schmooze with Wall Street money managers and
venture capitalists. COLUMN By TOM ABATE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FUTURE _  &LR;   &LR; San Francisco will peek into the future of biomedicine
Monday, when 4,000 money managers and venture capitalists flock
here for the opening of the four-day Chase H&AMP;Q Life Sciences
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   This year's conference opens as biotech stocks are hitting new
highs, in anticipation that completion of the human genome project
will usher in a new era in drug discovery. ``The year 2000 will be
viewed as the beginning of the genetic revolution,'' said John
Duane, co-director of McKinsey &AMP; Co.'s health care consulting
practice in Palo Alto. By TOM ABATE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; GADGETS _  &LR;  Las Vegas _ In one view of the future, a combination
CD/DVD player looks like a high-tech flower pot with a handle on
top. A DVD player resembles a hot plate with the unlikely color
combination of orange and silver, while another resembles a wooden
drum, or maybe a '60s-era end table. And in a throwback to the old
days when television sets always came in wooden cabinets, there is
a combination flat-panel TV-DVD player encased in a sleek wooden
pillar. By BENNY EVANGELISTA
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always great to see fresh designs, especially when
everything now is black or silver or gray,'' said showgoer Andy
Logan as he considered the curiously shaped electronic devices on
display at last week's Consumer Electronics Show here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; LATINO _  &LR;   &LR; Run by a staff of two and backed by a few maxed-out
credit cards, Web site LatinoLink.com still managed to attract a
loyal following among Hispanic Internet users. With content in both
Spanish and English, the 5-year-old site now draws 400,000 unique
visitors a month.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lavonne Luquis, the San Francisco entrepreneur behind
LatinoLink, has lined up $4 million in private placement funding,
increased her staff to 25 people and has big plans to morph her Web
zine into a portal. By CARRIE KIRBY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; LATINOSIDE _  &LR; Blame it on Ricky Martin, Jennifer Lopez or just the
mushrooming Latino population in the United States, but one thing
is clear: Web sites catering to Latinos _ once rare _ are now all
over the place. By Carrie Kirby
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERCRIME _  &LR; Top law enforcement officials from around the country
plan to converge in Palo Alto Monday to tackle ways of fighting a
troubling new wave of crimes _ those involving the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a handful of sleuths have been tracking down hackers
for years. But with the explosion of access to the Internet,
legions of pettier crimes are taking on a cybertwist. By Todd
Wallack
</P>
