<HEADER>
A1133 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE--COLUMN-SFCH     01-09 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HAPPY BIOTECH EXECS TO HOBNOB WITH MONEY MAVENS AT S.F. MEETINGS  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; The lobby of the Westin St. Francis Hotel should buzz this week
with talk of genes and proteins, worms that could teach humans a
thing or two, and sheep that might be coaxed into producing drugs
in their milk.
<P>
   The buzz will emanate from the Chase H&AMP;Q Life Sciences
conference, an annual event that gives biotech executives from 250
firms four days to schmooze with Wall Street money managers and
venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to last year's conference, when biotech stocks were
in the tank and the gathering was gloomy, today's opening session
comes amid a rebound so sharp that it has cured momentum investors
_ at least for now _ of their Internet addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in a long time, 70 percent of the companies
at the conference saw their stocks increase in market value in
1999,'' said Dennis Purcell, Chase H&AMP;Q's top biotech investment
banker and master of ceremonies at the event.
</P>
<P>
   That's a complete reversal from 1998 and 1997, when 70 percent
of the companies at the conference had suffered market value
declines, Purcell said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the sector began bouncing back in October, spurred by
excitement over looming completion of the Human Genome Project, 100
publicly traded biotech firms have seen their shares double in
value, Purcell said.
</P>
<P>
   This sudden good fortune isn't without its concerns. Purcell
fears the momentum investors who've fueled the run up may not
realize it could be a decade before gene data get turned into
drugs. ``The industry will have to learn to live with volatility in
2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investment banker Steve Burrill, who runs his own biotech
boutique in San Francisco, said volatility has been the industry's
consistent, if unfortunate, curse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public and private markets frequently over- or undervalue
biotech companies,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   But who can argue that it's an up market now, and one that has
rewarded recent biotech IPOs. Bay Area firms like Tularik, Caliper
and Maxygen have all soared since their fourth-quarter debuts. When
biotech has been hot in the past, the IPO window has stayed open
about nine months, Purcell said.
</P>
<P>
   So the private firms at this week's conference are blessed. They
have one shot to wow Wall Street during 30-minute slide shows made
to rooms packed crease to crease with suits. For instance, Exelixis
Inc. of South San Francisco will explain how it plans to make
investors rich by figuring out what fruit flies, worms and zebra
fish can teach us about human disease.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the presentations won't be that exotic. Blue-chip firms
like Genentech or Chiron will use their time to burnish their image
with the institutional money set. Rising stars like Gilead Sciences
_ which had a setback last year when an AIDS drug was unexpectedly
rejected _ will use their 30 minutes to convince investors another
stumble isn't coming.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing will be very new this year _ the Chase name on all
the conference banners. The New York megabank bought Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist for $1.35 billion in September. Like Montgomery Securities
and Robertson Stephens, which sold out before it, H&AMP;Q had been
homegrown and focused on technology, and on H&AMP;Q's part,
particularly on biotech.
</P>
<P>
   ``H&AMP;Q was the last of the boutiques to get eaten up by a big
concern,'' lamented Cynthia Robbins-Roth, a longtime industry
observer.
</P>
<P>
   Investment banks play a crucial role in taking private companies
public, and Robbins-Roth fears that biotech firms _ and their
venture backers _ will get short shrift as once-local bankers start
taking orders from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a vacuum of financiers who really know and want to
serve early stage biotech,'' says Robbins-Roth, predicting that a
new generation of boutique banks and VC firms will spring up to
finance firms too small for the giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far it's just rumblings,'' she says. ``But the people who
love biotech aren't going to be happy working for the big banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Purcell downplays such concerns, insisting it will be business
as usual at Chase H&AMP;Q _ except of course for the name. ``The Chase
management team has its finger on the pulse of the New Economy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, lucky Chase happened to finger biotech just as the
pulse of the industry started to race. We'll have to check back
when _ and it's more likely when than if _ the momentum players
tire of waiting for biotech to cure the common cold, taking their
money and some of the air out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
