<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1134 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-FUTURE-BIOTECH-SFCHRO     01-09 1742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-BIOTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH 2000: EXPERTS PREDICT THE CONCOCTIONS AND CONTROVERSIES 
 THAT WILL TRANSFORM BIOMEDICINE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. _ San Francisco will peek into the
future of biomedicine Monday, when 4,000 money managers and venture
capitalists flock here for the opening of the four-day Chase H&AMP;Q
Life Sciences Conference.
</P>
<P>
   This year's conference opens as biotech stocks are hitting new
highs, in anticipation that completion of the human genome project
will usher in a new era in drug discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year 2000 will be viewed as the beginning of the genetic
revolution,'' said John Duane, co-director of McKinsey &AMP; Co.'s
health care consulting practice in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Morrison, biotech consultant with Ernst &AMP; Young, said the
tools and techniques of bioscience, notably the ability to
manipulate molecules and create new compounds, are finding
application beyond the realm of medicine, opening markets in
agriculture and manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Given this burst of millennial optimism, The Chronicle asked
industry executives, scientists, financiers and observers to
identify trends that will chart the industry's course in 2000 and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Here are their predictions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gold rush: &LR;  The hottest word in biotech is genomics, the study
of genes and their functions. This year, researchers expect to
produce the first maps of the human genome _ rough charts pointing
to most of the genes that regulate life.
</P>
<P>
   The next step, according to San Francisco investment banker
Steve Burrill, will be identifying the subtle differences between
the genes of healthy people and the genes of people susceptible to
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists call these differences SNPs, or single nucleotide
polymorphisms.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take five to 15 years to develop drugs based on
knowledge gleaned from the gene maps and SNP databases. So it will
be a long, slow payoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fountain of controversy:  &LR; Biotech routinely touches ethical,
moral and political nerves. Whether the issue is human embryos in
research, cloning, or the escalating cost of drugs, biotech is in
the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 2000, the biotech industry will be forced to spend an
unprecedented amount of time and money to demonstrate its own worth
amid a great deal of consumer, media and political confusion,''
said David Flores, publisher of BioCentury Newsletter in San
Carlos.
</P>
<P>
   Flores flagged one issue that hasn't yet hit the public radar:
genetic privacy. What happens if the genome maps and SNPs make it
possible to show who has a propensity for heart disease,
schizophrenia, etc.?
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget, 2000 is a presidential election year. ``Medicare
reform and drug prices are certain to be campaign issues,'' said
Dennis Purcell, managing director of Chase H&AMP;Q's biotech investment
banking division.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell fears that even the threat of price controls on
prescription drugs could slow the flow of capital to support
biotech R&AMP;D. Flores said any such slowdown would affect ``everyone
in the prime of middle age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any novel medicine that has not reached clinical testing in a
few short years probably won't be available when the Boomers will
need it _ and want it _ as seniors later on,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Brain fix:  &LR; Scientists have long studied the brain, but their
efforts have gathered momentum of late thanks to new imaging
technologies _ similar to MRI scans _ that let scientists ``watch''
the mind at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next frontier will be the biology of the brain,''
predicted Zach Hall, vice chancellor for research at the University
of California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The new imaging tools give scientists the equivalent of
oscilloscopes, capable of detecting brain activity. Seeing where
the brain lights up when we speak, for instance, is a first step
toward treating damage caused by strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said some researchers are doing more than simply looking;
they're finding ways to tweak the brain's electric grid for
therapeutic purposes. Emory University researcher Mahlon DeLong,
for instance, has reduced Parkinson's disease tremors by delivering
precise electrical charges deep into the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said other researchers have rigged special electronics that
allow people with spinal cord injuries to grasp a glass of water.
To bypass the severed spinal cord, the movements of their hands are
activated by electrical signals from other parts of the body. A
shrug, for instance, might cause the hand to clasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has almost science fiction-like connotations,'' Hall said,
``but I think there's going to be increasingly sophisticated
electronic interventions we can use to create therapies.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Money in monoclonals: &LR;  Nothing better demonstrates the lag
between hype and payoff in biotech than monoclonal antibodies. For
20 years, biotech firms have promised to produce drugs based on
antibodies _ the proteins our bodies use to fight disease.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, that promise is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, monoclonal antibodies, mabs for short, chalked up $1.3
billion in revenues, led by products like Herceptin, a Genentech
drug to treat metastatic breast cancer. ``Humanized monoclonal
antibodies will play an increasing role in cancer treatment,''
predicted predicts  &LR; Lou Lavigne, chief financial officer at
Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monoclonals have been strong all year, and a next generation
is poised for FDA approval,'' said Richard van den Broek, an
analyst with Chase H&AMP;Q in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A list of mabs in late-stage human testing, compiled by industry
analyst Cynthia Robbins-Roth, supports Lavigne's contention.
Protein Design Labs, Idec Pharmaceuticals, MedImmune and Coulter
Pharmaceuticals all have anti-cancer mabs in Phase II or Phase III
clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Mabs for other conditions are also nearing the finish line.
Genentech is seeking FDA approval for a mab to fight asthma.
Abgenix is in late-stage trials of a mab to fight rejection of
organ transplants.
</P>
<P>
   No one takes FDA approval for granted, so some mabs could miss.
But it's good to know, amid he genomics hype, that biotech
eventually delivers cures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spare parts: &LR;  Organ transplants have saved many lives, but they
aren't perfect. Heart, lung and liver donors are always scarce. And
patients lucky enough to find a donor spend their lives taking
drugs to stop their immune systems from rejecting their
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be great to grow new organs?
</P>
<P>
   While we're still years away from growing replacement hearts,
Robert Langer, professor of biomedicine with the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, said biotech firms are already growing
simpler organs.
</P>
<P>
   Organogenesis Inc. of Massachusetts and Advanced Tissue Sciences
of La Jolla have FDA approval to sell bioengineered skin, grown
from real human cells.
</P>
<P>
   Reprogenesis Inc., a private firm in Massachusetts, is in
late-stage trials of two techniques to grow cells to fix leaky
bladders.
</P>
<P>
   Other research, still being tested in animals, seeks to grow a
whole new liver from a batch of cells. Langer said the human skin
products and bladder trials show that tissue engineers are on the
right track.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Love it or label it:  &LR; The fight over genetically engineered
foods has moved from Europe to the United States, with the focal
point of debate being the demand that whole or processed foods
containing bioengineered ingredients be specifically labeled.
</P>
<P>
   GE opponents in Europe have already won label laws, hoping
popular opposition will drive such foods off the market. A drive
for labeling in the United States is picking up steam.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Van Dyck, chairman of the nonprofit advocacy group As You
Sow, predicts shareholders will force reluctant U.S. firms to
swallow labels. ``You've already got 9 nine  &LR; shareholder
resolutions to that effect filed with life sciences companies, 16
with foodmakers and 13 with supermarkets,'' said Van Dyck, who
manages a socially responsible investment fund for U.S. Banc Piper
Jaffray.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco investment banker Burrill, a supporter of GE
foods, also believes that the industry will lose on labels.
``Expect to see government regulations regarding GE labeling on
foods,'' he said. ``It still remains to be seen if a majority of
American consumers really care.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pet pharmacies:  &LR; The 175 million cats, dogs, birds and other
pets who live in America don't know how lucky they are. To an
increasing degree, their owners are providing them the best
medicine money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending on animal drugs more than doubled from an
estimated $592 million in 1994 to $1.3 billion in 1998, according
to the American Health Institute. ``This is encouraging large
animal-health companies to spend more on R&AMP;D,'' said John Buchanan,
an analyst with the Burrill &AMP; Co. investment bank in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Today's pet potions go far beyond flea, tick and worm medicines.
Novartis, for instance, sells Clomicalm, a drug for separation
anxiety, i.e., to stop dogs from tearing up the house while master
is gone. Pfizer Inc., of Viagra fame, spends $200 million a year
searching for new remedies like Rimadyl, its $35-a-month arthritis
medication for dogs.
</P>
<P>
   With Pfizer betting that pet drug sales will grow 15 percent a
year, we can expect the industry to concoct more Fido and Kitty
pills _ in paw-proof containers, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rodney Dangerfield cured?  &LR; Call it wishful thinking, but Carl
Feldbaum, president of the Biotechnology Industry Association,
predicted 2000 is the year elected officials will recognize the
economic potential of biomedicine.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from the high-tech industry, Feldbaum is compiling
data to show biotech's clout. In 1997, for instance, California had
six regional biotech clusters, made up of 2,500 companies, which
directly employed 210,000 people, paid $8 billion in wages and
registered $4 billion in exports.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area boasted 670 biomedical companies and 78,000
employees, double the second-largest cluster in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Official recognition of the industry's importance made a modest
start when the U.S. Senate designated January as ``National
Biotechnology Month.'' Feldbaum thinks the industry can only get
more respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the demographics of the aging Baby Boomers,'' he said.
``The sheer number of people and the depth of their desire for new
medicines will create markets like no one has ever seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
