<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADGETS--TECHNOLOGY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PEERING INTO THE FUTURE: ENGINEERS DISPLAY WARES IN VEGAS  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ In one view of the future, a combination CD/DVD
player looks like a high-tech flower pot with a handle on top.
</P>
<P>
   A DVD player resembles a hot plate with the unlikely color
combination of orange and silver, while another resembles a wooden
drum, or maybe a '60s-era end table. And in a throwback to the old
days when television sets always came in wooden cabinets, there is
a combination flat-panel TV-DVD player encased in a sleek wooden
pillar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always great to see fresh designs, especially when
everything now is black or silver or gray,'' said showgoer Andy
Logan as he considered the curiously shaped electronic devices on
display at last week's Consumer Electronics Show here.
</P>
<P>
   The futuristic view was provided by engineers at Thomson
Consumer Electronics, which makes products for RCA.
</P>
<P>
   They displayed a series of concept home DVDs, television sets
and VCRs that may, or may not, someday be introduced into the
market. Similarly, car shows always have futuristically designed
cars that turn out markedly different when they finally hit the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson's idea was to get away from the boring standard metal
and plastic boxes that house today's consumer electronics. Instead,
the team of creative designers pushed way past the boundaries and
designed devices that fit better with other home furniture, or that
might be considered outlandish now but stylish in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, ``we didn't want this technology to stand out,
but more to blend in with the overall environment we live in
today,'' said Bryan Watson, manager of retail support for Thomson,
which is based in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   One example was the high-definition TV and DVD player designed
for the bedroom. The 15-inch screen is set into a 2-foot-wide
wooden stand, but is at eye level for someone lying in bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most successful designs are ones that look timeless,''
said Logan, who is himself a product designer for BMW subsidiary
Designworks/USA of Newbury Park in Southern California. ``They
would look good in 2020, or in 1920 or in 1420. They have a pure,
classic form to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Take the ``DVDble,'' the flower pot with a handle. When placed
upright on its base, it is a CD audio player, but when turned on
its side to reveal a TV screen, it becomes a DVD player.
</P>
<P>
   The hot plate, dubbed the ``Mambo,'' looked roughly like a
laptop computer, except instead of a keyboard, there was a large
orange glass plate covering the DVD disc. According to Thomson's
description, ``the aesthetics of the Mambo come directly from the
1950s bowling bag and suitcase forms.''
</P>
<P>
   The designers also dreamed up a pastel blue VCR with an
old-style clock, with hands, for those storied people whose digital
VCR clocks are perpetually flashing.
</P>
<P>
   The Music Alchemy is a series of toy musical instruments that
use DVDs to create the sounds of the basic instrument families:
strings, keyboard and horn. And a backpack, which one woman thought
looked like a vacuum cleaner, combined an MP3 player, speakers and
an insulated food storage compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Other new gadgets throughout the show still had the standard
look and feel of plastic and metal, but Casio offered Dick
Tracy-like gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   The Casio Databank Camera Watch, due out in the spring, can
store addresses and take digital pictures, while the Wrist Audio
Player can play back MP3 music files. The Wrist Audio Player, due
to retail at $250, will be on the market in about two months. The
camera watch should be out this spring for $200.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
