<HEADER>
A1137 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LATINOS-ONLINE-SFCHRO     01-09 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINOS-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATINO.COM HAS BIG PLANS TO BECOME HISPANIC PORTAL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. _ Run by a staff of two and backed by a
few maxed-out credit cards, Web site LatinoLink.com still managed
to attract a loyal following among Hispanic Internet users. With
content in both Spanish and English, the 5-year-old site now draws
400,000 unique visitors a month.
<P>
   Now Lavonne Luquis, the San Francisco entrepreneur behind
LatinoLink, has lined up $4 million in private placement funding,
increased her staff to 25 people and has big plans to morph her Web
zine into a portal.
</P>
<P>
   Set to debut on Valentine's Day, Latino.com will offer expanded
coverage of Hispanic-related news, sports and entertainment, plus
new features like Web search and e-commerce. LatinoLink.com will
stay on as one section of the new page. An initial public offering
is planned for later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Internet is relevant to people, they'll find a way to
go online,'' said Luquis, 40. That's why the former journalist
makes sure her site has plenty of articles, some written by her
10-person editorial staff, some from wire services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these are stories they would find in their daily
newspaper, but instead of on Page 15, we put it right in front,''
Luquis said. She plans to open news bureaus in Los Angeles,
Chicago, Miami and Texas as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be e-commerce, but it has to be in context. If
you're online planning a quincea &LR; n &LR; ara'' _ a coming-of age party
for 15-year-old girls _ ``you may decide to order certain items for
that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most e-commerce sites try to make shopping more convenient, but
Latino.com will sell things that some users couldn't buy at all
off-line _ where does someone living in a small Minnesota town pick
up tamale flour? EthnicGrocer.com already sells that and other
specialty foods through LatinoLink.com. Luquis says that users
constantly e-mail her asking where to buy hard-to-find food items
and Spanish-language music videos in cities across the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Latino) people are spreading out across the country,'' Luquis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Luquis herself was inspired to start the Web site when she moved
from Puerto Rico to Olympia, Wash., where she served as city editor
at the Olympian newspaper. She found almost no expression of Latino
culture in her new home, and when she went online for help, she
found nearly nothing there too. This was 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Latino.com will be one of many portals wooing the United States'
32 million Latinos. The biggest player is StarMedia Network, the
premier Internet company in Latin America, which set its sights on
the U.S. Latino market in 1998. Other Web sites vying for Latino
eyeballs include QuePasa.com, Yupi.com and El Sitio, which went
public December 15. Mainstream Web properties including Yahoo,
America Online and Prodigy have jumped into the fray with
Spanish-language offerings as well.
</P>
<P>
   All these competitors are fighting for an audience that the
Department of Commerce estimates to be only 12.9 percent of the
nation's 8 million Latino households _ that's how many were using
the Internet in 1998, according to the Department of Commerce's
report, ``Falling Through the Net: Defining the Digital Divide.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forrester Research, a technology analysis firm, believes the
Latino online audience is much bigger. Forrester says 36 percent of
Latino families had at least one member using the Internet in
mid-1999, and projects that 43 percent will be connected this year.
Unlike the figure from the Digital Divide report, Forrester's
figures include households whose members access the Internet at
work, at school or at the library.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester analyst Ekaterina Walsh said it's a myth that
minorities are less likely to get on the Internet. ``It's a
complete bogus idea. Race has nothing to do with online adoption or
buying a computer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Luquis believes that Latinos will embrace the Internet just as
they have picked up cellular phones, CD players and other
technological innovations in the past. To help make that goal a
reality, Latino.com will probably be involved in off-line campaigns
to encourage Latinos to get wired, Luquis said. But she believes
that the real key to getting more Latinos online is simply
providing something for them to do on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In her newspaper career, Luquis got to like the idea of service
journalism, or providing people with information that's useful to
their daily lives. She finds that easier to do on the Internet than
it was in print.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online, people immediately connect to you'' and send feedback,
Luquis said. ``It's easier to connect with readers.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of ways the Latino community can benefit from
using the Internet, Luquis said. One area LatinoLink.com is already
working on is helping Latino youth access scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Latino students are in urban schools, where they may not
have access to the best guidance counseling,'' Luquis said. So
LatinoLink.com lists scholarships and internships, some available
to all students and some just for Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   When Internet telephony develops to the extent that users in
Latin America can receive Internet calls, Luquis predicts that
Latinos will benefit greatly from low-priced Internet long-distance
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos are one of the groups that spend the most on
long-distance phone calls,'' Luquis said.
</P>
<P>
   Another area where Luquis predicts Latinos will find value in
the Internet is online language study, both for immigrants who want
to learn English and for American-born Latinos who want to discover
their roots by studying Spanish or Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   Luquis' goals sound altruistic, but she is confident that her
strategy will be profitable someday _ or at least allow her to
break even by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester's Walsh says she likes Latino.com's chances of
financial success but warns that the site has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to find a very strong peg that goes much farther
than just being a Latino site,'' Walsh said. To differentiate
itself from its competitors, Latino.com must find a niche within
the ethnic niche. That could mean picking an age group to cater to,
or focusing just on Latino sports or having the most up-to-date
news _ and this is something that she has not yet seen any of the
Latino portals doing, Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
