<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1138 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LATINOSIDE--WEB-SFCHR     01-09 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINOSIDE--WEB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPORTUNITY FOR LATINO WEB SITES IS MUY GRANDE  &HT;     BY CARRIE KIRBY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. _ Blame it on Ricky Martin, Jennifer Lopez or
just the mushrooming Latino population in the United States, but
one thing is clear: Web sites catering to Latinos _ once rare _ are
now all over the place.
<P>
   At QuePasa.com, you can buy a copy of ``The Matrix'' with
Spanish subtitles or pick up a recipe for Guatemalan cucumber soup.
At Yupi.com, browse 150 million links to Spanish-language Web sites
or make your own home page in the Ciudad Futura, or Future City.
Yahoo launched a site for Spanish speakers worldwide in 1998, then
added individual sites for Mexico, Spain and several South American
countries. Hit a tab on Prodigy's Web page to visit the
Spanish-language version.
</P>
<P>
   The 32 million Latinos in this country represent the
fastest-growing ethnic group. ``This is by far the largest
opportunity in the United States, and one that is underserved,''
said Roberto Ruiz, director of multicultural marketing for Internet
service provider Prodigy. Prodigy provides versions of its software
in both Spanish and English, and has bilingual customer support
available through a toll-free number.
</P>
<P>
   Online companies are beginning to wake up to the potential of
the Latino market, said Ekaterina Walsh, an analyst at Forrester
Research. One reason that Latinos are a valuable demographic is
their tendency to keep close ties with friends and family living
far away _ the reason the telecom industry has long targeted
advertising at Latino communities, she said. ``The No.1 reason for
using the Internet is keeping in touch,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   StarMedia Network and El Sitio are two companies with several
years of experience in Latin America that are now establishing a
presence in the United States. El Sitio Chief Executive Officer
Roberto Cibrian-Campoy, who works in the Buenos Aires headquarters,
said the move was natural once he noticed that 30 percent of the
traffic to his company's Latin American properties was coming from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Cibrian-Campoy said the key to succeeding in the U.S. market
will be El Sitio's 38-member Miami team, which writes local news
for Miami, the Bay Area, Chicago and several other U.S. cities.
News in the Bay Area section includes a story on San Francisco's
First Festival of Rock in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Sitio is an alternative to the one-size-fits-all site,''
Cibrian-Campoy said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a different approach, QuePasa.com places an article about
an Argentine soccer star and a feature about the Latino CEO of a
U.S. company on a single page. That's not necessarily a bad idea,
said Eva May, a partner at Espa &LR; n &LR; ol Marketing and Communications,
a Cary, N.C., advertising agency that targets Latinos. May said
plenty of features, from free e-mail to coverage of sports,
entertainment and world issues, would appeal to Latinos worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as it's relevant, people don't care if a site is made
for the general market, or just for Argentines, or what,'' May
said. She predicted that the sites that will come out on top will
depend more on ``who can talk the loudest'' than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
