<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-HURRICANES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHTER'S EFFORTS GO FOR NAUGHT AGAINST THE HURRICANES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Mike Richter deserved something better than a
1-0 loss to the Carolina Hurricanes here Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Ranger goaltender stopped pucks with his pads,
skates, stick and gloves. Richter stopped shots from all angles, on
power plays, odd-man rushes, at even strength. He stopped a shot
that had somehow climbed over his body and rolled down his back.
</P>
<P>
   He even stopped Jeff O'Neill on a breakaway with less than three
minutes remaining to give the Rangers a chance to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one shot that Richter could not stop out of the 28
he faced: an Andrei Kovalenko backhander in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Rangers, who were playing their second game in less
than 24 hours, could not find a way to beat Arturs Irbe, that was
one shot too many, as the Hurricanes (42 points) were able to pull
4 points ahead of the Rangers in the Eastern Conference standing.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rangers' 5-3 victory in Toronto on Saturday, Coach
John Muckler was asked if he felt his team could continue to play
the wide-open hockey, which it displayed in back-to-back victories
over the Maple Leafs, against defense-oriented teams like the
Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to,'' Muckler said, before catching himself.
``We're going to try to.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Rangers did Sunday night. They created numerous chances
for themselves. But the Rangers nevertheless trailed by a goal
after two periods.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly the fault of Richter, who was brilliant again. He
was acrobatic while stopping 20 of the 21 shots he faced through
the first 40 minutes. A post stopped another shot by Sami Kapanen.
A power-play blast from the Rangers' Mathieu Schneider, too, found
the post.
</P>
<P>
   The only shot that eluded Richter through two periods was
Kovalenko's. He sent a backhander into the top right corner of the
net 6 minutes 38 seconds into the second period. Kovalenko, who had
Eric Lacroix trying to shadow him, curled counterclockwise from
behind the net and through the slot before shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandre Daigle was also on the ice for the goal. Daigle came
to the Rangers with an astonishing plus-minus rating of minus-151
over the first six seasons of his National Hockey League career.
</P>
<P>
   In his first nine games with the Rangers, Daigle was a plus-8.
Since then, his rating has plummeted. Sunday night's game was
Daigle's 21st with the Rangers. With Kovalenko's goal, Daigle's
rating dropped to minus-9 over his last 12 games and minus-1 this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, things could have been much worse for the Rangers. Irbe
was just a little bit better at the other end for Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Petr Nedved's line did not create chance after chance.
The line of Nedved at center with his Czech countrymen Jan Hlavac
and Radek Dvorak on the wings had six shots on goal through two
periods, with five of them coming in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Irbe made the save of the game on Nedved with five minutes
remaining in the second period when Nedved skated in alone from the
right point.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved, who had scored four goals in two games against Toronto
after going 12 games without a goal, went backhand to forehand with
the puck. But Irbe made a pad save to keep Carolina's one-goal lead
intact.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the period, the Czech line turned up the heat on Irbe
again. But he turned aside good chances by Hlavac and Dvorak, who
is still looking for his first goal as a Ranger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
