<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAYOFF GROUNDSWELL OF THE VINTAGE KIND
</HEADLINE>
   (With FBN-COWBOYS-VIKINGS) 
(nk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington quarterback Brad Johnson watched his teammate,
running back Stephen Davis, closely in practice before the Redskins
played Detroit in their wild-card playoff game on Saturday. Johnson
saw how Davis was limping, as if stepping on hot coals, all because
of a still-healing ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson suddenly felt sick to his stomach. There was no way
Davis was going to be ready for the game, he thought. Without their
star runner, Johnson had to know that the Redskins could still beat
the sorry Lions. But any chance of a Super Bowl victory rested on
the tender ankles of Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him at practice on Wednesday, I really didn't think
he would play,'' Johnson said. ``Then Thursday he got better and
Friday he got better. Then he was full speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said later, ``And when he is full speed, there aren't
many who are better.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was any one theme from the opening playoff weekend, it
was the dominance of the running backs. Maybe it was
playoff-opening jitters, with coaches generally not wanting to take
inordinate risks by passing, but backs found their numbers being
called often.
</P>
<P>
   In Nashville, the Titans-Bills game was decided by what may have
been the trick play of all time _ a kickoff return for a touchdown
off a cross-field lateral. But Tennessee's Eddie George had 29
carries for 106 yards, with Buffalo players admitting that the
muscular George began wearing the Bills down late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   At Washington, Davis played about one and a half quarters before
leaving with a sprained medial collateral ligament in his right
knee. His early trip to the trainer's room did not stop him from
crushing Detroit with 119 yards and 2 touchdowns on 15 carries. His
58-yard run, in which he outran three defensive backs who had
surrounded him, was one of the more exciting plays of the first
round. The Redskins finished with 233 yards rushing, third best in
the team's playoff history.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the long run that he made, the play was really designed to
go inside, and Stephen started to take it inside, then at the last
second bounced it outside,'' Washington Coach Norv Turner said. ``I
don't know how to describe what allows the guy to do it, other than
the great vision he has.''
</P>
<P>
   In Minneapolis, there are Randy Moss and Cris Carter and Jeff
George in an offense full of passing and receiving stars, but it
was the ground game that truly pushed Minnesota past Dallas, 27-10,
on Sunday. The Cowboys, with their smallish linemen and
linebackers, were sometimes nailed into the ground like fence posts
by the Vikings' massive front. Holes opened the size of parking
lots, and Robert Smith trotted through them 28 times for 140 yards,
breaking his team's playoff rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Seattle, where no back on either the Seahawks or the
Miami Dolphins had the big day that Eddie George, Davis or Smith
enjoyed, Ricky Watters did have several key runs to keep Seattle
drives alive.
</P>
<P>
   And while quarterback Dan Marino played one of his best games
this year, J.J. Johnson gave the Dolphins the go-ahead touchdown
with his 2-yard run in Miami's 20-17 upset victory. The Seahawks
began blitzing Marino constantly, but had to slow their advances,
mainly because Johnson busted several key runs up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for coaches to be conservative when it comes
to the wild-card games. Coaches playing on the road take few risks
in hostile territory and those playing at home don't want to do
anything to blow the game or turn the crowd. There is also the fact
that offensive linemen love to run block more than pass protect.
</P>
<P>
   The running game really helped the Vikings by insuring that Jeff
George, their quarterback, did not have to win the game by himself.
The Vikings' staff wanted to give Smith plenty of carries as a
means of insulating George. It worked.
</P>
<P>
   The running will definitely continue in the second round of the
playoffs next weekend. Running back Edgerrin James and
Indianapolis, which had a bye in the first round, play at home
against Eddie George and the Titans. Smith and the Vikings travel
to St. Louis to play Marshall Faulk and the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Those two games alone probably mean lots of fireworks on the
ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
