<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-AFCGAME10-COX     01-09 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFCGAME10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marino performs old magic
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Dan Marino's not done yet. A 38-year-old quarterback
who holds every major NFL passing record, he led Miami to a 20-17
victory Sunday and the Dolphins shut down Seattle as well as the
Kingdome, before a hostile crowd of 66,170.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins will play at Jacksonville on Saturday, their Super
Bowl hopes alive. But the AFC West champion Seahawks, who made the
playoffs for the first time in 12 years, have only a new stadium to
look forward to in the future.
</P>
<P>
   With a pared-down offense, Miami focused on establishing its
running game early. However, for the team to win its first road
playoff game in 27 years, Marino had to direct the kind of 85-yard
fourth-quarter drive that was his specialty before critics began
caling for his retirement. The key play was a 23-yard pass to Tony
Martin on third-and-17 from the Dolphins' 8-yard line, with the
Seahawks in a zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was worth a shot and he made a great catch,'' said Marino,
who threw no interceptions Sunday while completing 17 of 30 passes
for 196 yards and one touchdown. ``The important thing was him
making the catch because the throw was a little high.''
</P>
<P>
   Six plays later, again on third down but this time from the
shotgun formation, Marino found Oronde Gadsden for 24 yards to the
Seattle 5. J.J. Johnson rushed twice, scoring from the 2 to give
Miami its first lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami defense then held firm, sacking quarterback Jon Kitna
twice before allowing him a single yard. The Seahawks got one more
chance with 1:05 remaining, but Kitna threw three incomplete passes
before a 17-yard pass. On 3rd-and-10, Terrell Buckley's intercepted
a pass with 23 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was such a great team win for us,'' said defensive end
Trace Armstrong. ``To play soundly in all three phases, it's just
good to get back on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jimmy Johnson, whose team lost five of their last six
regular-season games to back into the playoffs with a 9-7 record,
told his team all week that they would win -- and in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy was very upbeat this week,'' Martin said of the
embattled coach. ``He said, 'Just hang in there and be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   They had to be, since Seattle jumped out to a 7-0 lead on its
second possession with Kitna throwing a 9-yard pass to Sean
Dawkins.
</P>
<P>
   After Olindo Mare kicked a 32-yard field goal for the Dolphins,
Todd Peterson kicked a 50-yarder to give the Seahawks a 10-3
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, which had managed only 69 yards total offense, roared out
in the third quarter. The Dolphins tied the game after a 60-yard
drive, with Marino throwing a 1-yard TD pass to Oronde Gadsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving the length of the field to tie it up showed we can
move the ball and we can score points,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Charlie Rogers ran the ensuing kickoff back 85 yards
to put Seattle back in front 17-10. But Miami cut into the lead
with a 51-yard Mare field goal and recovered an onsides kick to
hold the ball at 13:05 in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle gained just 32 yards in the second half, and had just
three snaps in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no clue as to how they were able to push us around like
they did,'' said Ricky Watters, who had 40 yards on 19 carries.
``They made us look pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   First-year Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren said his team was ``in a
bind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had difficulty running the football against this team,'' he
said. ``I had hoped for better there. When we couldn't do that, the
pass protection, we struggled there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his team's lack of playoff experience was a factor, as
the Seahawks were not accustomed to the intensity level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you experience something like that,'' said the former
Green Bay coach, ``you don't believe it or know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna had 114 yards passing in the first half, but just 48 in
the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played OK,'' said Holmgren. ``It was his first of many big
games.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Marino, it wasn't his last.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
