<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEVELAND-CONCERTHALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THEY DIDN'T TAKE AWAY THE HALL'S LOVELY SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The sigh of relief at Severance Hall on Saturday
night was palpable, if not necessarily audible.
</P>
<P>
   Built for the Cleveland Orchestra and completed in 1931,
Severance has long been considered one of the best-sounding concert
halls in the United States. But it has just undergone an ambitious
22-month, $36.7 million restoration and expansion that included a
complete reconfiguring of the stage. It was the kind of exercise
guaranteed to have an orchestra's musicians, administrators and
listeners praying that the acoustics would come through intact.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 20 minutes into the program it was evident that there
was no cause for worry. By then, Christoph von Dohnanyi, the
orchestra's music director, had led his musicians in the world
premiere of Sir Harrison Birtwistle's ``Sonance Severance 2000'' _
a three-minute showpiece that offered rumbling basses, bright
brass, high-pitched string writing and varied percussion _ as well
as Wagner's ``Meistersinger'' Prelude, with its rich brass choirs
and lush, high-energy string writing.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, one wanted more power in the bass, a quality that
had been present earlier in the day, during a rehearsal of
Berlioz's ``Damnation of Faust.''
</P>
<P>
   Dohnanyi's reopening program went on to offer more detailed
tests. In Vaughan Williams' ``Lark Ascending,'' William Preucil,
the concertmaster, demonstrated the ease with which a melting
pianissimo floats through the hall. Prokofiev's ``Classical''
Symphony was one of several works in which Dohnanyi demonstrated
the crispness and transparency of the orchestra's sound.
</P>
<P>
   The eerie string clusters and strange percussion textures of
Gyorgy Ligeti's 1961 ``Atmospheres'' let Dohnanyi demonstrate the
hall's comfort with both delicacy and heft. And in Ravel's
``Daphnis and Chloe,'' the fast oboe and flute figuration, usually
heard as an impressionistic blur, was entirely distinct, and one
could hear the percussive edge of the harp strings being plucked.
</P>
<P>
   As an encore Dohnanyi led a trim, vigorous account of Mozart's
``Nozze di Figaro'' Overture.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who listens closely to the way orchestras sound in
their halls, the refurbishing of Severance Hall was cause for
anxiety, since changes can easily be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   A cautionary tale, though one with a good outcome, was provided
by the renovation of Carnegie Hall. When Carnegie reopened in 1986,
it looked fabulous, but a layer of concrete placed under the stage
floor had robbed the sound of its visceral punch. When the concrete
was removed, the Carnegie sound returned.
</P>
<P>
   That was clearly on the mind of Christopher Jaffe, whose firm,
Jaffe Holden Scarbrough, oversaw the acoustics of the Severance
Hall renovation. At a panel discussion at the Rock and Roll Hall of
Fame and Museum on Friday, he joked that he didn't have to warn
David Schwarz, the project architect, not to put concrete under the
stage. As it turned out, concrete that been there since 1931, as a
support for a stage element that is no longer used, was removed.
</P>
<P>
   Severance has had a more checkered acoustical history than its
reputation suggests. When the 2,000-seat hall opened in 1931, the
lack of a stage ceiling (there was a fly space instead) kept the
sound from projecting, and heavy curtains and carpeting absorbed
the sound that made it into the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Minor modifications were made during the hall's first 25 years,
but it took the forceful personality of George Szell to persuade
the board to undertake radical surgery in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   At Szell's suggestion, a wooden stage shell was built. It solved
the hall's acoustical problems, and since then the sound has
figured prominently in explanations of why the Cleveland Orchestra
is considered one of the world's best ensembles.
</P>
<P>
   But it also created problems that lay unexplored until 1993,
when the orchestra celebrated its 75th anniversary and appointed a
committee to study the state of the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the committee's proposals were entirely practical:
insufficient office space, inadequate locker rooms for musicians,
problems in the flow of audience traffic, and deficiencies in the
restaurant, parking and restrooms were all noted in the report and
were addressed in the renovation, which included an addition to the
rear of the building.
</P>
<P>
   The aesthetic concerns raised in the report were trickier.
Although it was apparently of little concern in 1958 that Szell's
modern, angular shell did not match the ornamental art-deco and
classical design of the 1931 hall, the mismatch seemed jarring in
the preservation-conscious 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   It was also decided, at Dohnanyi's insistence, that the
6,025-pipe E.M. Skinner organ _ part of the original hall, but
buried behind the Sell shell _ should be refurbished and made an
element of the stage.
</P>
<P>
   What was required was less a restoration than an idealized
completion of the hall: The stage had to look like an extension of
the ornate audience chamber, as Schwarz and Jaffe call it, but the
acoustical properties of the 1958 shell had to be retained.
</P>
<P>
   The original intention was to preserve rather than improve the
acoustics, but Jaffe persuaded Dohnanyi and the orchestra's board
that a slight increase in reverberation was desirable. The new
reverberation time, 1.8 seconds (up from 1.6) matches that of
Carnegie Hall and of Symphony Hall in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   A series of room-size resonance chambers at the sides of the
stage can be either closed or left open; Dohnanyi will experiment
with them in the coming weeks. His designated successor, Franz
Welser-Moest, may have his own ideas when he takes over the podium
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Visually the new stage is stunning. The musicians are seated on
risers, with convex maple and aluminum leaf panels (matching those
in the house) at the sides and back. Above the panels is grillwork
through which the sound enters and leaves the resonating chambers.
The organ pipes at the back of the stage provide both a gleaming
visual focus and another sound-reflecting surface. The organ itself
will be reinstalled in the summer and rededicated next January.
</P>
<P>
   The stage is brightly lighted; lighting within the translucent
proscenium gives the arch an unusual glow. The hall sounds as
seductive as it looks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
