<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-700&AMP;ADD     01-09 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS AND STRIPES LOSES ON LAND BUT WINS BY SEA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ A winner on the water on Sunday against
Nippon Challenge, Stars and Stripes fared more poorly against the
Japanese on paper, being penalized one potentially precious point
for using an illegal rudder against them earlier in the America's
Cup challenger semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty dropped Stars and Stripes into third place in this
round, from which only two of the six boats will advance to the
challenger final.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the America's Cup; it is not without drama or a few
potholes, and you have to negotiate them,'' said the Stars and
Stripes skipper Dennis Conner, who has helped cement this event's
reputation for that in his 25 years of sailing in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a very crucial point taken away, but we can't think
about that now,'' he said in an interview with New Zealand
television. ``We still have our destiny in our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars and Stripes, which is sailing without Conner on board, had
a chance to help itself in a hurry on Monday, when it was scheduled
to face second-place Prada on the Hauraki Gulf. A victory would put
Conner's crew back in a tie for second behind America One, the
syndicate headed by Paul Cayard that represents the St. Francis
Yacht Club in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   America One, now 5-1, is the only team to have beaten Stars and
Stripes in this round, if you choose not to count Nippon, whose
only victory against the Americans came in the jury room on Sunday.
Nippon had protested to the international jury that Stars and
Stripes had breached Article 19 of the America's Cup protocol by
using a rudder that was not made in its home country (the United
States) or in the host country (New Zealand).
</P>
<P>
   The rudder was designed by Americans but manufactured in
Australia at McConaghy Boats in Sydney with materials shipped from
the United States. The rudder _ shorter than the one used by Stars
and Stripes in the preliminary rounds _ was intended for use in the
third round robin but did not arrive in Auckland in time and was
installed for the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   But after Stars and Stripes beat Nippon with it on Jan. 2 in its
opening race, the Americans, concerned about possible
repercussions, removed the rudder and replaced it with a modified
version of the original.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon protested four days later, and the America's Cup
arbitration panel ruled on Sunday that the rudder was illegal.
Stars and Stripes then went out and won the closest race of these
challenger semifinals, beating Nippon by 10 seconds, by taking
advantage of miscommunication at the start between Nippon's
Australian skipper, Peter Gilmour, and his largely Japanese crew.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after the race had been completed that the
international jury imposed the 1-point penalty. But the jury did
not choose to award a point to Nippon, which did not sit well with
the Japanese and could lead them to request a reopening of the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Willis, the chairman of the jury, termed the breach of the
protocol ``a very serious matter'' and said ``that's why we imposed
a full point'' on Stars and Stripes. But he said that Nippon had
not been rewarded, because ``the use of the rudder had no
significant effect on the outcome of the match.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury made that judgment because Nippon lost the race by 55
seconds and experienced problems with a steering device on its keel
and because Stars and Stripes' boat performed just as well with its
original rudder in its next two races.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, we're very surprised about this decision,'' said
Emili Miura, a Nippon spokeswoman who called for syndicates to
respect the protocol and said her syndicate would decide later
Monday whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon was 2-4 and in fourth place after losing its third
straight race on Sunday. That disappointing record certainly helps
explain some of its disappointment with the jury's decision. In
fifth is America True at 1-4 and in last place is Le Defi Francais,
which is 1-5 and mathematically eliminated from contention.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that unless Nippon can get a point back from the
jury, this semifinal is now a three-boat race among America One,
Prada and Stars and Stripes, which all won on Sunday in light wind
conditions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Such conditions are far from ideal for Stars and Stripes'
USA-55, a boat conceived and constructed to prosper in moderate to
heavy winds, but Conner's crew has proved its resourcefulness here
on the water if not its sound judgment on land. ``We screwed up, so
we were at their mercy,'' said the tactician Tom Whidden, who made
Stars and Stripes' case to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ken Read, the helmsman of Stars and Stripes, the
decision to build the rudder in Australia was made because it
``cost less money and required a shorter period of time'' than
building it elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how we do things,'' Read said of his syndicate, which
has a $12 million budget that pales in comparison with Prada's $50
million and America One's $32 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stars and Stripes has paid a price for its error, but
Conner's crew may not have seen the last of the jury. If Stars and
Stripes wins the challenger series and earns the right to face Team
New Zealand in the America's Cup match, it could still be deemed
ineligible. Cup rules require a challenger to sign a document
assuring that it has broken no rules before racing the defenders,
and Stars and Stripes has undeniably broken a rule.
</P>
<P>
   But Willis said that the arbitration panel could determine that
this requirement be waived in light of the penalty already assessed
against Stars and Stripes. He said another option would be for the
defender, New Zealand, to accept the challenge despite the breach
on the grounds that a penalty had been paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess all these things will be cleared up near the end,''
Willis said rather hopefully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
