<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GADZURIC IS THE GOOD NEWS FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Locker-room leftovers from the first of what
should be nine wild weeks of league play for UCLA ...
</P>
<P>
   The good: Sophomore center Dan Gadzuric had the most productive
Pacific-10 weekend of his career with 25 points and 20 rebounds. He
grabbed 13 rebounds Thursday at Washington and scored 16 points
Saturday at Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   But Gadzuric's low-post offense is raw. He relies on
athleticism, not skill. That works against the Washington schools,
but not against Arizona and Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I do wrong,'' he said, ``is that when I get the ball
in the post, I go right away. I need to take my time.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad: While Gadzuric sparkled, forward Jerome Moiso and guard
Ray Young struggled.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso shot 37 percent from the field, 50 percent from the line,
averaged 9.5 points and committed nine turnovers. He seemed
distracted in both games and had a long talk with coach Steve Lavin
on the bench in the final minutes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Young's nemesis was foul trouble. He had four in both games,
spent prolonged periods on the bench and never found his groove. He
scored eight points in Seattle and one in Pullman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of growing into being able to play with sustained
intensity with an expanded role (this season),'' Lavin said. ``He's
a rhythm player. When he gets into a rhythm offensively, that tends
to pick his energy up at both ends.''
</P>
<P>
   The ugly: The Bruins made 21 of 40 free throws this weekend and
are shooting 60.2 percent for the season. They lost the Washington
game because of it, making 9 of 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been shooting 100 every day,'' Lavin said. ``There's no
pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is: poor concentration.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre: The weekend's most surprising development was the
ease with which UCLA dismantled Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Bruins (9-3, 1-1) had won their previous three
games in Pullman by a total of seven points, no one expected a
rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd never think it would be this weekend, especially because
of how we played at Washington,'' guard Earl Watson said. ``But
there was no way we were coming out of here 0-2.''
</P>
<P>
   The comeback: Ten days after deciding to transfer _ and one week
after returning _ sophomore guard Billy Knight proved his value.
</P>
<P>
   Knight made 4 of 7 shots from 3-point range and scored 14 points
in 16 minutes against Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's done is buy into what we've asked,'' Lavin said.
``That is to play solid defense and understand our (offensive)
sets. That will allow him to be a threat and keep him on the floor
for more sustained time.''
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week: The 22-point victory at Washington State was
UCLA's largest Pac-10 road win in 11 years _ since a 31-point win
at Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: After the one-point loss to Washington, Lavin said:
``The good news is, as poorly as we're playing, every game, even
Gonzaga, we've contested. Colorado State, we were in the game
(until the buzzer). Same with Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Since when was ``contesting'' a game against Colorado
State an issue for UCLA?
</P>
<P>
   How the standards have dropped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 2232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
