<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-IRAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S FIRST VISIT TO THE U.S. BEGINS WITH A NARROW LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GREGG BELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Javad Zarinche was an 11-year-old Iranian
soccer neophyte in 1978, when a student-led takeover of the United
States Embassy in Tehran became a 444-day holding of American
hostages. The siege remains the Western world's most disturbing
memory of Iran's Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But the thoughts that Zarinche and the 34,289 fans at Network
Associates Coliseum may have had Sunday of such history drowned in
a sea of red-white-and-green good will. Zarinche led an Iranian
soccer team onto an American field for the first time, and it was
greeted by the horns, cheers and flag-waving of an estimated 20,000
cheering countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   Zarinche, Iran's captain, may not have been happy with his
team's 2-1 loss to Mexico to open a three-match friendly series
that ends next Sunday at the Rose Bowl against the United States.
But he is proud of what he sees as progress through sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy that after 21 years, the sport of football, or
soccer as you call it here, brought us here to the United States,''
Zarinche said through an interpreter before Sunday's match. ``I'm
hoping sports can be a bond to bring people of the world
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The match, between two national teams playing without many of
their stars, brought out the second-largest crowd in the limited
history of soccer in Oakland and a live Iranian national television
audience (1 a.m. Monday in Tehran) to witness a wide-open,
entertaining match that included three first-half goals and plenty
of scoring chances throughout.
</P>
<P>
   The match ended after a frantic final push from Iran, which
controlled most of action in the final 45 minutes. Before that, the
Mexican forward Luis Hernandez dazzled the crowd with both his
long, flowing blond hair and his fleet offensive rushes.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez headed in Juan Pablo Rodriguez's perfectly arched free
kick from 10 yards out to open the scoring in the third minute. By
the time the crowd completed its first wave around the stadium in
the 24th minute, Rodriguez had helped Mexico take a 2-0 lead with
another accurate free kick. Cuauhtemoc Blanco headed Rodriguez's
line drive over Iran goalkeeper Hadi Tabatabei's reach.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's only score came in the 26th minute. Forward Esmaeil
Halali broke free into Mexico's penalty area and was tackled from
behind by Mexican defender Ramon Ramirez. Ali Daei grounded the
subsequent penalty kick past Christian Martinez for Iran's only
goal, despite its late-game offensive dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very good experience for us,'' said Iran Coach
Mansour Pourhaidari, who brought players from the team that beat
the United States, 2-1, in the 1998 World Cup. ``We made costly
mistakes early in the game, but I was proud of the way we fought
back and played hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparations for the groundbreaking tour included the State
Department's granting the Iranian players exceptions to the
fingerprinting that is required for visa applicants from nations it
determines to be a ``high threat,'' Iranians joyously greeting the
players at the Oakland Airport upon their arrival Wednesday and a
Western news media buildup that stressed the political significance
of playing in the United States over the matches themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Pourhaidari played down the importance of the
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results are not important,'' he said through an
interpreter. ``These matches are used to identify strengths and
weaknesses for the Asian championships. There has been too much
emphasis and importance placed on these matches.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Iran's players who play professionally outside the
country did not join the team until after New Year's Day.
Pourhaidari said five or six players who will play in the Asian
Games this fall did not make the trip. Sunday's loss was Iran's
first in international play since the 1998 Asian Games, a span of
11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Iran has a match against Ecuador on Wednesday in Los
Angeles before its Rose Bowl meeting against the United States, its
players have their sights on the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came back well,'' forward Emilio Mora said of his team's
effort Sunday. ``We are looking forward to playing the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday's match, no one was looking back. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
