<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REV. CARL ELKANAH BATES, 85, FORMER SOUTHERN BAPTIST LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Carl Elkanah Bates, a former president of the Southern
Baptist Convention, the country's largest Protestant denomination,
died on Dec. 21 at his home in Hendersonville, N.C. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, who led the convention from 1970 to 1972, had previously
been president of the Baptist General Convention of Texas and the
Baptist State Convention of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   He was considered a moderate who deplored the infighting between
opposite wings of the church that, after his presidency, led to the
ascendancy of the conservative wing of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Bates was born in Liberty, Miss., and became what is known
as a Gideon convert. As Bates told it, he was in a New Orleans
hotel room in 1934, standing by an open window and feeling
despondent enough to contemplate suicide. Just then he noticed the
Gideon Bible that is present in all hotel rooms and opened it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a self-styled agnostic,'' he once testified, ``but as I
read that Bible, it dawned on me that I had cut myself off from
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates graduated from Mississippi College in Clinton in 1937 and
was ordained a minister in 1938. He earned a master's degree at
Southern Baptist Theological Seminary in Louisville, Ky., in 1941,
and a doctorate of divinity at Baylor University in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   His ministry took him to Southern churches in several states. He
became pastor of the First Baptist Church in Charlotte, N.C., in
1959.
</P>
<P>
   For five years he was a senior professor of preaching and
pastoral ministries at Southern Baptist Seminary, which created a
Carl E. Bates Chair of Preaching in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Bates is survived by his wife of 60 years, Myra Mae Gray Bates,
who was a convention vice president in the 1970s; a daughter,
Judith Stoneham of Hendersonville; a brother, Eugene Bates of Baton
Rouge, La.; a sister, Mildred Day of Baton Rouge; and two
grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 2241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000109.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-SAILOR-     01-09 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-SAILOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EACH COMPETITION HAS ITS CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By KATIE PETTIBONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ I have made the transition from
around-the-world ocean sailor to around-the-marks America's Cup
sailor. I am now sailing with America True, a coed team backed by
the San Francisco Yacht Club, and we are currently in the
challenger semifinals with five other syndicates.
</P>
<P>
   I can hardly believe that it was almost two years ago that I
wrote from EF Education in the 1997-98 Whitbread Round the World
race about feeling as if we were moving ``furniture from side to
side in a house on jacks.'' Then, the friendliest thing we would
see for days might be a lonely albatross circling endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it has been interesting to go from racing around the
world with a 10-boat fleet for nine months of nonstop action to
competing one-on-one for an intense three-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   These two events _ the Whitbread, now called the Volvo Ocean
Race to recognize the event's new sponsor, and the America's Cup _
are definitely the premier international big-boat events today.
Although the two events have slowly evolved to have more
similarities, their backgrounds and purpose could hardly be more
different.
</P>
<P>
   The Volvo Race covers more than 32,000 miles over a nine-month
period. The history of the race is considered young; the first
Whitbread took place in the early 1970s. Initially, Whitbread
sailors were more pirates than bluebloods.
</P>
<P>
   The race was _ and still is _ considered extreme, before extreme
sports came into vogue. The yachts that took these adventure
seekers out into the ocean were not necessarily built for speed.
Rather, they had to get their sailors through some of the toughest
conditions on the planet and get them back to port in one piece.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the America's Cup is not only one of the
oldest events in sports history (the first trophy was awarded in
1870), but it has also been the symbol of the tired old stereotype
of yacht racing as a wealthy and privileged boys' club. While the
cup has a four-month buildup of races to determine the challenger
fit to battle the defender, the competition's finals are decided by
a five-of-nine series of races.
</P>
<P>
   Modernization in the ocean race and the cup has brought a level
of professionalism and sponsorship dollars that would dazzle the
founders.
</P>
<P>
   Recent performance in both has also put the age-old superstition
regarding women as bad luck in sailboat racing into the fairy-tale
books, where it belongs. Women's teams made an appearance in the
Whitbread first, but now have also made strong appearances in the
cup.
</P>
<P>
   You need look no further than America True's record in this
America's Cup for proof: We qualified for the challenger semifinals
_ five teams did not make it. We currently stand 1-4 in this
series. The ultimate victor among the challengers will meet New
Zealand in the finals in February.
</P>
<P>
   This campaign with America True is my first experience on the
professional level with a coed team. While my two previous
all-female projects _ the 1995 America's Cup with America3 and EF
Education in the 1997-98 Whitbread _ had men involved in coaching
or leadership positions, the crew members on each boat were women.
</P>
<P>
   On America True, there are three to five women racing a day; we
all grew up competing with and against men, so none of this is new
to us. I happen to be the only woman in a trimmer's position, but I
really don't even notice it. Among our competitors, however, there
are men who turned down spots on America True in favor of offers
from all-male teams. They thought that a coed effort wouldn't be
competitive. They, incidentally, have not made the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   As for the racing conditions in the two events, out on the
Hauraki Gulf we are crashing about in 75-foot carbon-fiber racing
machines in conditions that are marginal for these yachts.
</P>
<P>
   I have to chuckle: This is when a Whitbread 60 just started to
cook! America's Cup boats are technical prototypes designed to push
the design envelope; they are like Formula One race cars _
technically challenging, very sensitive and requiring the best to
drive and care for them. They aren't meant to be taken off-roading
into the wilds. That is for the Volvo boats _ the Range Rovers of
the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   However, here in Auckland, when the winds are howling up to 28
knots with large waves, my Whitbread experience has come in handy
in controlling the boat.
</P>
<P>
   The intensity on board the boat during a Volvo race has to be
paced. Although the level of competition has meant that the teams
push themselves harder for longer, it is not physically possible to
maintain the extreme level of mental concentration demanded by a
cup race. In a cup race, every nerve is firing, every fiber of your
being is straining to hear, see or react.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the intensity of the races themselves, the keys to
success are two-boat testing along with time, practice and the
money to develop your boat design. This is becoming the case in the
Volvo race as well, with more teams preparing and testing in the
years leading up to the event.
</P>
<P>
   So if the professionalism, preparation, technology and intensity
are all similar, what stands to differentiate the events? Pretty
simple: You have to be a little insane to do the Volvo race. During
a Volvo leg, you don't go home at night to a nice, comfy bed, eat a
fresh meal or cuddle up with a significant other. When I go into
work on America True, I am on _ working, sailing, sweating. But
when I leave the compound at night, I am off. I've even been known
to read a book.
</P>
<P>
   Having competed in both events, I find each stimulating and
challenging in its own way. The cup gives results in a day and
allows you to become specialized, hence extremely good, at one
thing. In my case, for America True I am trimming the forward
sails. In the Whitbread, the results of your efforts may not be
seen for weeks, even months, and you have to be good at a lot of
things, including sail changes, trimming all sails and driving.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how close the two events become, the one thing the cup
will never be able to teach its participants is the appreciation
for hot showers and dry, warm beds that don't move up and down. I
still thank God for my hot baths and showers to this day. Just
don't remind me of this when I get ready for the next Volvo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
