<SLUG> BC-BKW-CSUN-IDAHOSTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE ROUTS IDAHO STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANEL LAJ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On paper, Cal State Northridge should have had a
big advantage, but it wasn't until the second half that the
Matadors proved that fact.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho State dropped nine consecutive games after starting the
season 2-0. The Bengals (3-10, 1-1) recently beat Eastern
Washington for their third win, but their record doesn't accurately
indicate how aggressively they can play.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors had trouble getting the ball into the post, but
found success outside to pull away for an 82-53 victory at home
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the third time CSUN (8-4, 2-0) has beaten the
Bengals, and the important factors in the win didn't all show up on
the stat sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intangible things, that's me,'' said Northridge guard
Jamilah Jones, who scored all of her 10 points in the second half,
including eight in the first four minutes as CSUN expanded a 36-28
halftime lead to a 24-point advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Jones' defense and hustle that mattered most. Her
tenacity as a defender helped create turnovers and break up plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to go at them inside, that's where their
strength lies, in the post game,'' Northridge coach Frozena Jerro
said. ``They did a pretty good job in the post getting some blocked
shots. Jamilah did a great job of coming in and lighting it up in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what was key for us is that we got off to a good
start. Everybody got into the flow. We want to focus on playing a
solid 40 minutes of basketball and understand that if we do that,
wins are going to come.''
</P>
<P>
   More of the Matadors offense came from Keisha Harris. Harris was
7 of 8 from the field and finished with her second double-double of
the season with 14 points and 10 rebounds. Harris also had three
blocks and three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Edneisha Curry had 17 points, Neda Milic scored 12 and Lynda
Amari had 11 points, five steals and three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Jerro said another key was the 33 turnovers Northridge forced,
including 19 from steals. CSUN had 19 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho State was led by Chris Urbanski, who scored 18 points and
Mandi Carvers who had 13 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
