<HEADER>
A1156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PIGEON-SCHOOLCHILD     01-09 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PIGEON-SCHOOLCHILDREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM LOWLY PIGEON, LESSON IN BIRDS (AND BEES) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was not the most auspicious spot for studying the
mating habits of wild animals. A woman pushed a baby carriage
through the observation area. Another woman barged past, talking on
a cell phone, as traffic roared on Greenwich Street. Behold, the
wild kingdom of TriBeCa.
</P>
<P>
   The species under scrutiny was not particularly exotic, either _
Columba livia, better known as the rock dove, or pigeon. And the
researchers, part of a Cornell University ornithology project
spanning nine countries, were mostly under 4 feet tall and still in
the third grade.
</P>
<P>
   In front of Public School 234, Patricia Sanabria's 26 students
had spread some multigrain crackers on the sidewalk. They waited,
clipboards in hand, as a flock of pigeons descended, bird by bird.
For the next 45 minutes, they would count the pigeons and take
notes about how the birds paired off.
</P>
<P>
   The students are part of Project PigeonWatch, a program run by
the Cornell Laboratory of Ornithology, which has 400 other groups
of observers _ mostly schoolchildren _ around the world. They are
trying to answer two riddles about pigeons: why do they come in so
many colors, and how do they choose their mates?
</P>
<P>
   While they are helping science, the pigeon watchers learn that
the birds are monogamous, are used by rescuers to help find people
lost at sea, and are not, at least anatomically, rats with wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pigeons pose very interesting, genuinely unsolved evolutionary
questions,'' said John Fitzpatrick, director of the laboratory, a
research and education center in Ithaca, N.Y., affiliated with
Cornell.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how or why federal pigeons, once domesticated and
bred for particular traits, have maintained their diversity of
colors and patterns back in the wild. Students of the pigeon can
identify 28 color morphs, or feather patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, after several generations, Fitzpatrick said, wild
pigeons would be expected to revert to the standard look, known as
the blue bar, of pigeons found on Old World cliffs. But even a
cursory look around a city sidewalk or under a bridge reveals a
mosaic of pigeon morphs. So citizen observers have been recruited
to figure out why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they stable across big metropolitan areas?'' Fitzpatrick
asked. ``Are they constant across the country? Do pigeons of
different colors mate assortatively?'' _ that is, do they mate with
birds like them?
</P>
<P>
   It is within the power of 8-year-olds to help answer such
questions, and learn the skills of nature-watching at the same
time. Eleven schools in New York City are participating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we run and chase them?'' Mrs. Sanabria asked her students
on a chilly morning. They knew the answer was no. ``How do we have
to sit?'' she asked. One student, Edyth Florio, replied: ``Very,
very quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sanabria defined four courtship behaviors that the children
would be looking for: bowing, when the male bows and puffs out his
neck feathers; tailing, when he drags his tail feathers while
pursuing a female; driving, when he attempts to chase her; and
cooing, when the birds make sounds of approval.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing these behaviors, Mrs. Sanabria left out anything
that could kick a class from a PG to an X rating. Even so, the
students know enough to make accurate observations, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've seen eggs laid here, and the hermit crabs have had
babies,'' she said inside her classroom, which has a flock of
finches and a tank of crabs. ``It's sort of like they know about
the basics, as far as 8-year-olds should know about the basics.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some students noted that the birds were ``getting it
on,'' a term that was not on their clipboards.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Rendano also used decidedly unscientific terms to describe
what she had observed: ``We saw two in love, then the girl flew
away.''
</P>
<P>
   One student, Granville Gittens, remained engaged in the study
even after a pigeon relieved itself on his coat. ``I didn't know
who did it,'' he said. ``It was natural. I'm surprised it doesn't
happen all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview from Ithaca, Fitzpatrick said that instead of
reading books, answering questions at the end of chapters and
running experiments with predictable results, PigeonWatch students
were forging into the unknown, with the help of a most familiar
bird. The multiyear project is financed by the National Science
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What science is, in its basic form, is solving the mysteries
of nature, and what we want kids to do is see how fun it is to
solve these mysteries,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
