<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-CHANCELLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY BOARD OF EDUCATION SELECTS INTERIM CHANCELLOR 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Board of Education defied Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani on Sunday by rejecting his candidate for interim
schools chancellor and choosing Harold Levy, a banking executive
and member of the state Board of Regents, for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Levy's appointment is not yet assured, because he lacks formal
credentials as a school administrator and must receive a waiver
from Richard P. Mills, the state education commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The board voted, 4-3, Sunday to request the waiver, and Mills
said through a spokesman that he would decide quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani said after the vote that Levy was not qualified for
the job and complained that the teachers' union had pressured board
members to appoint him. The mayor said his candidate, Robert Kiley,
executive director of the New York City Partnership and a former
chairman of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, was much
better equipped to run the nation's largest school system because
he had more managerial experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have selected the least qualified of the two,'' Giuliani
told reporters at City Hall. ``I have to say to myself, there must
be some other influence involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy, 47, is director of global compliance for Citigroup and has
served on several commissions studying the condition of school
buildings in New York City, including one that issued a scathing
report on the deteriorating conditions of city schools in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic majority in the state Assembly appointed him to
the state Board of Regents in 1997, and he has used that platform
to push for more state aid for city schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education's surprise decision to support Levy came
at the end of a week fraught with political tension as the seven
board members scrambled to find a temporary replacement for Rudy
Crew, whom the board ousted as chancellor just two weeks ago, and
as mayoral allies pressured them to choose a candidate acceptable
to Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly, Terri Thomson, who sided with the mayor's
three allies on the board in voting against Crew last month, cast
her vote for Levy on Sunday, saying that he could do a better job
of carrying out Crew's policies than Kiley.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, she said, Levy could help the board carry out its
ambitious plan to end the automatic promotion of failing students.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the strong business management background as well as
the educational background, serving as a New York State Regent,''
she said. ``I made my decision based on what I think is right for
the kids.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
