A1277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-NYT     01-09 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SENSATION' EXHIBITION CLOSES AS IT OPENED, TO APPLAUSE AND
CONDEMNATION
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It ended much as it began, with long lines out the
doors and Catholic protesters praying on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sensation,'' an exhibition of contemporary British art culled
from the collection of the advertising magnate Charles Saatchi,
concluded its tumultuous three-month run Sunday at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope with our prayers we may send this picture back to hell
whence it came,'' called out one protester, Michael Mangan,
referring to ``The Holy Virgin Mary,'' the Chris Ofili painting
that prompted Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to try to cut off city
financing to the museum in September.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and several Catholic leaders, including Cardinal John
O'Connor, denounced the Ofili painting as blasphemous for depicting
the Madonna with a breast fashioned from elephant dung and with a
halo of close-ups snipped from pornographic magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also condemned as ``sick stuff'' several other works in
``Sensation,'' particularly the dissected corpses of cows and pigs,
a specialty of the British artist Damien Hirst.
</P>
<P>
   But under tight security Sunday, thousands of New Yorkers again
ignored Giuliani's imprecations, packing the exhibition halls for a
last glimpse at a show that resulted in an important First
Amendment victory for the museum, but that also raised questions
about the symbiotic financial relationships between museums and
wealthy private collectors like Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Williams, a spokeswoman for the museum, estimated that as
many as 180,000 people had seen ``Sensation'' in New York, although
she said the museum would have to sort through group ticket sales
before arriving at an exact figure.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although the attendance far exceeded the museum's internal
estimates before the opening of ``Sensation,'' it did not come
close to matching the 250,000 people who attended a recent Monet
exhibition at the museum. On the other hand, Impressionist
paintings tend to draw larger crowds than contemporary art, Ms.
Williams said, and museum officials were especially pleased by the
diverse and youthful demographics of the ``Sensation'' audience.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Art is freedom,'' said Ivaylo Gueorgiev, one of hundreds of
people in their 20s who waited patiently in line Sunday. Gueorgiev,
an artist from Manhattan who had never before visited the Brooklyn
Museum, is exactly the sort of patron that the museum's director,
Arnold L. Lehman, said he had hoped to attract with ``Sensation.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is evidence that some of those new visitors intend to
return; the museum, which has suffered from low attendance in
recent years, sold thousands of new memberships during
``Sensation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I joined the day that it opened,'' Peter S. Hogness, 44, a
writer and editor of a public health newsletter, said Sunday. ``But
part of that was I felt like, `Hey, that's my museum. Mayor, take
your hands off of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Weeks after Giuliani cut financing to the museum, Judge Nina
Gershon of U.S. District Court in Brooklyn ruled that his actions
were a flagrant violation of the museum's rights under the First
Amendment. She ordered the mayor to restore city payments and end
his effort to evict the museum from its city-owned building
overlooking Prospect Park. The city's appeal is scheduled to be
heard Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the legal victory and healthy attendance,
``Sensation'' also exacted a price. It bitterly divided New York
City's cultural institutions, with some signing a letter of protest
to Giuliani and others declining. It also raised questions about
the conflicts of interest museum professionals often face in
financing expensive exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   To help pay for ``Sensation,'' Lehman solicited hundreds of
thousands of dollars from individuals and companies that have a
direct commercial stake in the ``Sensation'' art. He also concealed
Saatchi's $160,000 donation from the public while giving him a
central role in shaping the show's artistic content.
</P>
<P>
   And while the attention on ``Sensation'' may or may not increase
the value of Saatchi's collection, the museum has also promised him
a refund of $60,000 if the show is a financial success. Ms.
Williams said Sunday that she did not know whether the museum had
made or lost money with ``Sensation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Newspaper accounts of these and similar arrangements at other
major museums helped prompt the Association of Art Museum
Directors, which represents 170 museums in the United States,
Canada and Mexico, to review its professional guidelines on
exhibition finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnold Lehman, you're going to pay the price,'' Mangan, the
Catholic protester from Queens, shouted into a megaphone Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Lehman, Lehman's wife, watched Mangan from a distance.
Then she turned and looked at the line of people waiting to get
into the museum. The line stretched for more than 100 yards. Mrs.
Lehman smiled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 2311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
