<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CROSSING-REVIEW-NY     01-09 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CROSSING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GENERAL, THE RIVER, THE FAMOUS BOAT RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM McDONALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A&AMP;E and Columbia TriStar Television recreate George Washington's
crossing of the Delaware Monday night, and the first thing you
should know about the movie ``The Crossing'' is whether it has the
father of our country standing in his boat or sitting.
</P>
<P>
   This is no small matter. The moment is a hallowed one in the
American saga, after all, and in reimagining it the difference
between standing and sitting is the difference between myth and
history. It's the difference between the iconography of the
19th-century artist Emanuel Leutze, who gave us the famously
fanciful image of Washington standing resolutely and a bit
precariously at the prow, and the scholarship of 20th-century
historians who have tried to paint a truer picture of Washington as
``a fallible human being made of flesh and blood and spirit _ not a
statue of marble and wood,'' as the biographer James Thomas Flexner
put it.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two camps, the one in which this movie falls is made
pretty clear long before it gets to the title scene; and when it
does, the treatment is happily restrained. In the dead of night,
launching a desperate expedition to surprise a Hessian garrison in
Trenton on Christmas Day 1776 and salvage the Revolution in its
darkest hour, Washington, played implacably by Jeff Daniels, climbs
into his boat and, for the rest of trip, sits. Ramrod straight, to
be sure, but he sits.
</P>
<P>
   That still leaves the question of how to breath life into him,
statue or not. And the film, directed by Robert Harmon (who also
directed ``Gotti''), would seem as if it should be up to the
challenge, for this is an intelligent, handsome and sometimes
bracing production. But try as it might to chip away at the marble
image of Washington, it only scratches the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels is a likable actor, probably no more so than when he
enlists his hangdog look in the service of deadpan, goofball
comedy, as he did as the smarter half of ``Dumb and Dumber.'' (Or
was he the other one?) There was also something agreeable about him
in his rousing turn as Col. Joshua Chamberlain in the Civil War
epic ``Gettysburg.''
</P>
<P>
   But in ``The Crossing,'' whatever anguish this Washington is
going through _ and we're asked to believe it's considerable _ is
more hinted at than shown. Daniels offers a sympathetic portrait,
but his expression generally remains as impenetrable as the one on
the dollar bill.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Fast, who wrote the novel on which the film is based, may
have understood the problem of Washington as leading man when he
decided to tell the story as much through the colorful figure of
Col. John Glover. He was the flinty commander of the Marblehead
Fishermen, the Massachusetts unit that piloted the boats across the
Delaware. And here, cast in the part, Sebastian Roche is suitably
scrappy. Indeed, the supporting players are the most convincing, in
particular John Henry Canavan as Gen. Henry Knox, a withering
skeptic on the American side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your troops always go in one direction,'' he haughtily tells
Washington at an officers' dinner. ``To attack requires the other
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is built, of course, on a foregone conclusion, but it
manages to maintain tension to such a degree that you begin to
wonder if Washington really will pull off what the history books
say happened. And the crossing itself is vividly depicted and
evocatively photographed _ the boats ferrying their huddled cargo
cut across the screen in silhouette through a blue mist _ without
the patriotic bombast that a schmaltzier film would drum up.
</P>
<P>
   The scene's understatement underlines the movie's faithfulness
to the facts. Minimizing the sort of expository dialogue common to
historical dramas, the film quickly sketches the Continental Army's
predicament. Defeated by the British at every turn, Washington's
army of 20,000 has been reduced to fewer than 2,000 and driven from
New York into Pennsylvania. Food, clothing and munitions are just
about gone. The men are freezing. The Continental Congress is
threatening to cut off money.
</P>
<P>
   Washington decides to go for broke and attack and turn the tide.
A man of stone? Not likely. In the end, it is in his boldness and
resolve, amply displayed here, that the truest picture of the man
emerges, even if the inner fire isn't visible on the screen.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CROSSING' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Monday night at 8 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rick Rosenberg and Bob Christiansen, executive producers; Robert
Harmon, director; David Coatsworth, producer; written by Howard
Fast based on his novel. An A&AMP;E Network and Columbia TriStar
Television production in association with Chris/Rose Productions.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jeff Daniels (Gen. George Washington), Roger Rees (Gen.
Hugh Mercer), Sebastian Roche (Col. John Glover), Steven McCarthy
(Capt. Alexander Hamilton), John Henry Canavan (Gen. Henry Knox)
and Ned Vukovic (Gen. William Stirling). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
