<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PHILLIPS-COLLECTION-N     01-09 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLIPS-COLLECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: THE MAN WHO HELPED MODERNISM TAKE ROOT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One way to ease happily into the new era is to
peruse ``Renoir to Rothko: The Eye of Duncan Phillips,'' a survey
of art mostly from the past century. The Phillips Collection, the
country's first museum of modern art, on the corner of 21st and Q
Streets here, is paying its founder lavish posthumous tribute with
this museumwide exhibition of 350 works, which remains on view
through Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Hurry, before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone who loves modern art already knows at least
something about the beloved Phillips Collection, but the show comes
at a useful moment, reminding people of Phillips' contribution at a
time when ``Sensation'' at the Brooklyn Museum of Art reignited the
usual antagonisms toward collectors of new art. Charles Saatchi's
extravaganza encouraged the suspicion that contemporary art
collecting is just a form of insider trading buoyed by hype, which
it can be, of course. But ``Renoir to Rothko'' nicely modifies this
perception by stressing that our national cultural heritage also
depends on rare patrons like Phillips (1886-1966). His evangelical
involvement with new art during the first half of the 20th century,
combined with his generosity, created what has become through
several generations an indispensable American institution.
</P>
<P>
   It has been indispensable partly because it has remained
intimate. Intimacy is an increasingly rare commodity in this age of
expanding museums and megacrowds, but even after a few expansions
of its own the Phillips Collection has managed to retain the
ambience of a home, which it was when Phillips founded it in 1921
in several rooms of the neo-Georgian pile where he grew up.
``Instead of the academic grandeur of marble halls and stairways
and miles of chairless spaces, with low standards and popular
attractions to draw the crowds,'' he wrote, ``we plan to try the
effect of domestic architecture, of rooms small or at least
livable.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of us are fortunate enough to live in places the size of
Phillips' house, so small and livable are relative terms. But the
idea of spaces at least cozier than most museum galleries was
crucial to the notion of a museum that would be a ``joy-giving,
life-enhancing influence, assisting people to see beautifully as
true artists see'': the sort of phrase that sounds fatuous coming
from other culturati but in Phillips' case has the ring of truth.
</P>
<P>
   Art was truly joy-giving to Phillips, or, to be precise, the art
he loved was joyous, meaning that he embraced painters like Renoir,
Cezanne, Matisse and Bonnard (at a time when Bonnard was
unfashionable, by the way), and he kept a distance from artists
whose works were dark, ironic, subversive or dry.
</P>
<P>
   Dada, Surrealism and Pop were out for him. So he didn't collect
Duchamp or Warhol, although it happened that Duchamp arranged the
donation to Phillips of works by Mondrian and Kandinsky that were
part of the legacy of the great American modern art collector
Katherine Dreier, and Phillips did want one work by Duchamp that
ended up going to the Museum of Modern Art. Reflecting both his
inclination toward pleasure over anxiety and the integrity of his
taste, Phillips also preferred Braque to Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   There is a difference, Phillips understood, between pleasure and
mindless amusement: Art can be both complicated and pleasing to
look at, as is the case with artists like Cezanne. Phillips was
clearly not looking for escapist entertainment when he bought
difficult pictures like Matisse's ``Studio, Quai St.-Michel.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was rejecting the idea that modern art had to be
rebarbative to be serious, a point that many young artists today,
looking to move beyond the preachifying and prickly styles of the
earlier 1990s in favor of more visual pleasure, would certainly
agree with. ``Renoir to Rothko'' is a timely show in that sense: It
dovetails with a gradual shift in contemporary art toward visual
satisfaction, however peculiarly expressed it may sometimes be.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which fills every corner of the rambling museum,
begins with Giorgione, El Greco, Chardin, Constable and Ingres,
historical soil from which sprung the modernists Phillips admired.
Born into old money, Yale educated, he clearly had enough social
standing and confidence not to worry about what other people
thought.
</P>
<P>
   He believed that modernism did not break definitively with the
past but was on a continuum that included American artists. So,
ignoring standard opinion, he not only bought underappreciated
Europeans like Bonnard but also embraced living Americans while
they were still considered provincial.
</P>
<P>
   As a result his collection rivaled Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney's
in terms of artists like Albert Pinkham Ryder, Rockwell Kent,
Arthur Dove, John Sloan, Charles Burchfield, John Marin, Arthur B.
Davies, Marsden Hartley and Stuart Davis, leading Americans of the
first half of the century who in turn established the historical
framework for later Americans in the collection like Mark Rothko,
Morris Graves and Richard Diebenkorn.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips established his own history of art. The essential
linking principles were classicism, lyricism, spirituality and
color. Spirituality connected Kandinsky and Klee with Georges
Rouault, Rothko and Graves. Classicism tied Chardin to Cezanne and
Cezanne to Matisse and Matisse to Diebenkorn. A quality of humane
decency also linked other artists, including painters like Joseph
Solman and Karl Knaths and Horace Pippin and Jacob Lawrence.
Phillips was the first major collector to endorse Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious throughout the exhibition that Phillips loved
painters who loved painting as much as he did. Craft, the finesse
of pigment on canvas, was the crux of art to him, and it was
irrelevant to him that his collection was not comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   The famous story is that as a young art critic seeing Matisse,
Cezanne and van Gogh for the first time at the 1913 Armory Show he
expressed total revulsion. His conversion to modernism and his
eventual endorsement of these artists therefore demonstrated a
gradual, independent and authentic evolution of thought.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' genius during the years immediately after the Armory
Show, the realization that still should mean the most to people who
look at new art, was to keep his eyes open. He belonged to the
extraordinary generation of American patron-missionaries that
included Dreier, Whitney, Abby Aldrich Rockefeller and Albert
Barnes. They established a foothold for modernist art. Phillips was
a prince among them.
</P>
<P>
   We are still learning to see through his eyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
