<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-EDITORIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS CAN'T BE OVERLOOKED; MCCAIN RAISES DOUBTS BUT NOT FATAL
ONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For months, conventional-thinking campaign theorists
have wondered when _ not if _ the laws of presidential-aspirant
averages would fall on John McCain's head.
</P>
<P>
   They wondered when his delirious spate of ``positive'' profiles
churned by the national media would turn a corner and ``go
negative,'' as they say in the biz. It always does, they say.
</P>
<P>
   They wondered when the famous temper would do him in. Or when
the inevitability of George W. Bush's $70 million would cause
reality to set in and bring McCain's giddy ride to an end.
</P>
<P>
   They're still waiting. In the meantime, though, the Arizona
senator's presidential aspirations have hit a serious bump that's
arisen from a seemingly unlikely source: questionable campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's most ardent _ indeed, most righteous _ advocate for
campaign finance reform now must defend himself against charges of
having browbeaten a federal agency on behalf of corporations whose
employees gave thousands of dollars to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Among the evidence surfacing against McCain are letters he wrote
as chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee to the Federal
Communications Commission arguing for action on a case involving
Paxson Communications Corp., whose president, Lowell Paxson, is a
major donor to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Also under scrutiny now are McCain's actions on behalf of some
of the regional ``Bell'' telephone companies, whose employees were
among the senator's top contributors for his 1998 re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has deemed his conduct ``entirely appropriate,'' and
contends he was just trying to prod into action one of Washington's
most notoriously pokey bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's semi-religious advocacy for reform of campaign
finance has made it inevitable that such actions would be weighed
against such contributions. John McCain has created an expectation
that his standards should be higher than those of others.
</P>
<P>
   The people raising the ugly spectre of the Charles Keating
Affair are not entirely off the mark. McCain was the least culpable
of the five senators. But his family flew in Charlie Keating's
plane to Charlie Keating's island after he took Charlie Keating's
campaign money. Now he is under the gun for using the corporate
jets of campaign contributors after arguing their cases before
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Even the comments from the FCC bureaucrats are reminiscent of
the Keating mess. Despite McCain's insistence that he was
interested only in prodding the process to a conclusion, FCC
officials told the ``Boston Globe'' last week that they got the
chairman's message and acceded to Paxson's wishes. Federal Home
Loan Bank Board officials expressed a similar sense of intimidation
to the Senate Ethics Committee in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Even McCain's reaction to this electoral crisis - throwing open
his correspondence files for all to see - is reminiscent of his
extraordinary Keating-era press conference at which he vowed to
respond to reporters' questions till they ran dry.
</P>
<P>
   That given, this is not Keating Redux. It is, in fact, McCain's
duty as chairman of the Commerce Committee to occasionally kick
agency butt. The FCC had delayed the Paxson decision for more than
700 days. And, in all, it received more than 25,000 letters from
members of Congress over the past three years, many no doubt
sternly worded.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the broader question of whether it is reasonable
to hold McCain to some mystical higher standard of ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions affecting virtually all of American industry are
weighed before McCain's Commerce Committee. It was inevitable that
determined researchers would unearth evidence of ``hypocrisy'' by
McCain, known in some circles as ``Senator Sanctimony.'' Left
untilled, however, is evidence of McCain actions and decisions that
run contrary to the wishes of his campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain's life, public and military, is one marked by
astonishing resiliency. In view of what has come before, it is hard
to envision this event _ by itself _ as the one that done him in. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
