<HEADER>
A1289 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-AIRPORT-CLOSED-KAN &LR;      01-09 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-CLOSED-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARDS-GEBAUR STANDS AS MONUMENT TO COLD WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At Richards-Gebaur Memorial Airport stands a
reasonable facsimile of a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps four stories tall, the massive cube of concrete was
Kansas City's version of Cheyenne Mountain, the Colorado Springs
headquarters of the North American Aerospace Defense Command, or
NORAD. Full of computer equipment, the structure housed the early
warning systems for much of the United States and Canada during the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Today the building houses BTM Inc., or Belton Tool and Machine,
a manufacturing business.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains a relic from the Cold War of what once was
Richards-Gebaur Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:59 p.m. Sunday, Richards-Gebaur closed as an airport. It
is to become an intermodal freight hub, where the Kansas City
Southern Railway will transfer cargo between trains and trucks for
shipment elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The airport and surrounding property, however, will always
represent a monument to the tension between the Soviet Union and
the United States in the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cold War was the only reason for the base being there,''
said Dick McMahon, an Air Force veteran who flew out of the base
for years and was the Air Force's civilian airfield manager there
from 1984 through 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, the year after the Cuban Missile crisis, the base was
home to 3,500 active duty military personnel. About 800 civilians
also worked there.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way.
</P>
<P>
   When Kansas City began buying land on the site in the early
1940s, the original idea was to build an auxiliary municipal
airport. It was there, in 1951, that many commercial airliners came
to land after the Downtown Airport was closed during that year's
ruinous flood.
</P>
<P>
   Given the times, however, military needs generally dictated.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1944, the Army air force began using what was then
known as Grandview Airport. But the fate of the site changed after
the summer of 1950, when North Korean troops crossed the 38th
parallel and invaded South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Some six months later, the Air Force announced plans to
establish the Central Air Defense at the airfield. The growth of
Soviet long-range aviation in the late 1940s, along with the test
of a Soviet atomic device in 1949, united Canada and the United
States under the threat of nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest officers of the Kansas City command, which then
served as the eyes and ears for about 20 states, worked from a
downtown office building.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1954, the command had moved to the airfield and added a
unit of fighter jet pilots trained in rapid deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Soon surrounding residents learned about sonic booms. The threat
of foreign attack and the need for jet interceptor aircraft that
could achieve supersonic speed was still a novelty to many.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Stuart Symington of Missouri, during a November 1955
ceremony dedicating the airfield as a permanent Air Force base,
sought to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer is it the musket over the fireplace,'' said
Symington, a former Air Force secretary. ``Rather it is the roar of
the modern jet which symbolizes our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1957 the field received its current name, in honor of two
area pilots who died in combat _ one in World War I, the other
during the Korean War. About 600 units of nearby base housing were
completed by 1960.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961 the base began flying the Canadian flag, in observance
of those members of the Canadian military who helped staff the
local NORAD contingent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Richards-Gebaur wasn't all dedicated to early warning and
fighter interceptors. Many associate the base with the long history
of the 442nd, a reserve troop carrier wing which for years operated
out of the base.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961 President John F. Kennedy activated the 442nd, calling
approximately 1,500 members to regular duty. The act was
precipitated by the construction of the Berlin Wall, which
prevented residents of Communist East Berlin from fleeing to the
western part of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The 442nd, many of its members from the Kansas City area, spent
much of the next 10 months ferrying men and equipment. At
demobilization ceremonies the following August, an officer told the
442nd that its active service had ``vastly increased our deterrent
power in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   And though they served half a world away from Berlin, the 442nd
still suffered losses. Seven men died in the December 1961 crash of
a C-124 Globemaster, a troop and cargo carrier which experienced
engine trouble soon after taking off from Richards-Gebaur.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Grubaugh of Ozark, Mo., who commanded the seven men and
visited family members that night, still considers the men Cold War
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those men were very special,'' said Grubaugh. ``I still feel
they are part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorial bearing the names of the seven stands at
Richards-Gebaur. For several years the 442nd Air Force Reserve
Association has organized a ceremony remembering them; the most
recent was held last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll keep doing this until no more of us are left,'' said Joe
Blair, association president.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the base's history, the military prided itself on
being a good neighbor to the nearby civilian communities. The
Richards-Gebaur Base Community Council formed in 1960 with members
from many surrounding cities.
</P>
<P>
   Another act of civilian outreach was the organization of air
shows, which continued into the 1990s. The first air shows date to
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Once the federal government began its gradual pullout from the
property, Kansas City tried to return to its original idea of
operating an auxiliary municipal airport. However, in recent years
the city lost an estimated $1.3 million annually doing so, and city
leaders soon grew enamored of the idea of a freight hub at the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Last August Kansas City voters approved the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, some area residents with longtime ties to the
base are defiant in regard to the pending change in the facility's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, opponents of the freight hub went to federal
court in an attempt to stop the project.
</P>
<P>
   The intermodal facility won't chase out the Richards-Gebaur
Composite Squadron of the Civil Air Patrol. Chartered in 1964, the
squadron has spent most of its years on the base. Despite the
apparent transition of Richards-Gebaur from airport to freight hub,
its members will continue to meet in a building near the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be keeping the name,'' said Gary Gregory, squadron
commander. ``We will not let it die.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether the site should retain its current names is
questionable for relatives of Lt. Col. Arthur W. Gebaur, a pilot
who died during the Korean War. That's especially so if the
facility becomes a freight hub.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine why they would want to leave the name on that
facility,'' said Linda Manichia, a Kansas City niece of Gebaur.
``My family feels that would be inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Gebaur and Lt. John F. Richards, she said, ``were
aviators and war heroes. That really doesn't correspond with a
train-truck hub.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-00 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000109.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-09 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1290 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-STATE-BUDGETS-KAN &LR;      01-09 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-BUDGETS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALE OF TWO BUDGETS: KANSAS, MISSOURI FACE SEPARATE REALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK AND WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Out in front of business executive Barry
Seward's home, State Line Road resembles any busy metropolitan
thoroughfare.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant suburban houses dot both sides of the street.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, which side of the street those houses stand on is
significant, the result of goings-on at the Missouri and Kansas
state Capitols.
</P>
<P>
   It's an issue of money in your pocket, an example of how things
can operate so differently in adjacent states.
</P>
<P>
   Seward lives and works east of State Line, in Missouri. He can
expect a special tax refund from the state this year, thanks to the
Hancock Amendment. He may also benefit from proposed new tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   If he lived and worked west of State Line, in Kansas, he could
forget about treats. No special tax refund. No new tax cuts either.
Kansas will reduce planned spending and consider a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   What in the name of politics is going on here?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Missouri phenomenon,'' said Seward, who lives near
Rockhurst High School and follows the vagaries of state government
in his job with a health-care company.
</P>
<P>
   One such phenomenon is the Hancock Amendment, approved by voters
in 1980, which requires refunds to Missouri taxpayers if government
revenue grows too fast. Kansas has no such law.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the economy in both states has performed well. Seward,
despite his knowledge of government, can't fully explain the
financial variations across State Line Road. He's hardly alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``How the heck can they be out of money?'' asked Missouri Rep.
Tom Hoppe, a Kansas City Democrat whose district borders Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Kansas share the same question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are befuddled,'' said Kansas Rep. David Adkins of
Leawood, chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, whose
district borders Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   His nutshell response: ``The Legislature has not exercised
sufficient discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   A fuller explanation begins in the 1990s, when the economy in
both states boomed. Missouri basked in an unprecedented wave of
prosperity for six years. Kansas saw tax money flow in beyond all
predictions.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri expects $6.9 billion of general revenue for the year
ending June 30, up from $4.4 billion in 1993. Kansas expects $4.2
billion, up from $2.9 billion in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   With so much money available, legislators and governors of both
states distributed the riches. State programs won more dollars. Tax
cut after tax cut won approval.
</P>
<P>
   There, Kansas and Missouri diverged.
</P>
<P>
   In Jefferson City, Mo., state government prosperity continues.
</P>
<P>
   Tax reductions totaling $650 million have been approved for
three consecutive years. Last year, Missouri taxpayers received a
$200 million tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock Amendment refunds totaled $874 million the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the good times stem from growth in the stock market,
said Mark Ward, state budget director. Capital gains revenue for
the state doubled in one year, he said. Unemployment is at a record
low.
</P>
<P>
   Excess revenue remains. A $98 million Hancock Amendment refund
is planned for late this year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some lawmakers are pushing for a new tax cut. Numerous
bills already have been filed by Democrats and Republicans alike to
trim property, income and other taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In Topeka, Kan., state government finds itself in a bind.
</P>
<P>
   The state budget has been soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on programs financed by general tax revenue jumped 7.4
percent in 1998 and 10.5 percent in 1999. Under the original budget
for this year, spending would have risen an additional 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the economy, though still healthy and growing moderately,
isn't booming like a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Projections of future state tax revenue proved overly
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Tax reductions will leave residents and businesses with roughly
$600 million more than they otherwise would have had this year.
That's money no longer available to the state budget. Also, the
reductions returned a little more money to taxpayers than
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   By the summer of 1999, it was clear that trouble lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're spending more than we're taking in,'' said budget
director Duane Goossen.
</P>
<P>
   Without action, a year-end reserve fund, which needs to be at
least $300 million to keep the budget operating smoothly, wouldn't
be large enough, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state doesn't face catastrophe. Spending this year still may
exceed last year's.
</P>
<P>
   But budget reductions will top the agenda when the Legislature
convenes today. A few lawmakers have proposed tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   How all this happened sparks disagreement among legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Rep. Phill Kline, a Shawnee, Kan., Republican who was a
leading advocate of tax cuts in the 1990s: ``The revenue
projections were off.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Senate President Dick Bond of Overland Park, Kan., a
moderate Republican: ``We cut taxes too much.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Tim Huelskamp of Fowler, Kan., a leader of conservative
Republicans: ``Some legislators and bureaucrats have been blaming
tax cuts for the state's fiscal difficulties. The real culprit,
though, is the enormous spending increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Missouri, legislators want to avoid the same pitfalls.
Warnings about the good times slowing down can be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope,'' said Senate President Pro Tem Ed Quick of Liberty,
Mo., ``we don't put ourselves in the same position as Kansas.''
 &LR; tag1:To reach John A. Dvorak, who covers Kansas government and
politics, call {(816) 234-7743} or send e-mail to
{jdvorak &LR; kcstar.com}
 &LR; tag1:To reach Will Sentell, Jefferson City correspondent, call
(573) 634-3565.
</P>
</TEXT>
